\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b \uc2 APEC\uc2  CLOCKS ROBUST GROWTH IN FIRST QUARTER\b0\par\par\uc2 814 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 August 2021\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Yuni Arisandy Sinaga\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - The \uc2 APEC\uc2  region recorded an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 6.1 percent in the first quarter of 2021, bouncing back strongly from a two-percent decline in 2020 Q1, the APEC \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Support Unit\u8217\'20\'19s updated report stated.\par \par \uc2 The number securely places the region on course to meet the year\u8217\'20\'19s growth expectations, currently estimated at 6.4 percent, or slightly higher than the earlier forecast, according to a written statement issued by the APEC \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Support Unit and received here on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 High growth in the \uc2 APEC\uc2  region in the first quarter of 2021 is attributed to a plethora of factors, comprising the low comparison point following substantial \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  contraction a year ago as well as higher government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on account of the sustained impact of the pandemic on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities, while domestic consumption grew considerably during the period.\par \par \uc2 In the near term, the APEC \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Support Unit still sees sustained \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures from governments driving the region\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 Private consumption will also receive a boost of confidence, as consumers are expected to draw on their accumulated savings, bolstered in part due to cash transfers and wide-ranging \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  to households.\par \par \uc2 "Vaccination programs and rollout still drive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and the recovery progress in the region," according to Denis Hew, Director of the APEC \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Support Unit.\par \par \uc2 "We are still seeing a disparity in access to vaccination coverage across \uc2 APEC\uc2 . Thus, economies with faster rollouts and sustained \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  support will recover faster and stronger, while economies that struggle with vaccine access and have limited \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  space will take more time to recover due to these \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Hew pointed out.\par \par \uc2 Vaccination coverage across \uc2 APEC\uc2  is noticeably diverse, ranging from 148 doses per 100 residents to a low of only one dose per 100 residents. Consequently, the rate of fully vaccinated people across economies varies significantly, from as low as 0.2 percent to as high as 72 percent of the population as of mid-August.\par \par \uc2 "The race to vaccinate as many people as possible in the shortest period of time is extremely crucial," according to Rhea C. Hernando, an APEC \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Support Unit researcher, who updated the report.\par \par \uc2 "Economies cannot afford to continue to impose restrictions, close borders, and indefinitely provide wide-ranging \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary support," she stated.\par \par \uc2 Hernando believes multilateral cooperation is the key to facilitating the free flow of vaccine components and related supplies, as it will contribute significantly to the accessibility and affordability of vaccines, especially for low- and middle-income economies.\par \par \uc2 "It is now clear that for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery to be on firmer footing, health must be safeguarded, which in turn necessitates access to vaccines to protect as many people as possible, as soon as possible," she affirmed.\par \par \uc2 In terms of trade, the region performed positively in the first quarter of 2021, with the value of merchandise exports and imports growing at a higher rate of 16.8 percent and 16.2 percent, respectively, from a contraction of 6.1 percent for exports and 4.1 percent for imports during the corresponding period last year.\par \par \uc2 This improved performance is brought about mainly by pharmaceuticals and office and communications equipment, while the agrifood, apparel, metals and minerals sectors also added to the trade boost.\par \par \uc2 The unfaltering impact of COVID-19 on the transport and travel sectors continues to drag \uc2 APEC\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s commercial services performance.\par \par \uc2 For the January-March 2021 period, commercial services declined further to 12 percent for exports and 15.2 percent for imports, as compared to a decline of 9.5 percent for exports and 9.2 percent for imports for the corresponding period in 2020.\par \par \uc2 The updated report also indicated an increase in inflation during the first half of 2021 to 2.3 percent, as compared to 1.6 percent in the first half of 2020 on account of the gradual normalization of prices.\par \par \uc2 Inflation is expected to revert to its pre-pandemic levels globally once prices factor in pandemic-related supply-side disruptions.\par \par \uc2 The whole-year forecast of inflation for the \uc2 APEC\uc2  region is two percent, while it could increase to 2.2 percent in 2022.\par \par \uc2 There is a risk that the upward trend in inflation could persist, as consumption activity strengthens following successive quarters of pent-up demand. The report notes that price pressures require continued monitoring and clear communication from monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  authorities to guide inflation expectations.\par \par \uc2 "Addressing the ongoing health crisis, primarily through rapid vaccination rollouts even as appropriate health measures continue to be observed, remains paramount to strengthening \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery," Hernando affirmed.\par \par \uc2 "When people feel safe, they are more confident to go out, work, and spend accumulated savings while business could resume investment activity, supporting a gradual but uninterrupted \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reopening toward a stronger recovery," she stated.\par \par \uc2 (T.Y012/A/R013/R013) 18-08-2021 18:40:51\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020210818eh8i0012x\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
