\par\par \b \uc2 BI holds  \highlight22\uc2 policy \highlight\uc2  rate at 3.5%, sets up MSME financing boost\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 422 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 August 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) \uc2 announced on Thursday that it would hold its benchmark interest rate at a record-low 3.5 percent, a stance intended to accommodate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recoveryin response to slow business activity duringthe ongoing second COVID-19 wave.\par \par \uc2 Following a two-day \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  meeting, the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  also held its benchmark deposit facility rate at 2.75 percent and lending facility rate at 4.25 percent.\par \par \uc2 "This decision is in line with the need to ensure stability in the rupiah exchange rate and the financial system, amid low inflation and efforts to boost \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth," said BI Governor \uc2 Perry Warjiyo\uc2  on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 BI is also set to introduce an inclusive macroprudential financing ratio (RPIM) \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  starting in September, which it hopes will improve financing for micro, small and medium enterprises (MSMEs) and related parties.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  maintained its 2021 forecast of GDP growth of between 3.5 and 4.3 percent and inflation of between 2 and 4 percent.\par \par \uc2 In July, the consumer price index (CPI) rose by 1.52 percent year-on-year (yoy), less than both the previous month and a year earlier, Statistics Indonesia (BPS) data show.\par \par \uc2 Perry added that the rupiah had depreciated 2.24 percent year-to-date (ytd) as of Aug. 18 but had appreciated 0.63 percent from last month, thanks to calmer global financial markets and improved investor confidence in the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which had led to higher foreign capital inflows.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's current account \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  remained at a narrow 0.36 percent of GDP in the January to March period. The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  estimates that the annual \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  will fall between 0.6 and 1.4 percent of GDP.\par \par \uc2 Perry described the RPIM \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as "MSME financing plus, plus" as it would allow more non-bank institutions or "agents" to channel loans to MSMEs, would enable more MSMEs to issue securities and would expand productive loan access to include individuals involved with MSMEs.\par \par \uc2 Economists at the University of Indonesia's Social and \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Research Institution (LPEM) said global developments related to the \uc2 Delta\uc2  variant outbreak and the decisions of the \uc2 United States Federal Reserve\uc2  would be key external factors driving market movements this year.\par \par \uc2 "Therefore, amid the high \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , we believe that BI needs to maintain its interest rate at 3.5 percent while maintaining the exchange rate and the financial sector's stability," they wrote in an analysis published on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210820eh8l00003\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Steam Power Plants Running on Fumes\b0\par\par\uc2 1,946 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 August 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 A WEEKEND virtual meeting held on August 7 was used by the Executive Director of the Indonesian Coal Mining Association (APBI) Hendra Sinadia to defend his organization\u8217\'20\'19s members. \u8220\'20\'1CPLN\u8217\'20\'19s coal needs planning must also be evaluated and remedied,\u8221\'20\'1D said Hendra, repeating his association\u8217\'20\'19s demand in that meeting, when speaking to Tempo on Tuesday, August 17.\par \par \uc2 That Saturday, Hendra was in a tight spot. The inviting party, Director-General of Minerals and Coal Ridwan Djamaluddin, had recently issued export bans to 34 coal companies. Four of those companies were APBI members. They were deemed to have not fulfilled their obligations as found in the contracts to supply coal to steam power plants (PLTUs) owned by state electricity company PLN for January-June.\par \par \uc2 That morning, before the meeting, Ridwan sent a letter about that export ban to the director-general of foreign trade at the trade ministry, director-general of customs at the finance ministry, and the director-general of sea transportation at the transportation ministry. It mentioned that the export ban could be lifted if the penalized companies had met the domestic coal needs according to the supply contracts.\par \par \uc2 Four APBI members, namely \uc2 Arutmin Indonesia\uc2 , Bara Tabang, Borneo Indobara, and Prima Multi Mineral, were on the list of companies accused of not fulfilling contracts. The letter included a copy of the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the basis for issuing that penalty: Energy and Mineral Resources Ministerial Decree No. 139.K/HK.02/MEM.B/2021 on meeting domestic coal demand.\par \par \uc2 As it turns out, amid a looming financial crisis resulting from an electrical supply surplus which has been building up due to decreased demand for electricity during the Covid-19 pandemic, PLN has also experienced a coal supply shortage. The national electricity system is highly dependent on PLTUs. Over half of the total installed capacity of 72,899 megawatts consists of coal-fired power plants. Most of the PLTUs are owned by PLN, with a total capacity of 32,924 megawatts.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 THE coal supply issues which led to export bans for those mining companies began with a letter from PLN dated August 4. At that time, PLN proposed an additional supply of coal for the August-December period for PLTUs managed by the company, including its subsidiaries. This letter also mentioned that 34 coal-mining companies had defaulted on their supply contracts for January-July.\par \par \uc2 Actually, there had been a lengthy discussion about this fuel crisis experienced by PLTUs owned by the PLN Group with the energy and mineral resources ministry. Since December 2020, the coal supply to PLN had dwindled, always far below plan. In January, for instance, the volume of coal scheduled to be received should have been 5.25 million tons. However, in reality, only 4.12 million tons were supplied. Things were even worse last April, when PLN received just 5.74 million tons of coal from the initial plan of 7.08 million tons.\par \par \uc2 As a result, last May, seven PLTUs owned by PLN in the Java-Madura-Bali electricity system were on critical status, as their fuel supply was only enough for less than 10 days of operation. The Paiton 9 PLTU di Probolinggo, East Java, for example, only had enough stock for six days. Other power plants, such as the Labuhan Ratu PLTU, Labuan PLTU, and the Suralaya PLTU, had the same problem. In the first half of this year, PLN had received a supply of 53 million tons, less than half of the total planned need for 2021 of 113 million tons.\par \par \uc2 This problem is what led to a meeting between the energy ministry, PLN, and a number of partnered coal suppliers in Bali on June 18. At that time, PLN acquired commitments for additional supplies of over 4.6 million tons of coal for July-December. This is to come from old and new suppliers. \u8220\'20\'1CEfforts to seek additional (supply) continue to be made by PLN,\u8221\'20\'1D said Agung Pribadi, Head of the Bureau of Communication, \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Information Services, and Cooperation at the energy ministry, when announcing the signing of those agreements.\par \par \uc2 As it turned out, those commitments did not automatically increase the supply. Energy Minister Arifin Tasrif finally issued Decree No.139.K/ HK.02/MEM.B/2021. This new \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  includes an export ban penalty and fines for mining and transport companies which do not fulfill domestic market obligations (DMO) and supply contracts.\par \par \uc2 Hendra Sinadia did not want members of his association to be blamed in this manner. He claimed that APBI members had fulfilled the DMO above 25 percent, the level required by the government. On top of that, those four APBI members which were penalized faced different issues in honoring their contracts with PLN.\par \par \uc2 According to Hendra, shipments of coal supplies from APBI members often face limited ship availability, especially for shipments from Kalimantan to Java. Also, the amount of supplies prepared by some mining companies becomes \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  due to planning changes from PLN. \u8220\'20\'1CThe user also needs to make improvements, from infrastructure to procurement planning to be as accurate as possible,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Sudin Sudirman, Corporate Secretary for Golden Energy Mines, said the same thing. GEMS\u8212\'20\'14the stock code for Golden Energy Mines\u8212\'20\'14is the parent company of Borneo Indobara, one of the companies slapped with the export ban on account of this issue. According to Sudin, the shortage of coal stock has not occurred because of any mistake on the part of Borneo Indobara, but due to the lateness of ships from PLN.\par \par \uc2 A coal-hauling truck crosses a coal mine road in Tapin Regency, South Kalimantan, July 2021. Antara/Bayu Pratama S\par \par \uc2 On August 8, the export ban against Borneo Indobara was lifted after the company made up the supply shortage according to the contract for January-July, namely 19,000 tons. The company, Sudin explained, had finally sent 55,000 tons that Sunday, according to the available ship capacity. \u8220\'20\'1CThere was an additional commitment from Borneo Indobara to PLN for the July supply,\u8221\'20\'1D said Sudin. He also sent the penalty cancellation letter signed by the director-general of minerals and coal.\par \par \uc2 Zaenal Arifin Hasibuan, Chair for Organizational and Membership Affairs of the Indonesian National Shipowner\u8217\'20\'19s Association, verified the news that there are not enough barges to haul coal to PLN right now. The reason is the demand for shipping nickel from Sulawesi has increased. Shipping businesses prefer nickel shipping orders because the price is higher compared to delivering coal to the PLTUs as offered by PLN. \u8220\'20\'1CSo there is high shipping demand, but not enough ships,\u8221\'20\'1D said Zaenal.\par \par \uc2 On Friday, August 20, Director-General of Minerals and Coal Ridwan Djamaluddin sent another letter. This time it was addressed to the management of companies holding coal mining and shipping licenses. That letter noted that 575,000 tons of planned coal shipments to PLTUs owned by PLN failed to get barges. That much coal needs seven supramax vessels, five small handy ships, and 10 sets of 330-cubic-feet barges. All that was available was one ship and 22 barges.\par \par \uc2 In that letter, Ridwan asked those coal mining and shipping license holders to be willing to shift barges being used for domestic destinations\u8212\'20\'14in addition to being used for general purposes and export\u8212\'20\'14to be rented by PLN up until at least August 31. Even though that letter was seeking company willingness, it read like a veiled threat should the energy ministry was not given certainty for the shifting of barge services. \u8220\'20\'1CThe directorate-general of mineral and coal will coordinate with the related institutions to reduce the number of barges servicing exports,\u8221\'20\'1D read that letter signed by Ridwan. \u8220\'20\'1CSo that they can be used to ship coal to PLN Group\u8217\'20\'19s PLTUs.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 THE limited number of ships and barges is said to be just the tip of the iceberg of problems stemming from the poor commerce system to meet coal needs for PLN\u8217\'20\'19s PLTUs. The main problem has to do with price.\par \par \uc2 To date, the DMO price of coal for electricity generators is set at US$70 per ton. Meanwhile, the price of Indonesian coal in the international market can be less or more than the benchmark price. The disparity in coal prices is often the cause of not achieving the DMO target.\par \par \uc2 When the world prices skyrocket, mining entrepreneurs were suspected of prioritizing exports to make more money. The same thing is suspected to have happened at this time, when the reference coal price continued to climb from the start of the year up to US$130.99 per ton as of August.\par \par \uc2 While coal supplies for PLN\u8217\'20\'19s PLTUs are not enough, the export of coal goes on nearly unhampered. The directorate-general of mineral and coal\u8212\'20\'14through the Minerba One Data Indonesia alias Modi site\u8212\'20\'14recorded exports from January-June of 169.1 million tons, only 200,000 tons less compared to the same period last year.\par \par \uc2 Panjiva, the international trade data provider platform, recorded that at least eight of the 34 companies sanctioned for not fulfilling supply contracts with PLN were still actively trading outside Indonesia from January to May. Among those eight companies, Borneo Indobara was conducting the most trade, namely 8.2 million tons through 114 shipments. Those coal exports worth US$335 million mostly went to China, India, and South Korea.\par \par \uc2 At the end of last February, for instance, the MV Sea Honesty vessel was recorded arriving in Hosan, South Korea, carrying 88,000 tons of coal sent by Borneo Indobara from Satui Port in South Kalimantan. That coal shipment worth US$3.7 million was sent to Korea Southern Power Co Ltd (Kospo), a South Korean electricity company.\par \par \uc2 Kospo told the Korea Center for Investigative Journalism (KCIJ) Newstapa, Tempo\u8217\'20\'19s collaboration partner in South Korea, that they had no record of imports for February. Kospo only verified the information that to date their company has imported coal from Indonesia. The total amount from 2016-2020 came to 33.23 million tons. \u8220\'20\'1CTo lower power generation costs, we introduced coal from Indonesia, which has good \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  feasibility,\u8221\'20\'1D was Kospo\u8217\'20\'19s written reply to Kim Ji-yoon from KCIJ Newstapa. \u8220\'20\'1COn top of that, Samcheok Bitdream was designed as a power plant which uses low-calorie coal, and mostly uses Indonesian coal.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Golden Energy Mines Corporate Secretary Sudin Sudirman said that the market price is currently good. Sudin explained that the greater share of exports made by Borneo Indobara, which is a subsidiary of Golden Energy Mines, go to China and India. \u8220\'20\'1CAbout 60 percent,\u8221\'20\'1D said Sudin. Even so, he assured that Borneo Indobara has met the coal DMO at the 37 percent level in the second quarter of this year.\par \par \uc2 Dileep Srivastava, Director and Corporate Secretary of Bumi Resources (BUMI) expressed similar words. \u8220\'20\'1CWe have balanced exports which prioritize the domestic market, and have met the condition of 25 percent for DMO for July,\u8221\'20\'1D said Dileep, representing BUMI\u8217\'20\'19s subsidiary, \uc2 Arutmin Indonesia\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Singgih Widagdo, a commissioner at PLN Batubara, said that the domestic coal supply issue is not limited to the matter of volume. He considers there are many problems with the supply chain, upstream at the mines, downstream to generators. From the user side, alias PLN and PLN Batubara, he continued, the problems include long shipping times, the scale of coal PLTUs, and unloading time. \u8220\'20\'1CEverything is part of a supply chain which must be integrated,\u8221\'20\'1D said Singgih, who is also chairman of the Indonesian Mining and Energy Forum.\par \par \uc2 DEVY ERNIS, AISHA SHAIDRA, RETNO SULISTYOWATI, RAYMUNDUS RIKANG\par \par \uc2 Judith Neilson Institute\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/08/22/780605/780605_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/08/22/780606/780606_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/08/23/780651/780651_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020210823eh8n0000b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
