\par\par \b \uc2 Will the real energy transition begin from corporations?\b0\par\par\uc2 965 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 September 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Naufal Rospriandana and Rezky Khairun Zain , Jakarta/Canberra\par \par \uc2 The use of cleaner and sustainable energy sources has been trending under the global climate change mitigation agenda. Solar photovoltaics (PV) have shown rapid growth, especially in recent decades. Its global installed capacity increased from only 1.4 gigawatts (GW) in 2000 to 627 GW in 2019. China (204 GW), the United States (76 GW), Japan (63 GW), Germany (49 GW) and India (43 GW) are the five largest PV user countries.\par \par \uc2 Vietnam emerged as a regional leader in Southeast Asia by successfully achieving 7.5 GW in just three years. This significant development is followed by Thailand (3 GW) and Malaysia (1.2 GW). Developing countries, including most Asian countries, are expected to lead the future of PV deployment. The recent rapid expansion of PV capacity has resulted from dramatic declines in equipment cost and the local availability of abundant solar resources.\par \par \uc2 Spreading widely in the equatorial zone thus blessed with abundant solar irradiation throughout the year, Indonesia has a promising opportunity for PV development. However, the growth remains modest in the country, with only about 75 megawatts peak (MWp) utility-scale in operation. Although some proposed big projects are reportedly coming up (including the groundbreaking of the 145-MWp Cirata floating and Hijaunesia projects), not a significant number have materialized.\par \par \uc2 The protracted negotiation of power purchase agreements (PPA) between state electricity company PLN and project developers contributes significantly to the low PV uptake in Indonesia. Moreover, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown caused by COVID-19 and electricity oversupply has perpetuated the release of new capacity expansion and rendered the future development of renewables \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 However, with the increasingly competitive cost and growing consciousness about sustainability, the landscape of PV in Indonesia will slightly change and turn around. It is corporations, primarily commercial and industrial (C&I) users, that perhaps will take the lead in the real energy transition of the country.\par \par \uc2 In the markets, recently we all have witnessed how companies covering various sectors of daily goods, apparel, cement, mining, petrochemicals, fisheries, farming, etc., have launched their plans and projects to use PV in their factories. The capacity of each project varies from 1 MWp to around 20 MWp depending on the load and is typically for self use. The schemes can either use leasing or EPC (engineering, procurement and construction) contracts, but leasing is recently more attractive as it offers a more practical scheme to use cleaner energy with zero upfront investment.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, more than a few independent power producers (IPPs) have developed a new business strategy to tap the C&I-based PV opportunity, such as Medco, \uc2 Indika Energy\uc2 , Engie and \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  Power. It complements other emerging start-up companies like SUN, Xurya, LYS and BECIS Symbior.\par \par \uc2 It is not surprising that corporate actors were the fastest-growing demand for voluntary renewable energy (aside from power purchase from compliance market and retailers) from 2013 to 2019 in other advanced PV-user countries such as the US. IRENA (2018) reported that most companies that actively sourced renewable energy for self-use were headquartered in Europe and North America, followed by emerging markets on the rise. As more companies embark on the race toward sustainable energy sources, it is expected that voluntary renewable procurement will drive further development of renewables, including in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 We see three major factors that trigger the growth of C&I-based PV adoption in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 First is undeniably the energy cost competitiveness. Globally, it is observed that the PV price has declined over time, even becoming lower than the retail \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2 , known as hitting grid parity. This price decline has consequently impacted the growth of C&I-based PV. With the leasing-based corporate PPA model, the lower cost at around 10-15 percent over industrial electricity \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  through PV affects the cost efficiency to the corporates as end-user while also offering a practical scheme for them to use clean energy.\par \par \uc2 Second is pressure from headquarters and investors, especially for multinational corporations (MNCs) and/or stock exchange-listed companies. For MNCs, the HQ in their country of origin typically has set out sustainability policies and strategies to be implemented by their branch companies worldwide.\par \par \uc2 In Indonesia, as generally the electricity supply is served by PLN, in most cases, installing PV comes to be the solution as part of clean energy diversification, for example, in \uc2 Danone\uc2 , AEON and \uc2 Unilever\uc2  factories. Likewise, generally, by using PV, stock exchange-listed companies also benefit from the green branding, which later relates to implementing the environmental, social and governance (ESG) aspects and annual sustainability disclosures report.\par \par \uc2 The third is consumer pressure. In developed countries, green labeling that ensures the sustainable supply chain, including clean energy use, is a consideration for consumers when buying products. Green labeling perhaps has not been applied to Indonesian retail consumers due to low awareness. However, this might apply to those companies that export their products internationally. The existence of a clean energy use component in a company's production chain, for example, PV-cold storage for the fisheries sector, can increase the attractiveness of the export markets, especially those\par \par \uc2 that require this.\par \par \uc2 All the above indicate that a real clean energy transition in Indonesia is likely to be driven by corporates, especially amid the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  of utility-scale projects. Less complex bureaucracy and negotiation process while motivations are also there for C&I PV. It remains to be seen how this will go further. Stronger political will is needed to spur clean energy.\par \par \uc2 ____________________\par \par \uc2 Naufal Rospriandana is a cofounder of Forum Energi Muda and works for an infrastructure financing company. Rezky Khairun Zain is a freelance technical consultant in renewable energy and an MSc \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Environmental \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  student at the \uc2 Australian National University\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210905eh9600008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
