\par\par \b \uc2 Discourse: Robotics, AI will replace cheap labor, warns Korean ambassador\b0\par\par\uc2 1,080 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 September 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 The partnership between Indonesia and South Korea has lasted for decades in various fields, particularly with regard to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Outgoing Indonesian ambassador to South Korea Umar Hadi spoke with The Jakarta Post's Kornelius Purba about South Korea's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  trends and how Indonesia should prepare for future developments. The following are excerpts from the discussion.\par \par \uc2 Question: How has the COVID-19 pandemic changed South Korea's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ?\par \par \uc2 Answer: The pandemic has made the world unstable and has made old conflicts resurface. The fast-changing nature of the pandemic makes reliable predictions more difficult. Surrounded by \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , along with disruption, the pressure is getting stronger. Thus, we are living in an unstable world, embracing the age of chaos.\par \par \uc2 Emerging markets are adopting new technologies and renewable energy. Companies are trying to shrink supply chains and gradually change traditional manufacturing and industrial practices into the use of modern and smart technology. There is also a dire need for the utilization of big data and artificial intelligence (AI), as well as data accessibility through remote working.\par \par \uc2 The world has changed. If we don't change, we will be left behind. South Korea has adapted to this situation by announcing the Korean New Deal: National Strategy for a Great Transformation on July 14, 2020. This strategyplans to invest 160 trillion won [Rp 1.96 quadrillion] to create 1,901,000 jobs by 2025 based on two main policies - the Digital New Deal and the Green New Deal - and an overarching \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  support to strengthen employment and the social safety net.\par \par \uc2 How should Indonesia respond to the use of AI in industry?\par \par \uc2 AI is growing very rapidly in the US, China, Israel and South Korea. Recently it has reached a tipping point in every sector, including health care and industry. In the future, with system automation and AI, there will be no more development of the manufacturing industry. For example, during the production of masks, all the processes are carried out by robots. The Hyundai factory, which was built in Jakarta, also uses robots for its manufacturing process.\par \par \uc2 With robotic technology and AI, practically, there will be no longer any need for a cheap workforce since laborers will only be for maintenance and cleaning. The employees only work on installing screws on the dashboard and the company-bought exoskeleton technology so that those who work on screwing will not get tired.\par \par \uc2 How about Indonesia's traditional exports?\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's exports to Korea continue to experience a surplus of around US$1 billion to $2 billion annually. However, this is still largely in the commodity sector, such as coal and minerals, while exports in the manufacturing sector remain low. However, in the last two to three years there have been improvements in the performance of products such as plywood, iron, steel and processed food and beverages.\par \par \uc2 If you look at the export figures from Indonesia to Korea, it really depends on the price of coal. If coal prices are good like in 2013 and 2014, Indonesia's total exports to Korea could reach $25 billion. However, when coal prices plummeted in 2017, the total trade also fell to $15 billion. Since Indonesian export performance figures with South Korea depend on coal prices, when many countries are projected to become coal-free, Indonesia's export performance will drop.\par \par \uc2 How about the trends in investment from South Korea?\par \par \uc2 The most important way to support Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery post-COVID-19 is through research and development and also human resource development. The embassy is focusing on establishing partnerships with Korean companies that are part of the "future industry". Instead of focusing on the traditional manufacturing sector, foreign direct investment [FDI] began to shift toward new industries of renewable energy, semiconductors, petrochemicals, lithium batteries and electric vehicles.\par \par \uc2 Both countries moved from labor-intensive industries to more capital-intensive ones. The cooperation includes elements of sharing knowledge through joint research and development in a way that meets Indonesia's needs. FDI is not just creating jobs but creating jobs with higher salaries.\par \par \uc2 What should Indonesia do to enter the market in these areas?\par \par \uc2 As ambassador, I formed a new division, namely creative and digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Behind the globalization of the Korean Wave, there is a consumption of creative products in the Korean market itself. The South Korean market's appreciation for cultural and creative products is already very high.\par \par \uc2 However, of course, the process is not instant, but we are gradually exporting our creative products. For example, batik will now be available online on the Korean market. The agreement between a Korean e-commerce platform and an Indonesian batik company is a milestone in the trading relations of creative products between the two countries.\par \par \uc2 How has South Korean investment grown in Indonesia?\par \par \uc2 The first wave of Korean companies came to Indonesia back in the late 1960s and early 1970s. When Indonesia started to open up its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the late 60s and early 70s, companies from other countries came to Indonesia as big corporations. On the contrary, Korean companies that came to Indonesia were small and medium ones, especially in the garment sector. They were of the first generation, and I call them pioneers. Many of them stayed in Indonesia and had children in Indonesia. So that's why now I have met quite a number of young Koreans who were actually born in Indonesia. If you go to Ungaran, Central Java, you will find a village full of Korean garment factories. Because the owner has lived in Indonesia for a long time, he has expanded his business in Indonesia and loves staying there.\par \par \uc2 How has Indonesia contributed to peace in the Korean Peninsula?\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's role in the Korean Peninsula issue is crucial and part of history. Indonesia's fifth president [\uc2 Megawati Soekarnoputri\uc2 ] is seen as a reform figure who made South Korean reformers regard this as a plus. She was an interlocutor with North Korea, but now North Korea has changed, so it takes extra effort from Indonesia to reach out.\par \par \uc2 In the middle of an increasingly unstable world, many are concerned about the Korean Peninsula situation. There are many factors and situations that have to be considered. We may see the possibility of more guaranteed stability on the Korean Peninsula. Thanks to our long history with North Korea, Indonesia stands a good chance of being a peace mediator in the Korean Peninsula.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210908eh9900004\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
