\par\par \b \uc2 Consumer confidence plunges to lowest in 12 years\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 590 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 September 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Consumers, long the driving force behind Indonesia's emerging \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , have turned more pessimistic as a seemingly endless COVID-19 pandemic stokes fear about jobs and income.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's (BI) consumer confidence index fell to 77.3 in August, the lowest since at least 2012, according to BI data published Wednesday. Values below 100 signify pessimism while higher readings denote optimism.\par \par \uc2 The index had climbed into optimistic territory before the government tightened mobility restrictions in response to a surge in cases and deaths this summer, but the latest reading puts it even below the 77.8 seen in May 2020, just two months into the pandemic in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 "The \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  consumer survey for August indicates that consumer confidence about \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions remains under pressure, in line with the continuation of the mobility restrictions \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the survey period aimed at fighting the spread of the delta COVID-19 variant," BI spokesman Erwin Haryono was quoted in a press release as saying on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 The government has been gradually relaxing the restrictions as daily new COVID-19 cases and deaths have begun to decline, allowing shopping centers to reopen.\par \par \uc2 The further dip in the index was driven by negative \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  perceptions of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions, as reflected in the present situation subindex, which declined to 59.4 in August from 67.1 a month earlier.\par \par \uc2 The expectations subindex, meanwhile, improved to 95.3 in August from 93.2 in July. This index reflects people's assessments of income, business and employment opportunities with regard to the next six months.\par \par \uc2 Consumers earning between Rp 3.1 million (US$217) and Rp 4 million were the most pessimistic in the August survey, followed by those earning Rp 2.1 million to Rp 3 million. Consumers with income above Rp 5 million were the least pessimistic.\par \par \uc2 The decline in the present situation subindex was driven by significantly more pessimistic views on current income opportunities and job availability.\par \par \uc2 "It is reasonable that [the consumer confidence index] still declined despite some relaxation in [mobility restrictions] in August, as companies need some time to adjust their labor needs," Faisal Rachman, an economist at state-owned \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2  told The Jakarta Post in a text message on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 "Moreover, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  regarding COVID-19 going forward remains, so companies are not likely to open vacancies soon."\par \par \uc2 Employment was very slow to pick up despite some easing of mobility restrictions because businesses wanted to maximize the use of their furloughed workers rather than open new vacancies, said Shinta Widjaja Kamdani, deputy chairwoman of the Indonesian Employers Association (Apindo).\par \par \uc2 "This takes into account the slow recovery in demand in the market, which makes it risky for a company's financial stability to open vacancies too early," Shinta told the Post in a text message on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 BI also reported that the retail sales index was estimated to have contracted last month by 0.1 percent year-on-year (yoy), though that marks an improvement over the 2.9 percent annual contraction in July.\par \par \uc2 Alphonzus Widjaja, chairman of the Indonesian Shopping Center Association (APPBI), said improvement in the retail industry was expected to be a gradual process, since the government also eased the restrictions for shopping centers in a gradual manner.\par \par \uc2 "Based on last year's experience, visitor numbers tend to [pick up] slowly and gradually, but the important thing is that there is an improvement," Aphonzus told the Post in a phone interview on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210909eh9a00001\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
