\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Banking industry fundamentally in good shape amid challenges\b0\par\par\uc2 1,042 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 September 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Rully Arya Wisnubroto, Mandiri, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 During the second quarter of this year, Indonesian banks delivered a very good income performance. The combined net profit of the largest six banks in Indonesia reached Rp 46.7 trillion (US$3.27 billion), increasing significantly by 19.7 percent from the year before, driven by rising net interest income that also rose by almost 20 percent to Rp 129.9 trillion. Improving banks' profitability came after the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  experienced a strong recovery out of a recession during the second quarter.\par \par \uc2 Yet banks still face many challenges, especially from the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  impacts of stricter social restrictions to curb the spread of the more infectious COVID-19 variant, the Delta.\par \par \uc2 There are signs of slowing loan growth and weakening asset quality. Loan growth in July slowed to 0.5 percent on a yearly basis from 0.6 percent in June. And at the same time, the ratio of troubled assets increased to 3.4 percent from 3.2 percent.\par \par \uc2 Banks' performance will continue to improve this year, thoughthey may be affected by a slowdown in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery in the third quarter amid the second wave of the COVID-19 pandemic. Many macro indicators have shown a significant downturn since multi-tiered \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM) were implemented on Java and Bali Islands.\par \par \uc2 Consumer confidence decreasedquite significantly to 80.2 in July from 107.4 in June.\par \par \uc2 The Purchasing Managers' Index (PMI) at the same time dropped to 40.1 from 53.5. In August, the index improved slightly to 43.7 but still showed a contraction in the manufacturing industry.\par \par \uc2 Both output and new orders for industry products fell for two months straight as pandemic restrictions weighed on production and demand. Furthermore, the country's hotel occupancy rate in July plummeted to only 22.4 percent from 38.6 percent in June.\par \par \uc2 Banks have anticipated the weakening \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity by building up loan loss provisions. On the other hand, the threat of rising nonperforming loans (NPL) looms as the loan moratorium program is set to expire by March 2022.\par \par \uc2 Fortunately, the \uc2 Financial Services Authority (OJK) \uc2 decided to extend the loan restructuring relaxation program to March 31, 2023, from the previous deadline of March 31, 2022. This decision was made as a countercyclical \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to cushion banks and borrowers from the impact of the Delta variant.\par \par \uc2 Banks are given more time to build up more provisions and at the same time, debtors are given a greater ability and more time to manage their business to avoid turmoil when the relaxation program is over.\par \par \uc2 Amidweakening asset quality and weak loan demand, commercial banks in Indonesia are fundamentally strong and in very good condition. Besides strong profitability in the second quarter, the capital adequacy ratio (CAR) was very high at 24.7 percent as of July, well above the minimum regulatory threshold of 8 percent.\par \par \uc2 Banks' liquidity remained ample, with loan-to-debt ratio (LDR) standing at 79.9 percent in July and banks' fund placement in \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 's (BI) open monetary operation instrument amountingto Rp 657.3 trillion as of Aug. 20, as BI continued to conduct a very accommodative monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Banks' fund placements at government securities reached Rp 1.46quadrillion at the end of August, up by Rp 85.9 trillion fromthe end of 2020.\par \par \uc2 Some of the largest banks remain optimistic and maintain loan growth targets at 4 percent to 7 percent this year despite the sharp \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  deceleration in the third quarter. They expect certain industries and segments that have been driving the loan growth during the first six months of this year to continue throughout the year.\par \par \uc2 From the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  perspective, regulators, including theOJK, BI and the Finance Ministry, have taken a very important role in maintaining the health and stability of the banking industry in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 A recent pickup in demand for consumption loans was bolstered by a temporary luxury \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cut \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by the Finance Ministry for property and automotive sales. Recent improvements in micro, small and medium enterprise (MSME) loans in the past few months were also backed by the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  support as part of its National \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Recovery (PEN) program.\par \par \uc2 The OJK and BI continued to implement several regulations to accelerate digital transformation, increase Indonesian banks' competitiveness and strengthen intermediary functions, especially for small businesses.\par \par \uc2 The OJK issued in August three new regulations to improve banks' efficiency and competitiveness.\par \par \uc2 First, there is OJK \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 12/2021 on commercial banks, which emphasizes strengthening institutional regulations, including simplification in licensing. Second, OJK \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No.13/2021 on commercial banks' products emphasizesthe need for license and productimplementations to be more risk-based instead of capital-based. Finally, there is OJK \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 14/2021 on management quality.\par \par \uc2 At end of August, BI issued a \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  related to the Ratio for Macro-Prudential Financial Inclusion (RPIM), which is defined as the ratio of loans to MSMEs'total loans, as stated in BI Indonesia \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 23/2021.\par \par \uc2 The RPIM aims to improve banks' intermediary functions to the MSME segment, as well as providefinancing access to low-income individuals. The proportion of loans to MSMEs' total loans, as of June, is approximately 18.5 percent, which has stagnated for many years.\par \par \uc2 BI estimates that there is approximately Rp 1.6 quadrillion in unmet MSME credit demand, and realizing all of that unmet demand would potentially raise the MSME loan proportion to 45.7 percent of total disbursement.\par \par \uc2 Going forward, banks will have reasons to be more optimistic as there are signs of improvement in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially domestic household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Our Mandiri \b \highlight22\uc2 Spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  Index, an indicator for people's \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  based on debit card usage, has shown that \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities in both Java and outside Java have rebounded strongly in the past few weeks. The frequency of debit card use has bounced, surpassing pre-PPKM levels by the end of August.\par \par \uc2 This is encouraging, as household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is the largest component of Indonesia's GDP, thus, a very important indicator to determine the pace of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. But overall, there are still plenty of reasons whybanks must remain prudent, as \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  remain high.\par \par \uc2 ___________________\par \par \uc2 Senior fi nancial market analyst at Bank Mandiri\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210914eh9f00006\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
