\par\par \b \uc2 ASEAN, AUKUS and Australia's future nuclear submarine\b0\par\par\uc2 1,051 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 October 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Arie Afriansyah and Curie Maharani, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The announcement of a trilateral alliance of Australia, the United Kingdom and the United States in the Indo-Pacific, dubbed AUKUS, has surprised many, including the US' transatlantic allies and Australia's neighbors.\par \par \uc2 Before making a judgment of AUKUS' significance to the regional security architecture, we should ask what we know of the alliance besides the US promise to supply nuclear-powered submarines to Australia. Will Australia's future possession of nuclear-powered submarines trigger a nuclear arms race? What cards are left for ASEAN to play to keep the region away from a seeming trajectory toward war?\par \par \uc2 Arguably formed to deter China, AUKUS has instead taken down France as its first victim, when Australian Prime Minister Scott Morrison announced the dismissal of US$90 billion worth of submarine contracts inked with France in 2016.\par \par \uc2 The second victim is New Zealand, previously in ANZUS, but now left as a bystander. Prime Minister \uc2 Jacinda Arden\uc2  has insisted upon a nuclear-free \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and has banned nuclear-powered submarine in the country's waters, indicating disapproval of Australia's plan.\par \par \uc2 The third victim might have been the \uc2 European Union\uc2 , which was not consulted, but AUKUS utterly eclipsed its announcement of an Indo-Pacific strategy.\par \par \uc2 Inside Australia, whose \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  also remains in the dark on the alliance, concerns are also growing. Australia's joining of the elite club that operates nuclear submarines will surely boost its deterrence and regional standing, but there are also downsides from \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 , technological and strategic perspectives.\par \par \uc2 Australia's decision to cancel the French submarines would render five years of work and $2.4 billion as a "sunk cost" (The Strategist, Sept. 23, 2021). This includes 350 jobs at \uc2 Naval Group\uc2  Australia and more when considering its supply chain companies.\par \par \uc2 Australia will likely get fewer submarines because nuclear submarines are among the most expensive weapons systems to procure and maintain. Although Australia has the most globalized defense industry, which hosts 34 subsidiaries of global players, the transfer of submarine production capability entails risks of delay in delivery and underperformance.\par \par \uc2 Finally, the deal also violates the Australian core value of autarky because, without sovereign nuclear capability, Australia will be dependent upon a foreign nuclear propulsion system.\par \par \uc2 AUKUS conveys a strategic message that Australia has, at last, chosen to side with the US. China has already taken the new alliance as a hostile move and has changed its military deployments and countermeasures.\par \par \uc2 As expected, ASEAN members' initial responses are divided. As an immediate neighbor to Australia, Indonesia was informed about the alliance shortly before the announcement and responded straight away with concern of an arms race and conflict escalation.\par \par \uc2 Malaysia welcomed the partnership but "rejected the nuclear submarine". Singapore responded positively, conveying their hope for the partnership to contribute to peace and stability, followed by the Philippines and Vietnam.\par \par \uc2 But there is one crucial thing that China -- and Indonesia too -- got wrong: Nuclear-powered submarines are not the same as nuclear weapons. The nuclear triad concept consists of nuclear bombs and missiles launched from land, air and sea (including by non-nuclear submarines), not a platform powered by nuclear energy.\par \par \uc2 Providing Australia with a nuclear-powered submarine is also not the same as extending nuclear deterrence. Whether or not Australia becomes a nuclear power will also be determined by its \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  support, which now, is only supported by one third of its population (ASPI polling result, Sept. 28, 2021).\par \par \uc2 The short-to-medium-term effect of AUKUS might be derived from the fact that Australia will have a 15-year strategic gap between the retirement of its current submarines in 2025 and the indigenous production of new submarines in 2040. This strategic gap might be covered by leasing options or stationing allies' nuclear submarines in Australian bases, at the risk of inconveniencing neighbors and provoking adversaries.\par \par \uc2 How should ASEAN respond to this possibility?\par \par \uc2 At a time of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about inter-state politics, it is pertinent for ASEAN member to revisit their commitments based on the rule of law and reconsider their obligations in the 1971 Kuala Lumpur Declaration on the Zone of Peace, Freedom and Neutrality (ZOPFAN). It has been widely recognized that ZOPFAN is an effective diplomatic tool for ASEAN member countries in maintaining a neutral foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and preventing the excessive political influence of major countries.\par \par \uc2 ASEAN countries anticipated increasing number of nuclear-powered submarines and game-changing weapons in the region in their legal commitments to the Bangkok Treaty (the Treaty of the Southeast Asian Nuclear-Weapon-Free Zone) in 1995. This convention comprehensively prohibits all forms of proliferation and use of nuclear materials in the Southeast Asian region, except with the cooperation of the \uc2 International Atomic Energy Agency\uc2  (\uc2 IAEA\uc2 ).\par \par \uc2 Combined with the rights granted by the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea (UNCLOS) from 1982, ASEAN countries can act more decisively in terms of regulating their sea areas. In protecting the areas to be passed by nuclear-powered ships or submarines, ASEAN countries can also prohibit the exercise of their right of passage in accordance with Article 22(2) of UNCLOS 1982.\par \par \uc2 Thus, the position of Indonesia and other ASEAN member countries becomes essential by encouraging the parties to have dialogue in search of a peaceful power balance.\par \par \uc2 The presence of nuclear-powered submarines and other related technology in the region can be anticipated legally and politically. The concern about the impact of nuclear power being used on submarines is not its use as a weapon but its potential to create hazardous waste. ASEAN can voice concerns over the security and safety of using these submarines when passing through in the area.\par \par \uc2 One thing that needs to be avoided is the endless questioning of submarines as nuclear weapons. This could be used as pretext for others to build more nuclear weapons in the future as a response to AUKUS.\par \par \uc2 _____________________\par \par \uc2 Arie Afriansyah is an associate professor at the University of Indonesia's School of Law, the president of the Indonesian Society of International Law Lecturers (ISILL) and a member of the Executive Council of the Asian Society of International Law (AsianSIL). Curie Maharani is a faculty member at the Department of International Relations at Binus University and a research fellow at Lab45.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020210930eha100002\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
