\par\par \b \uc2 Want to put a price on CO2? Start with a coal  \highlight22\uc2 tax \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 979 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 October 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Theresia Betty Sumarno and Tara Laan , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Indonesia is currently considering its next big step in the fight against climate change: carbon pricing (Macroeconomic Framework and \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Principles for 2022, Finance Ministry).\par \par \uc2 Negotiating and implementing a carbon pricing mechanism will likely take years, but it doesn't mean we need to wait for an effective carbon \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 . There are other \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  solutions that could be implemented immediately to achieve the same goal.\par \par \uc2 Putting a price on carbon dioxide (CO2), the No. 1 contributor to climate change, is widely agreed to be one of the most effective and economically efficient ways to reduce emissions, according to "Taxing Energy Use 2019" by the \uc2 Organization for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development\uc2  (\uc2 OECD\uc2 ). This is because it encourages consumers and investors to switch to less polluting alternatives. The options on Indonesia's table include a national emissions trading scheme and a carbon \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 But the government is finding out that, while carbon pricing is an economically elegant solution, it is also politically controversial. The Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry has come out in support of a carbon \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (Kontan.co.id, Aug. 25, 2021), but wants more analysis of its potential impacts and a road map for implementation, including incentives.\par \par \uc2 Carbon-intensive sectors have voiced concerns that the carbon \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  would impact their competitiveness ("Putting A Price On Emissions", F. Rodyanto & A.S. Suwana, Mondaq). In response, the government is considering applying the carbon \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  only to coal-fired power plants starting in 2022, and then gradually imposing it on other sectors from 2025 onwards.\par \par \uc2 The final outcome of these consultations and negotiations are \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  and could take considerable time. And once an approach is agreed, phased implementation of the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  will likely take years. South Africa's carbon \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  was nearly a decade in the making. Even after the Carbon \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Act 15 of 2019 was enacted, most large emitting industries remain exempt, including coal and coal energy.\par \par \uc2 While the government is developing a carbon pricing mechanism, a process we wholeheartedly support, an interim solution would be to simply bump up regular \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on coal ("Taxing Coal to Hit the Goals", T.B. Sumarno, IISD). Imposing excise and value added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (VAT) on fossil fuels can act as a de facto carbon price. Applying conventional \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  on coal would be remarkably effective, given that coal accounts for 40 percent of Indonesia's energy-related emissions. It would also be relatively easy to administer, applying one \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate to one type of fuel.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's existing \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2  on coal are way too low to reflect the fuel's costs to society. In contrast, coal production and consumption benefit from multiple \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  exemptions. The social costs of coal include air pollution, land and water contamination, and climate change.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's coal-fired power plants are estimated to cause around 7,480 premature deaths per year from air pollution-related diseases, according to a study published in Environmental Science & Technology. A \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  would go some way to incorporating these social costs in the price of coal.\par \par \uc2 A coal \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  also generates significant revenue. A \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp 78,700 (US$5.50) per ton of coal, equivalent to a carbon \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp 32,000 ($2.20) per ton of CO2, would generate annual revenue of around Rp 49 trillion ($3.6 billion). This rate is less than half of the government's currently proposed carbon \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp 75,000 ($5.20) per ton of CO2. The coal \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  could be gradually increased to give the coal and electricity sectors time to adapt, while the revenue could be used for climate finance and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery.\par \par \uc2 India has demonstrated that coal \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  is politically and economically feasible. Like Indonesia, India has a large coal industry, substantial electricity \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , significant poverty and rapidly growing electricity demand. Despite these challenges, India imposed a coal "cess" (special \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 ) in 2010 that is equivalent to a rate of $5.50 per ton of coal today, similar to Indonesia's proposed rate, which raised $3.7 billion in revenue in 2019.\par \par \uc2 But what about the flow-on effect for electricity prices? Indonesia's indebted national electricity supplier, state electricity company PLN, can ill-afford extra costs. This challenge could be overcome by allowing PLN to pass on the coal \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  to consumers. The suggested coal \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate of Rp 78,700 per ton is likely to raise electricity prices by 3 percent. The \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue could then be used to compensate vulnerable households via targeted \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  such as cash transfers, or to improve energy efficiency in households and businesses.\par \par \uc2 Higher coal prices could also reduce coal production and export volumes, resulting in lower producer revenues, but this could be offset by revenues from the new coal \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate would need to be set to ensure a net increase in revenues, so the government is making more money from less coal. The revenues can be reinvested in coal workers and communities to help remediate mining sites and fund a just transition.\par \par \uc2 Coal has been the foundation of the country's development, but also a significant source of pollution. Now is the time to put in place a \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2 , while coal is still prevalent, so it can raise the revenues needed to support a just transition to clean energy.\par \par \uc2 If the government is committed to addressing carbon emissions, it should not delay action while it waits to develop and implement a carbon pricing mechanism. Instead, it should act immediately by imposing a coal \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a de facto carbon price.\par \par \uc2 As the Indonesian saying goes, "Tak ada rotan, akar pun jadi" (If there is no rattan, roots are OK).\par \par \uc2 ___________________\par \par \uc2 The writers are researchers at the \uc2 International Institute for Sustainable Development\uc2  (IISD). The views presented here are personal.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211003eha400009\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
