\par\par \b \uc2 Afghanistan, Biden's strategy and Indonesia's interests\b0\par\par\uc2 1,038 \uc2 words\par \uc2 11 October 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Wibawanto Nugroho Widodo, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The fall of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan on Aug. 15 to the hands of the \uc2 Taliban\uc2  following the exit of the United States and allied forces marked a new beginning for Afghanistan and the country's strategic impacts on international security in the coming years.\par \par \uc2 Three general historical patterns are obvious with regard to Afghanistan. First, the land, which connects Eurasia, has been continuously contested by foreign and global powers. Second, the tribal inhabitants are prone to fighting each other. And third, no clear unifying ideology exists to integrate different tribes, as even religious-political ideologies have failed to sustain their unity as a nation and country.\par \par \uc2 That said, no global powers stay there for a long time since their periodic presence in Afghanistan is only measured by Afghanistan's temporary influence on their national interests.\par \par \uc2 The future of Afghanistan under the \uc2 Taliban\uc2  hinges on their capability of coping with human, national and global security issues. The international community has noted that the \uc2 Taliban\uc2  have still not fulfilled many of their promises, including -- but not limited to -- redressing the warlord-dominated Cabinet and discrimination against women.\par \par \uc2 First, it remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  whether the \uc2 Taliban\uc2  can provide human security throughout the country according to the universal standard of the Human Rights and Human Security Indexes. Many say it is \uc2 Taliban\uc2 , rather than the Afghan people, who have the upper hand in changing the destiny of Afghanistan. This is the inverse logic of founding a state, in which citizens are the main subject of national development.\par \par \uc2 Second, there is no clear picture of the \uc2 Taliban\uc2 's ability to protect Afghanistan's territory or to create a secure, just and prosperous Afghan nation. The \uc2 Taliban\uc2  are likely to transform Afghanistan into a police state that emphasizes achieving national security at the cost of human security while at the same time being unable to provide basic services and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  goods to the Afghan people.\par \par \uc2 Third, the international community doubts that the \uc2 Taliban\uc2  regime can or will avoid creating international security problems.\par \par \uc2 So far only Saudi Arabia, United Arab Emirates and Pakistan that have acknowledged the \uc2 Taliban\uc2 's rule in Afghanistan, with Qatar, Iran, China and Russia predicted to follow suit. In principle, these states assume, and make their own justifications, that the \uc2 Taliban\uc2  are indeed central to regional stability.\par \par \uc2 President \uc2 Joe Biden\uc2 's assumptions regarding Afghanistan and global security are neo-Kantian: That modern affairs are driven mainly by democratization and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth rather than stressful security affairs; that the primary instruments are democratic institutions and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  instruments instead of military power; that the geographic focus is on Indo-Pacific and other regions instead of the Greater Middle East; and that the main foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  goal shall be democracy and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth instead of stable security affairs.\par \par \uc2 For Biden and his administration, although it was a fiasco to establish an inherent political system in Afghanistan (with an average 70 percent of the Afghan state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  backed by the US), the US national security objectives during its presence in Afghanistan from 2001 until 2021 have been achieved to a certain extent, such as overthrowing the \uc2 Taliban\uc2  government that led to the capture of \uc2 Osama Bin Laden\uc2  and getting the \uc2 Taliban\uc2 's promise not to attack the US or the post-World War II world order, so that the overall benefits are assumed to be bigger than the costs.\par \par \uc2 The Biden administration does not see the withdrawal from Afghanistan as a defeat. Reflecting on the US forces' pullout of Vietnam in 1973, which led to the collapse of Soviet Union communism in 1991. Biden's strategic logic assumes that religious extremism and violent movements instigated and promulgated by the \uc2 Taliban\uc2  will be defeated and reduced in years ahead.\par \par \uc2 Consequently, in the coming years, the US national security strategy with respect to the Greater Middle East and Afghanistan will be overhauled and shift toward progressive multilateral approaches, where modes of action at least will be more indirect instead of direct, multilateral instead of unilateral and covert instead of overt, by orchestrating more on non-US governmental actors and on governmental nonmilitary instruments of power that include intelligence, information, diplomacy and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In terms of strategic approaches, the US national security strategy with respect to Afghanistan is also shifting toward more observing, accommodating, shaping, persuading, enabling and inducing, instead of coercing, subduing and eradicating. In short, Biden's post-Afghanistan strategy will draw more from the experiences of how the US defeated communism in the post-Vietnam War era, 18 years after their withdrawal from the lower Mekong.\par \par \uc2 As for Indonesia, we will observe the developments in Afghanistan strategically and determine whether we need to acknowledge the \uc2 Taliban\uc2  government.\par \par \uc2 First, the geopolitical implications for Indonesia are not direct but still significant. These include the ideologies of hardline Islamist political movements inspired by the \uc2 Taliban\uc2 's return to power, which contradict Pancasila values as our center of gravity, strategic culture and way of life, as well as the possible exodus of Afghan people to Indonesia, ASEAN and Australia.\par \par \uc2 Second, Indonesia needs a global and proactive counterterrorism strategy and the application of Pancasila as a working ideology in the lives of Indonesians to counterbalance the ideological warfare fought on the global level between key players involved in the affairs of the post-US-era Afghanistan.\par \par \uc2 Third, Indonesia needs to have access to the Middle East's major stakeholders: Jews, Arabs and Persians. Such access is a key asset for Indonesia to monitor and influence the situation in Afghanistan in line with Indonesia's national interests.\par \par \uc2 Fourth, Indonesia should consider the shifting of US security \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and resources from Afghanistan to the South China Sea and, therefore, review our strategic assumptions and geostrategy accordingly.\par \par \uc2 These four \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  orientations are not a panacea, but at least they are the determining ingredients to leverage Indonesia's freedom of interests to protect and advance national security interests in the contemporary international security environment.\par \par \uc2 ___________________\par \par \uc2 Deputy chair of defense and security affairs at the Association of National Resilience Institute Alumni (IKAL) Strategic Centre and international director at the Democracy and Integrity for Peace (DIP) Institute. The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211010ehab0000b\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par \b \uc2 Galvanize Cloud Adoption to Power Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s Digital  \highlight22\uc2 Economy \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 1,215 \uc2 words\par \uc2 13 October 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Despite the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by the Covid-19 pandemic, Indonesia continues to be one of the fastest-growing digital economies in Southeast Asia. By 2025, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s digital gross merchandise value (GMV) will hit $124 billion, up from $44 billion in 2020.\par \par \uc2 Cloud technology, which allows for the delivery of different computing services such as data storage, servers, and databases through the Internet, has catalyzed Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. In 2019, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  cloud market was expected to grow from $0.2 billion in 2018 to $0.8 billion in 2023.\par \par \uc2 It has supported the advancement of small and medium enterprises (SMEs) by democratizing access to technologies and services that used to be available only to large enterprises. It has also enabled the government to provide better services such as the Cash-for-Training (Kartu Prakerja) program from the Coordinating Ministry of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs and online learning initiatives from the Ministry of Education.\par \par \uc2 As more Indonesians come online and local businesses switch to cloud solutions, demand for cloud services is growing exponentially. The private sector has driven a significant part of this growth in cloud adoption. Grab, for instance, has used cloud computing technology to rapidly accelerate the digitization of SMEs by helping merchants with zero online presence get onboarded to the platform, set up digital payment and delivery systems, and access business analytics tools.\par \par \uc2 While the private sector has been the primary engine for cloud adoption in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , there is a tremendous opportunity for digital transformation in the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector. The Covid-19 pandemic has helped governments realize the potential of cloud solutions, especially as they are forced to deploy digital services quickly to respond to citizens\u8217\'20\'19 needs.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.alibabacloud.com/press-room/indonesia-adopts-cloud-based-technology-during-pandemic"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 A recent survey by Alibaba Cloud }}}\uc2 found that 83 percent of executives in Indonesia believe that cloud-based tools help them cope with their needs during Covid-19, highlighting the uptick in\par \par \uc2 cloud service adoption in the country.\par \par \uc2 To truly leverage the cloud to spur the growth of Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , it is imperative that the digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is empowered to embrace the cloud at speed and scale easily. The government\u8217\'20\'19s cloud-first \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  must translate into forward-looking regulations that promote, not hinder, cloud adoption.\par \par \uc2 To ensure that the Indonesian digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reaps the full benefits that cloud computing solutions have to offer, the government needs to address crucial aspects of existing policies that may impede the ability of the digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to adopt cloud solutions quickly, dampen innovation, and impact investments that drive growth in this space.\par \par \uc2 A 2020 Ministerial \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on Private Electronic System Operators (MR 5), 2018 Government \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on E-Government (GR 95), and the Personal Data Protection Bill all contain welcome improvements to the existing legal framework. However, there are provisions within these that create an \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  and fragmented regulatory environment.\par \par \uc2 MR5, for instance, defines Electronic System Operators (ESOs) very broadly, essentially encompassing most types of electronic system providers that may not pose a risk to Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s national security, cause social and political unrest, or personal data breaches.\par \par \uc2 Cloud service providers are equated with other ESOs, including the likes of social media and search engines. That creates confusion over the responsibility of the cloud, especially over personal data, and grants excessive access for law enforcement and regulatory purposes. The potential inclusion of offshore entities is also a concern, along with the onerous registration\par \par \uc2 processes involved, details of which are not clear.\par \par \uc2 The Personal Data Protection Bill (RUU PDP), which regulates personal data processing in Indonesia, exempts data owners\u8217\'20\'19 rights if their data are needed for the purpose of national defense and security, law enforcement, state administration, supervision of the financial or monetary sector, payment systems, or financial system stability. These exemptions are concerning because they provide the government with unfettered access to personal data.\par \par \uc2 In addition to RUU PDP, Indonesia also has restrictive data localization policies that make the Internet less accessible and secure, more costly and complicated, and less innovative. A recent study on cross-border data flows by ITIF notes that over five years, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s gross \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  output dropped by 7.8 percent while experiencing lower productivity and an increase in prices due to more stringent data restrictions from 2013-2018.\par \par \uc2 Specifically, for cloud service providers, data localization makes it impossible for them to employ cybersecurity best practices, such as through \u8220\'20\'1Csharding,\u8221\'20\'1D wherein data is spread over multiple data centers. This is particularly useful to SMEs who cannot afford to implement a robust security program.\par \par \uc2 The National Data Centre initiative, part of the legal framework for e-government services \u8211\'20\'13 GR 95, is an ambitious project intended to be a shared infrastructure/managed service to ensure efficiency among the Central and Local Governments. In preparation for the National Data Centre, which is targeted to be completed in 2024, Kominfo has issued two circulars that seem to be antithetical to supporting a holistic cloud computing environment for \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  agencies.\par \par \uc2 First, Circular 5/2020 requires all \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  agencies to seek Kominfo\u8217\'20\'19s clearance before procuring data centers, including the \u8216\'20\'18data center lease\u8217\'20\'19 of cloud or disaster recovery centers. A second Circular \u8211\'20\'13 3/2021 on the Use of Cloud for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Sector \u8211\'20\'13 indicated that cloud procurement does not require clearance. This contradicts Circular 5/2020, as cloud services can be considered a \u8216\'20\'18data center lease\u8217\'20\'19, and therefore would require Kominfo approval.\par \par \uc2 However, Kominfo\u8217\'20\'19s stance for usage beyond 2021 is also unclear. Additionally, Circular 3/2021 states that while ministries and agencies \u8220\'20\'1Cmust prioritize integration into a National Data Centre, they may \u8220\'20\'1Cuse their own data centers to increase the availability and capacity of cloud computing services.\u8221\'20\'1D This implies that cloud is the second preferred option after the National Data Centre, which contradicts the objective of leveraging cloud services to strengthen the delivery of e-government services.\par \par \uc2 Unlocking the true potential of cloud to power Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  As policymakers and regulators seek to reap the benefits of cloud technology while managing its risks, it is\par \par \uc2 important to recognize that the legal and regulatory landscape for cloud is highly complex and as broad as the scope of the technology itself, spanning multiple industries and geographies.\par \par \uc2 Implementing a data classification \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that adheres to a risk-based data classification framework is fundamental in helping governments adopt cloud solutions. Recognizing the inherent security of the cloud architecture and the evolving nature of this technology will be critical to responsibly unlock the potential of cloud services for Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector, businesses, and\par \par \uc2 society.\par \par \uc2 Consistent, cloud-friendly policies that recognize the unique model of cloud, are aligned with industry best practices, and are harmonized with other cloud-related policies can be achieved by working closely with industry to develop regulatory frameworks that can effectively aid national efforts to stimulate the country\u8217\'20\'19s cloud ecosystem and strengthen trust and participation by all stakeholders. Only then would the government be able to fully maximize the potential of cloud computing to drive the growth of the country\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a whole.\par \par \uc2 Jeff Paine is managing director of Asia Internet Coalition, a trade association co-founded by \uc2 eBay\uc2 , \uc2 Google\uc2 , \uc2 Nokia\uc2 , Skype, and \uc2 Yahoo! \uc2 in 2010 to promote \b \highlight22\uc2 public policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues about the Internet in the Asia Pacific region.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020211013ehad00005\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
