\par\par \b \uc2 Oil output could plummet 87% by 2040: Board\b0\par\par\uc2 Divya Karyza, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 686 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 October 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The \uc2 National Energy Board\uc2  (DEN) predicts a drastic decline in domestic oil output over the coming two decades, with current production already far below the targeted 1 million barrels of oil per day (bopd).\par \par \uc2 DEN secretary-general Djoko Siswanto predicted that oil production would drop to only 300,000 bopd in 2030 and 119,000 bopd in 2040 without regulations and incentives to encourage more exploration, enhanced oil recovery (EOR) and the acquisition of oil fields abroad.\par \par \uc2 "Efforts to increase oil production need to be carried out quickly," he said during an online webinar on Tuesday, adding that progress toward achieving the 1 million bopd target was hindered by conflicts of interest within organization units, slowing down the procurement of drilling rigs, the implementation of EOR and the acquisition of permits from regional administrations.\par \par \uc2 Upstream Oil and Gas Regulatory Special Task Force (SKKMigas) spokesman Rinto Pudyantoro declined to provide details on exploration and production in the third quarter but said the agency would arrange a press conference in the near future.\par \par \uc2 "We cannot comment yet," he told The Jakarta Post on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Separately, \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Research Institute for ASEAN and East Asia\uc2  (ERIA) energy economist Alloysius Joko Purwanto said the DEN's estimation was based on the assumption that the downward trend in production from 2016 to 2020 would continue to 2030 and beyond.\par \par \uc2 "It is possible that the government will miss the target if there is no significant improvement compared to the 2016-2020 period," he told the Post.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's oil production has declined over the past five years. Output fell from 831,000 bopd in 2016 to just 708,000 bopd in 2020, Energy and Mineral Resources Ministry data show. A further decline to 300,000 bopd in 2030 and 119,000 bopd in 2040 would amount to a drop of around 58 and 87 percent, respectively, from the 2020 level.\par \par \uc2 Joko went on to say that the government should consider using carbon \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenue to provide incentives for the implementation of carbon capture, utilization and storage (CCUS) technology. The captured carbon dioxide (CO2) would speed up the EOR process.\par \par \uc2 Reforminer Institute executive director Komaidi Notonegoro did not rule out such a scenario. "[The prediction] is valid," he said via text message on Wednesday, adding that, without a significant amount of new development and exploration wells, oil production will not reach the target.\par \par \uc2 Exacerbating the situation, the National General Energy Plan (RUEN) projects a drastic increase in oil and gas consumption over the coming decades.\par \par \uc2 Similarly, according to SKKMigas data, domestic oil consumption is forecast to more than double to 3.97 million bopd in 2050, while natural gas consumption is expected to more than quadruple to 26,000 million standard cubic feet per day (mmscfd).\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Oil and Gas Companies Association (Aspermigas) secretary-general Moshe Rizal said the prediction would come to pass if stakeholders were idle. In reality, state-owned oil and gas company \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  and oil and gas contractors had undertaken efforts to prevent the decline in oil production, he said.\par \par \uc2 "The probability of [the prediction] coming to pass is very low," Moshe told The Jakarta Post on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Challenges to achieving the 1 million bopd target, Moshe said, included contractors' and investors' reluctance to invest in high-risk activities not directly related to production, such as exploration, due to the fluctuating oil prices and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by the pandemic.\par \par \uc2 "Strategic efforts are critical to attract [investment into] exploration projects," SKKMigas head representative for Java, Bali and Nusa Tenggara Nurwahidi said during the same event on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Nurwahidi also projected an oversupply of gas in East Java and Central Java in 2022 as oil and gas firm Husky-CNOOC Madura Limited (HCML) and \uc2 Pertamina\uc2 's upstream subsidiary PT Pertamina EP Cepu (PEPC) come onstream. He went on to say that gas supply to West Java would depend on the construction of the Cirebon-Semarang gas pipeline (Cisem).\par \par \uc2 "The excess gas would be used to develop a petrochemical facility and build a liquified natural gas refinery," he said.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211014ehaf0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
