\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b \uc2 INDONESIA READY TO DEEPEN  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMIC \highlight\uc2  ENGAGEMENT WITH LAC COUNTRIES: INDUSTRY MINISTRY\b0\par\par\uc2 470 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 October 2021\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Juwita Trisna Rahayu\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) -\par \par \uc2 Indonesia is ready to deepen its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  engagement with Latin America and Caribbean (LAC) countries post-COVID-19 pandemic, Industry Ministry \uc2 Agus Gumiwang Kartasasmita\uc2  said.\par \par \uc2 In his speech at the 2021 INA-LAC Business Forum held online on Thursday, he stated, \u8220\'20\'1CIndonesia is ready to explore the potential to deepen its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  engagement with LAC countries.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 He made this statement following announcement that Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s total global trade was recorded at only 2 per cent, while the total for LAC countries only reached 0.32 per cent.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThese figures do not reflect our true potentials,\u8221\'20\'1D he stressed.\par \par \uc2 However, Gumiwang is optimistic that Indonesia will achieve \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery by 2022, influenced by various factors, such as successfully handling COVID-19, a recovery in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consumption, the implementation of structural reforms and rising prospects for the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The IMF World \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Outlook published this year estimated developing countries may reach a strong growth of some 5.2 per cent.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIn line with this, our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery in 2022 is expected to grow 5.0 to 5.5 per cent,\u8221\'20\'1D he explained, but acknowledged the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by the emergence and spread of new COVID-19 variants will remain determining factors that must be considered.\par \par \uc2 However, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s experienced in managing the second wave of COVID-19 through a mandatory vaccination program and the enforcement of health protocols increased the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s confidence to move forward with social \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities, he stressed.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CI am proud that Indonesia was nominated to be one of the best countries in the world in managing the second wave of COVID-19. The recognition of John Hopkins University was a result of Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s ability to reduce confirmed cases by over 58 per cent weekly,\u8221\'20\'1D Gumiwang said.\par \par \uc2 The enforcement of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity restrictions (PPKM), especially in the islands of Java and Bali, decreased case by 94 per cent from the peak in July 2021, he added.\par \par \uc2 Businesses and industries, therefore, began to reopen and local economies started to recover.\par \par \uc2 The trade balance in August showed a surplus of US$4.7 billion, out of a total US$19.1 billion from January 2021.\par \par \uc2 Exports grew by 37.7 per cent year-on-year, supported by exports of coal, palm oil, basic iron, steel and natural gas, while imports grew by 33 per cent year-on-year driven by positive growth in imports of raw materials and capital goods.\par \par \uc2 The global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continues to recover in line with the optimism as indicated by the rebound in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the second quarter of 2021, Gumiwang noted.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe must recover and grow powerfully together,\u8221\'20\'1D he said in conclusion.\par \par \uc2 (T.J010/A/H-FDH/H-FDH) 15-10-2021 00:02:35\par \par \uc2 Document 