\par\par \b \uc2 Seven years on, Jokowi sticking with  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 833 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 October 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 President Joko "Jokowi" Widodo has consistently prioritized \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development in his seven years of leadership, but Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has remained below target.\par \par \uc2 COVID-19 policies are the latest example of how the Jokowi administration places the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  above other \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  goals; in this case, over \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  health. During the early days of the pandemic, the government refused to heed scientific advice to impose a lockdown aimed at curbing the spread of the coronavirus.\par \par \uc2 The government pointed to the severe \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  repercussions of a lockdown and the huge \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  that would be needed to keep people and businesses afloat. Instead of a lockdown, the government enforced a variety of activity curbs, including the latest emergency social restrictions (PPKMD) in a tiered system adapted to the regional threat level.\par \par \uc2 Comparatively loose curbs allowed Indonesia to record a smaller \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  contraction than other countries at 2.07 percent in 2020, Statistics Indonesia (BPS) data shows. The government also booked a \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  smaller than other governments at 6.1 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) last year, Finance Ministry data shows.\par \par \uc2 The Jokowi administration's refusal to lock down the country, however, came at a cost. When the Delta variant drove the second wave of the pandemic, the number of daily confirmed deaths peaked at 2,069 on July 27.\par \par \uc2 Mohammad Faisal, executive director of the Center for Reform on Economics (CORE) Indonesia, said that \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  decision, which made it hard to bring the pandemic under control, had dragged out the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery.\par \par \uc2 "The pandemic response was very slow in the beginning; with minimal healthcare intervention. It improved in 2021 but was still plagued by many problems," Faisal told The Jakarta Post in a phone interview on Monday.\par \par \uc2 In 2020, the government spent only an extra Rp 63 trillion (US$4.51 million) on health care, just 10.95 percent of the actualized national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery (PEN) \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Finance Ministry data shows.\par \par \uc2 Amid the pandemic, the government also pursued structural reforms through the job creation bill, which the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  passed into law in early October last year. The law revised nearly 80 laws to simplify business procedures.\par \par \uc2 The Job Creation Law prompted protest from labor unions, environmental groups, human rights activists and students, as the reforms came at the expense of labor rights and environmental protection.\par \par \uc2 For example, the law introduced a risk-based approach that requires businesses to get an environmental permit only if their operations are deemed to pose a high risk to health and safety.\par \par \uc2 "The approach was overly simplistic and rushed, so the law came at the cost of dissatisfaction among various elements [of society], even though the intention is good," Faisal said.\par \par \uc2 Faisal added that many issues hindering investment and job creation were unrelated to regulations, and the law did not necessarily address these.\par \par \uc2 Corruption, for example, remained a key challenge to doing business in Indonesia, British Chamber of Commerce in Indonesia (BritCham) chairman Olly Riches said last month, citing a business confidence index produced by European business chambers.\par \par \uc2 During Jokowi's first term in office from 2014 to 2019, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies focused on the development of infrastructure like highways and airports, especially outside Java, to improve connectivity and reduce logistics costs. In addition, the administration focused on foreign direct investment (FDI) and universal\par \par \uc2 health care.\par \par \uc2 In Jokowi's first term, the administration planned to develop 223 projects and three programs as part of national strategic projects totaling Rp 4.18 quadrillion. However, between 2016 and August 2019, the government developed only 81 projects with an investment of Rp 390 trillion.\par \par \uc2 In 2017, the Jokowi administration launched the Mandalika special \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  zone (SEZ), which measures 1,035 hectares, in Central Lombok, West Nusa Tenggara. After years of construction, the SEZ now hosts a 4.31-kilometer MotoGP circuit. But the project is mired in alleged human rights violations, according to the United Nations.\par \par \uc2 Despite his push for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms and major infrastructure projects, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth never met the targets outlined by the government. In 2019, for example, the government aimed for 8 percent GDP growth, but actual growth was only 5.02 percent, BPS data shows.\par \par \uc2 Faisal Rachman, an economist at state-owned \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2 , said the failure to meet the growth target was related to a slowdown in global growth and the end of the commodity boom.\par \par \uc2 Infrastructure development is expected to lead to faster and more sustained \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the medium and long term, according to Faisal.\par \par \uc2 The pandemic has added pressure on the government's efforts to meet its growth target. Last year, Indonesia suffered its first recession since the Asian financial crisis.\par \par \uc2 "If the government can really implement structural and bureaucratic reforms, there is still a potential to meet [the growth target], although it will be quite difficult because of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  related to the pandemic," Faisal told the Post in a text message on Monday.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211020ehal00002\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
