\par\par \b \uc2 Increasing risks of bad bank loans amid pandemic\b0\par\par\uc2 991 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 October 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Harry Pattikawa , Rotterdam, the Netherlands\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) \uc2 and the \uc2 Financial Services Authority (OJK) \uc2 have been actively working hand in hand to save the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from the health crisis caused by COVID-19.\par \par \uc2 BI has increased the loan to value (LTV) ratio from 80-90 percent to 100 percent. The LTV is the ratio of the total loan to the value of the assets financed with that loan. An LTV at 100 percent indicates no equity required. This \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is valid from March to December. Furthermore, LTVs of 100 percent may only be given by banks with non-performing loan (NPL) ratios of less than 5 percent of total loans. This LTV \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is only limited to the property and car industries.\par \par \uc2 Concerning the NPL criterion mentioned, the OJK has simultaneously relaxed the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on the classification of NPL ratios by taking out restructured loans from the classification. The \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is valid until March 2022.\par \par \uc2 There are four negative impacts from these policies that I need to address.\par \par \uc2 First, systematic risk in the banking sector is most likely to increase. The 5 percent NPL required for the 100 percent LTV does not represent the actual banking risk. This is because restructured loans have been removed from the NPL classification, causing the NPL ratio to look less concerning.\par \par \uc2 Restructured loans in the banking sector are worrying and can potentially drag the entire financial system. According to Fitch's Rating Agency, restructured loans at the 12 largest banks rose to about 21.5 percent of the total at the end of the first quarter of 2021, from 5.5 percent in the same period in 2020.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the property sector in Indonesia has actually weakened, threatening the banking sector even more. \uc2 Moody's\uc2  expects demand in the property sector to rise in 2021 and 2022, but the agency forecasts this sector to remain weaker than pre-pandemic levels due to high US dollar debt levels while rupiah income has not fully recovered.\par \par \uc2 According to \uc2 Moody's\uc2 , the rupiah has depreciated by around 15 percent against the greenback this year. A depreciation of the rupiah against the dollar will weaken the ability of Indonesian property developers to serve dollar debts.\par \par \uc2 More than two-thirds of the companies' combined debt is in dollars, while their income is in rupiahs. \uc2 Moody's\uc2  expects the financial leverage of developers to deteriorate significantly.\par \par \uc2 Restructured loans arise because borrowers fail to meet their obligations. If the borrower still has an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  future that is fine, the coronavirus may be to blame, but in many cases there are zombie companies that should actually be liquidated, but are forced to live on. The entire banking system has not been forced to set aside solid provisions to cover the blows when these zombie companies actually die.\par \par \uc2 Given the great potential for NPL ratios to deteriorate and the ailing real estate sector, the easing of LTV and restructured loans will pose significant risks to the banking sector.\par \par \uc2 Second, this LTV \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  only applies to the property and car sector. In essence, BI and the OJK are participating in allowing zombie companies to live by using resources from potential \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sources. A study by the \uc2 Bank of Canada\uc2  and published by the \uc2 Organization for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development\uc2  shows that increases in zombie companies suppress investment and employment growth of productive companies and have been associated with widening the productivity gap between zombie and productive companies.\par \par \uc2 This research shows the healthiest productive companies are the most harmed by zombie companies. By excluding the productive sectors, Indonesia will lose opportunities, especially after the pandemic ends.\par \par \uc2 Third, this \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will refoster moral hazard. For general \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  understanding, moral hazard is risk-increasing behavior by bankers if they do not assume the direct risk of their actions. Hence, the gain is for them, and the pain is for the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Many scholars have argued that moral hazard played an important role in the 2008 financial crisis.\par \par \uc2 The bankers take the position that the government always comes as a guiding angel by facilitating regulations such as restructured loans that are rolled out further into the future. The debtors take a relaxed position that the banks are willing for another restructuring in the event of default. The banks have subsequently restructured loans on restructured loans, and eventually the government bails out the distressed banks.\par \par \uc2 Fourth, BI and the OJK have ingeniously combined risk management and incentives, which can pose a big risk in the financial system. Yet stable risk management greatly contributes to a sound banking system and confidence in the banking system. For this reason, risk-management \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  should be focused only on potential risks and not be redesigned to satisfy the need for national incentives.\par \par \uc2 As a result, this inconsistent risk-management \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has the potential to create distrust in BI and the OJK. The \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  tends to believe that these two institutions have been used as tools for government actions. Furthermore, the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  doubts the independence of BI and the OJK, which ultimately creates \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . According to empirical research conducted by \uc2 the Bank of France\uc2 , \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  about \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies plays a role in shaping the credibility and reputation of central banks. Eventually, \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  from shocks to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  cause an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  contraction and a relatively sharp decline in confidence or satisfaction levels, which generally take longer to rebuild than the time needed to rebuild the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The COVID-19 crisis is new, unique and it will perhaps take some time to really understand it. It is difficult to predict. Therefore, based on the four points I have addressed, using BI and the OJK as tools is not an option that can be accounted for. In this new type of crisis, the government is the only one that must bear the full burden.\par \par \uc2 Rising government debt and deficits are consequences that affects all governments nowadays.\par \par \uc2 ______________\par \par \uc2 A monetary analyst\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211020ehal00009\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
