\par\par \b \uc2 Profit at any cost?: Government sends mixed signals on SOEs' fates\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 767 \uc2 words\par \uc2 1 November 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 President Joko "Jokowi" Widodo's recently expressed desire to end financial support for state-owned enterprises (SOEs) has raised concerns in the sector, as many such companies rely on government bailouts to escape dire financial straits.\par \par \uc2 Jokowi said on Oct. 16 that he wanted to stop providing state capital injections and other "protections" to ailing SOEs, noting that he would prefer instead to close them as government underwriting had kept SOEs uncompetitive and unprofessional.\par \par \uc2 The president's statement came a few months after the \uc2 SOEs Ministry\uc2  proposed the allocation of Rp 72 trillion (US$5.127 billion) for capital injections next year to assist debt-laden SOEs and streamline government projects.\par \par \uc2 Economists told The Jakarta Post that ending such capital injections would be tough as the government often needed SOEs to execute loss-making government programs, such as providing subsidized goods, developing \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  infrastructure and implementing COVID-19 relief programs.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, government \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  (PP) No. 45/2005 guarantees government compensation for SOEs that carry out unprofitable government programs.\par \par \uc2 "If SOEs were left alone to find funding, they would definitely fall into a ravine of problems. A very high debt-to-equity ratio would occur," said Toto Pranoto, an expert on SOEs from the University of Indonesia (UI), on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 He said the root of the problem was the poor handling and weak oversight of state capital injections, rather than the funding itself. Thus, the government should only close ailing SOEs whose products and services were not vital to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interest.\par \par \uc2 Official data shows that SOEs' finances have been generally declining since at least 2016 as a result of falling commodity prices and government-ordered projects, but the pandemic-induced \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturn last year took a further toll on the companies' books.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 SOEs Ministry\uc2  estimated that SOEs' net profits plummeted by 77 percent to Rp 28 trillion last year, while revenue fell 25 percent to Rp 1.2 quadrillion, as the coronavirus pandemic led to mobility restrictions and hit household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 At the same time, SOEs' liabilities rose 9.6 percent to Rp 6.7 quadrillion last year, around half of which came from higher third-party funds from state-owned banks, while the other half came from debt, according to the ministry, as quoted by kontan.co.id.\par \par \uc2 Statistics Indonesia (BPS) data show that SOEs' debt-to-equity ratio has been generally increasing since at least 2016, when the ratio was 1.87.\par \par \uc2 Aside from the financial sector, the construction sector posted the highest debt-to-equity ratio at 2.88, followed by the transportation and warehousing sector.\par \par \uc2 State-owned construction firms such as \uc2 PT Waskita Karya\uc2 , \uc2 PT Hutama Karya\uc2  and PT Perumnas are on the front lines of the Jokowi administration's infrastructure development plans, which include building toll roads, airports and electricity grids.\par \par \uc2 "There are a lot of assignments for SOEs. If the government is serious, then some SOEs must be allowed to reject some of the projects that are not feasible financially," said Institute for Development of Economics and Finance (Indef) executive director Tauhid Ahmad on Monday.\par \par \uc2 Jokowi warned SOEs to properly calculate the rate of returns and the necessary support from the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for government-assigned projects.\par \par \uc2 But in a move that points in the opposite direction of his declared intention, Jokowi recently signed a presidential \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  allowing state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  intervention in the Jakarta-Bandung high-speed railway, a project blighted by significant cost overruns and multiple delays.\par \par \uc2 Some SOEs also benefit from good ratings from credit rating agencies, despite global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  or internal financial problems, thanks to direct or indirect government backing.\par \par \uc2 For 20 state-owned publicly listed companies, the ratio of debt to earnings before interest, \b \highlight22\uc2 taxes\b0 \highlight\uc2 , depreciation and amortization (EBITDA) has also surged. Standard & Poor (S&P) Global Ratings estimated that the ratio, which reflects debt servicing capacity, swelled to around 5 in 2018, up from 1 in 2011.\par \par \uc2 Center of Economics and Law Studies (CELIOS) director Bhima Yudhistira said the idea of rescinding protection could be good for businesses as a whole, if the government could pull it off.\par \par \uc2 "If some SOEs turn out to be in a poor state after revoking their protection, then we know which companies are underperforming and no longer need to be kept going," Bhima said.\par \par \uc2 However, he said the government should handle the matter with the utmost caution, as not all sectors could be freed from protection and full privatization could harm the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interest.\par \par \uc2 -- Vincent Fabian Thomas contributed to this story.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211031ehb10000b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
