\par\par \b \uc2 New normal and new post-pandemic fraud landscape\b0\par\par\uc2 1,200 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 November 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Esther Roseline , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The full-blown COVID-19 has staggered all nations across the globe, but what comes with it and especially after it is not less "deadly" and threatening, which is a new post-pandemic fraud landscape.\par \par \uc2 With vaccinations being administered and mobility restrictions lifted, there are shifts in business operations and changing consumer behaviors that may remain in the "new" normal, which should compel organizations to prepare for and brace themselves in the face of a "post-pandemic" reality. There is a possibility that the health crisis has translated into emerging fraud risks.\par \par \uc2 A global survey conducted from March to April by the \uc2 Association of Certified Fraud Examiners\uc2  (ACFE), in partnership with Grant Thornton, discovered that the majority of organizations around the world had uncovered more fraud since the onset of the pandemic, and expected the level of fraud impacting organizations to increase even more over the next year.\par \par \uc2 This consequential finding should set off alarm bells among national and organization leaders that immediate action must be taken before mere ignorance takes its toll. Leaders must refrain from finding solace in no fraud having ever been uncovered in their current organization and so indulging in the gratifying delusion that there is no fraud to fear.\par \par \uc2 No or little fraud having been uncovered always means two possibilities: the best scenario, indeed the organization has an excellent environment for deterring fraud - which is the ideal goal of every organization; or the worst, the organization has virtually no sufficient measure to detect fraud and so the rat has total freedom to gnaw at every resource the organization has with no worry of getting caught.\par \par \uc2 In either scenario, however, no organization can afford to be complacent at a time such as this.\par \par \uc2 In the foreseeable post-pandemic situation, there are two significant changes that are inevitable: changes in fraud risks or schemes, and changes in anti-fraud programs and tactics.\par \par \uc2 Fraud does not stand still, and it is even more rapidly changing when the perfect storm permits. According to the same survey by ACFE and Grant Thornton, some of the top fraud schemes that are expected to significantly increase over the next 12 months are cyberfraud, social engineering, identity crime, unemployment fraud, payment fraud, fraud by vendors and sellers, healthcare fraud and insurance fraud.\par \par \uc2 It is not a surprising finding that cyberfraud, social engineering and identity crime top the list in a situation where almost all activities have gone online, remote working is implemented and people are forced to socially distance.\par \par \uc2 Unemployment fraud is very likely increasing as unemployment increases due to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturn, and payment fraud as well as external fraud by vendors may subsequently follow for the same reason. Healthcare fraud and insurance fraud, on the other hand, are highly possible to increase when health becomes one of the people's primary concerns and it becomes a golden opportunity seized by fraudsters to cash in on the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's genuine fears.\par \par \uc2 The education sector is also not immune to such pernicious threats when prevalence of COVID-related online cheating comes to the fore and the so-called "global epidemic of online cheating" dominates many news media outlets around the world.\par \par \uc2 Long-term consequences begin to loom in the post-pandemic world: pervasive academic dishonesty triggered by remote learning may have severe consequences for the future workplace and for the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 What does the future hold when the future generation's integrity and capability are adversely affected by remote learning? Another fraud risk is imminent.\par \par \uc2 In view of the great \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  mixed with impending threat enveloping the post-pandemic fraud landscape, a strategic change in anti-fraud tactics is bound to be undertaken, especially when the circumstances also influence the way anti-fraud programs are to be executed. For example, person-to-person interviewing style must be shifted to online communication with certain limitations such as being unable to see physical cues and difficulty in developing a rapport. Also, site visits and offline compliance monitoring, including face-to-face training must be switched to online monitoring and online training style, with concerns of ineffectiveness.\par \par \uc2 The question thereby left to us remains: how to tailor our tactics to the pressing demands, including wielding technological power to the advantage of anti-fraud goals.\par \par \uc2 First, addressing means of communication and training. Communication is key to collaborative efforts against fraud and should always be of utmost importance; and training is just one way of communicating. On one hand, remote training and online communication often have their effectiveness questioned at their base, albeit not without legitimate reasons (such as people's focus may diminish with lack of direct contact).\par \par \uc2 Nonetheless, on the other hand, ensuring that people are always able to access the right information in a timely fashion at their point of need is hardly possible without the help of technology and online mechanisms. Therefore, adjustments are necessary to find the methodology that could allow the disadvantages of the former to be offset by the benefits of the latter.\par \par \uc2 A way of doing it could be by starting off with a risk-mapping to know which activity or which department needs the most attention, and conducting a bottom-up approach to know which way of communication works and does not work for them, and why. It is also noteworthy that having general annual training is important, but the necessity of allowing specialized training to be held that is ad-hoc in nature and kept abreast of the current fraud issues, is not to be overlooked - this same idea applies also to the whole communication program.\par \par \uc2 The second and third issues are related to monitoring process and investigative work. Although complaints are not scarce during days of remote working with regard to limited sight in monitoring and investigating, a novel idea is incited: in this new normal era when people are propelled to contribute to data and rely on digital devices, are we not able to take the interpretation of data to a new level that interlinking them will provide information and knowledge that we really need?\par \par \uc2 Truly, here is where technology nowadays plays a big role in making the greatest transition in anti-fraud endeavors: from reactive measures to proactive measures; from reactive investigation to proactive investigation. With the rise of data science and artificial intelligence, anti-fraud fighters have discovered ways to make use of the big data phenomenon, in disrupting criminal activity and detecting fraud as early as possible.\par \par \uc2 Although this avenue is not without stumbling blocks, it is worth exploring. With the technological help, analyzing large data in one sitting ceases to be a dream, automating fraud detection is not a fantasy, and predicting fraud before it occurs is no longer a preposterous idea.\par \par \uc2 At last, the post-pandemic time is not a moment to solely focus on racking up profits after suffering a COVID-19-induced \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturn, but also fighting tooth and nail to ward off fraud even in the greatest unknown.\par \par \uc2 _____________________\par \par \uc2 A holder of the Certified Fraud Examiner credential, deputy director at Bibit Samad Rianto Center and legal advisory director at Awesome Consulting. The views expressed are her own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211101ehb20000h\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
