\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Governments that invest in climate innovation invest in growth\b0\par\par\uc2 1,030 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 November 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Dave Sivaprasad, \uc2 Boston Consulting Group (BCG)\uc2 ,\par \par \uc2 As we head toward the United Nations Climate Change Conference (COP26) this November, countries accounting for almost 70 percent of global emissions have either committed to or are considering net-zero commitments. That said, the path to achieving net-zero is far from obvious.\par \par \uc2 Technological innovation is going to be critical. \uc2 Boston Consulting Group (BCG) \uc2 estimates that existing technologies can eliminate about 25 percent of current emissions, and technologies in early adoption can address another 40 percent. This means that new technologies will need to be developed to address the remaining 35 percent of current annual emissions.\par \par \uc2 Financing this innovation will be key. The world is currently short of between US$90 billion and $210 billion a year in annual investment in climate-altering technology needed to achieve net-zero, according to analysis by BCG and the Global Financial Markets Association (GFMA) on global climate finance requirements.\par \par \uc2 Governments can play a key role to support innovation through targeted investments that progress both the innovation agenda and positively contribute to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. In our latest research, Governments that Invest in Climate Innovation Invest in Growth, we highlight the imperative and the success factors for governments to invest in innovation and unlock new opportunities for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 Innovation investment gap\par \par \uc2 There is already a significant shift underway when it comes to climate-related technology investment.\par \par \uc2 Venture capital and private equity investments in climate innovation have been growing about 14 percent a year since 2016, with most of the funding going into mobility, renewables and waste. Investment totaled about $30 billion in 2019 and $37 billion in 2020. But this is not nearly enough. Our analysis indicates this is as much as $210 billion short of the yearly investments needed in climate-altering technology to reach net zero.\par \par \uc2 Governments as catalysts\par \par \uc2 Since the 1990s, average temperatures in Indonesia have recorded a 0.3 degrees Celsius increase and rainfall has reduced by 2 to 3 percent, making clear the importance of investing to tackle climate change. Ultimately, \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  funding will be required to meet these vital targets, acting as a catalyst to overcome private investment hesitancy triggered by barriers such as \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  returns, lack of track record and payback timeframes.\par \par \uc2 There will be long-term \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  paybacks for governments willing to invest in climate innovation. Climate innovation is a huge opportunity to create value, create new jobs and sources of growth. There is clear evidence that countries can build a sustainable competitive advantage, as China and South Korea did in the last decade with photovoltaic (PV) cells and batteries respectively.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  funding via co-investment and matching mechanisms can help lower risk perception and mobilize increasing venture capital and private equity investments in climate innovation, providing a self-generating benefit for the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Patient, long-term capital can help close current funding gaps by compensating for the impatience of private capital for extended payback cycles and lengthy \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  funding processes.\par \par \uc2 Growing importance of climate innovation funds\par \par \uc2 Climate innovation funds can be a powerful tool in this journey, and one which has seen growing global adoption over recent years. Governments like Japan, Germany, and the United States have announced capital commitments for climate innovation funds that will support the next generation of climate-focused start-ups. The \uc2 European Union\uc2  has also launched a 10-billion euro ($11.55 billion) climate fund to commercialize innovative low-carbon technologies.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has taken important steps to address climate change. It is a supporter of the Kyoto Protocol -- a \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  body put in place to legally approve the target of decreasing carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions by 55 percent from 1990 by industrialized countries.\par \par \uc2 Under the Paris climate change agreement, Indonesia has committed to an unconditional 29 percent reduction in emissions below a business-as-usual (BAU) scenario, up to 41 percent reduction with conditional support. The government has also recently announced ambitions to achieve net-zero by 2060. Renewable energy will play a significant role in this more carbon neutral future, representing a shift away from coal as a major source of energy. Achieving this ambition will require innovative new solutions that meet local needs, such as distributed energy solutions across the country, low carbon mobility solutions or nature-based solutions.\par \par \uc2 Setting up \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector climate innovation funding for success\par \par \uc2 Designing the right climate innovation focus and funding mechanism for a particular country should take into account the ecosystem capabilities of the domestic environment, access to capital and maturity of the ecosystem, and the current carbon-intensity of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Countries should adopt a mission driven approach, focusing efforts that build on a country's natural advantages.\par \par \uc2 We have identified six key success factors in delivering an effective climate innovation fund.\par \par \uc2 * Set a clear investment focus that concentrates investment in select areas.\par \par \uc2 * Carve out a complementary market role that focuses investments on underserved segments to mobilize private capital and avoid direct competition with private investments.\par \par \uc2 * Coordinate fund activities and \b \highlight22\uc2 public policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to provide the required demand-side \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  via policies and regulations.\par \par \uc2 * Build an experienced team with a demonstrable track record and a strong partner network.\par \par \uc2 * Provide transparency by reporting impact, with highly visible communication and engagement efforts that create convincing proof points.\par \par \uc2 * Establish a strong and recognizable brand that signals commitment to climate innovation and to being an attractive co-investor for private-sector funds.\par \par \uc2 The time is now\par \par \uc2 There is wider recognition that the severity and pace of climate impact may be underestimated and we are running out of time to course-correct. Many of the solutions are known and need to be implemented quickly and at scale. There are also solutions yet to be discovered, and there is an urgent need to innovate and to ensure that these innovations are well-funded. Governments that want to make an impact must target funds accordingly, and in doing so, unlock the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  benefits of a more climate-resistant and climate-competitive country.\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par \uc2 Boston Consulting Group\uc2  is the Consultancy Partner for the 2021 UN Climate Conference. Dave Sivaprasad, managing director and partner, is SEA leader for climate and sustainability, \uc2 Boston Consulting Group\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Document 