\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: COVID-19 downward trend brings hope for retail sector recovery\b0\par\par\uc2 1,255 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 November 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Nadia Kusuma Dewi, Mandiri, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Daily COVID-19 cases in Indonesia continue to show a downward trend. The daily addition of cases, as of Monday, amounted to 244 cases, which has decreased significantly compared with its peak of 56,757 cases on July 15. At the same time, the progress of the COVID-19 vaccination program is quite encouraging. As of Monday, at least 125.4 million people, 60.2 percent of the total population, had received the first dose of vaccine.\par \par \uc2 The conducive situation has finally prompted the government to relax the rules for restricting people's mobility, one of which is related to the retail sector, and in particular shopping centers and mall. The mobility relaxation, supported by the recovery of purchasing power in line with the gradual \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery and increasing consumer confidence, will drive the retail sector.\par \par \uc2 In the Home Ministerial Instruction No. 57/2021, which regulates the implementation of restrictions for community activities (PPKM) in the Java-Bali region, more regencies and cities have entered PPKM Level 1. In this \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , activities at shopping centers, malls or trade centers in PPKM Level 1 areas are opened with a maximum capacity of 100 percent with operating hours until 10 p.m. local time.\par \par \uc2 Supermarkets and hypermarkets within shopping centers are allowed to open with 100 percent visitor capacity. Meanwhile, restaurants and caf?s located inside shopping centers are allowed to open with strict health protocols until 10 p.m. local time with a maximum capacity of 75 percent. Children under 12 years old are allowed to enter the shopping center provided that they are accompanied by their parents.\par \par \uc2 Last but not least, all visitors and shopping center employees are required to use the PeduliLindungi application to ensure that everyone who enters the shopping center is healthy in order to prevent the spread of COVID-19. This \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  takes effect from Nov. 2-15, and will then be reviewed in line with the development of COVID-19 cases.\par \par \uc2 The opening of mall capacity to 100 percent was very welcomed by retail sector players and the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . People go to shopping centers or malls nowadays not only for shopping, but also for refreshing and gathering with family, friends and business relations. The Google Mobility Index shows that people's mobility to retail and recreational areas has been increasing since the beginning of August\par \par \uc2 after PPKM Darurat (emergency restriction) enforcement ended. Mobility to retail and recreation areas since October has even surpassed the position in June when there was a relatively large movement of people after Lebaran.\par \par \uc2 In our opinion, the opening up of shopping centers and malls to 100 percent capacity is appropriate at this time. We see the 100 percent opening of malls in PPKM Level 1 areas as an opportunity to increase sales turnover this year after the recovery that occurred in the second quarter was hampered by the surge in COVID-19 cases that prompted the government to implement the PPKM Darurat \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Several factors act as a positive catalyst for the growth of the retail sector in the fourth quarter.\par \par \uc2 First, increased \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity will improve people's purchasing power. The IHS Markit Indonesia Manufacturing Purchasing Managers Index (PMI) jumped to a record peak of 57.2 in October, from 52.2 in the previous month, indicating that companies continue to increase their business expansion.\par \par \uc2 Second, the consumer confidence index in October returned to the optimistic zone -- above 100 -- at 113.4, up from 95.5 a month earlier. Increased consumer confidence coupled with a recovery in purchasing power will further encourage \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Third, the celebration of Christmas and New Year which is usually followed by many year-end discounts will boost retail sales.\par \par \uc2 Fourth, the government's decision to cut the number of collective leave days at the end of the year, which will most likely be followed by restriction regulations on people's mobility to travel outside the city, will likely be used by the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  to go to malls with their families.\par \par \uc2 However, we also see that the opening of shopping centers or malls with a capacity of 100 percent is a big challenge for the retail sector to prove that it will not be a source of the spread of new COVID-19 cases going forward.\par \par \uc2 We strongly emphasize that the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of opening malls with 100 percent capacity must also be accompanied by strict monitoring and efforts to mitigate the potential spike in COVID-19 cases.\par \par \uc2 For mall building managers and tenants, the implementation of strict health protocols to provide a secure and convenient shopping experience for consumers should be the main priority. The mall building managers must ensure the cleanliness of the retail space and shopping equipment as well as \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  facilities. The potential for a surge in mall visitors in line with the allowing of 100 percent mall capacity must be anticipated.\par \par \uc2 In addition, retail space arrangement that supports consumers to keep their distance from one another and optimizing the use of mall open space should also be considered by mall building managers.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, the use of the PeduliLindungi application also must be carried out strictly. We still often see several shopping centers in suburban cities that are just displaying the QR codes as a formality, without monitoring the eligibility of incoming visitors.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, from the retailer side, the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of opening 100 percent mall capacity creates opportunities as well as competitive challenges, especially when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and people's purchasing power have not fully recovered. In this case, retailers must have a strategy to win the competition and adapt to consumer behavior during the pandemic. Among other things, determining the promotion strategy according to the target market and their shopping product subcategories.\par \par \uc2 Although currently consumers are still prioritizing products related to basic needs, health and hygiene, the Mandiri \b \highlight22\uc2 Spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  Index (MSI) shows a different proportion for shopping product subcategories between income groups. MSI conclude that higher income group spend more on household product at 16.4 percent, than middle income at 11.4 and lower income a 10.2 percent.\par \par \uc2 We see that the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  regarding COVID-19 cases is still quite high. This will be a major risk factor in the future. The potential for a spike in cases caused by the emergence of new variants can still occur. This can encourage the government to reimpose strict PPKM rules at any time, resulting in a hindered recovery of the retail sector as people tend to hold back on \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  as consumer confidence and purchasing power decline.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, we support retailers to continue developing omnichannel sales strategy. In addition to reaching wider market access and adapting to changing consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  patterns in the digital era, retailers can better absorb physical store stock with online channels. Retailers can also optimize online channels for promotion so that consumers have a fairly clear picture before they decide to go to the offline store to buy the products they want.\par \par \uc2 In sum, the recovery of the retail sector in the future will be largely determined by the mobility restriction \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , people's purchasing power and consumer confidence. We all hope that the 100 percent opening of malls will be able to go hand in hand with efforts to control COVID-19 cases so that a balance between the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector and the health sector can be realized. This is important in an effort to accelerate Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery.\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par \uc2 Senior industry analyst, Bank Mandiri\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211109ehba0000b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
