\par\par \uc2 INTERNATIONAL NEWS\par \b \uc2 APEC MINISTERS ISSUE JOINT STATEMENT ON RESPONDING TO COVID-19 CRISIS\b0\par\par\uc2 296 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 November 2021\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Yuni Arisandy Sinaga\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - Ministers from 21 \uc2 APEC\uc2  member economies concluded the 2021 APEC Ministerial Meeting on Tuesday (Nov 9) by issuing a joint statement on responding to the COVID-19 crisis.\par \par \uc2 The joint statement describes collective \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  commitments to be implemented by \uc2 APEC\uc2  economies over the next year to expedite and ensure a resilient and sustainable long-term recovery, with trade, inclusion, sustainability, innovation, and digitalization as drivers of quality growth, according to a release issued at the APEC Ministerial Meeting and received here on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Those collective \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  commitments entailed continued support and response to COVID-19, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and trade policies that bolster recovery, increasing inclusion and sustainability for recovery, pursuing innovation and a digitally-enabled recovery, and strengthening \uc2 APEC\uc2  as an institution.\par \par \uc2 The joint statement also encompasses two annexes on the report of the APEC Services Competitiveness Roadmap review and a reference list of Environmental and Environmentally Related Services.\par \par \uc2 Such a joint statement was made by \uc2 APEC\uc2  ministers on account of the persistent and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  nature of the pandemic and its unceasing impact on the health, well-being, and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prosperity of the region and resulting in estimated losses to the tune of US$1.2 trillion from unrealized \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities as a consequence of border and travel restrictions.\par \par \uc2 The 2021 APEC Ministerial Meeting was co-chaired by New Zealand Minister of Foreign Affairs Nanaia Mahuta and Minister for Trade and Export Growth \uc2 Damien O\u8217\'20\'19Connor\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 It will be followed by the continuation of the 2021 APEC CEO Summit on November 11 and the culmination of the 2021 APEC \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Leaders\u8217\'20\'19 Meeting on November 12.\par \par \uc2 (T.Y012/B/H-FDH/H-FDH) 10-11-2021 16:44:51\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020211110ehba000m9\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 The Lurking Risk behind Alluring Optimism\b0\par\par\uc2 631 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 November 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 THE de-escalation of the Covid-19 pandemic in Indonesia has given rise to optimism that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will recover more quickly. Markets, small shops, restaurants, and malls are starting to operate normally in accordance to the relaxation in mobility restriction. Household consumption, one of the main engines for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, is rising.\par \par \uc2 That optimism is reflected in the consumer confidence index which has been in its highest level since March 2021. Consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  throughout October increased by five percent compared to the previous month.\par \par \uc2 The jump in exports also pushed \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. The prices of Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s various main export commodities, such as palm oil and coal have been sharply ascending in the past few months. The trade balance surplus is soaring.\par \par \uc2 That positive sentiment has certainly helped the stock market. The Jakarta Composite Stock Index, which reflects the movement of all stocks in the \uc2 Indonesian Stock Exchange\uc2 , recorded its highest all-time number at 6,691 on Thursday, November 11. Foreign investors joined back into Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s stock market. Since the start of the year until November 12, net foreign capital inflow reached Rp32 trillion.\par \par \uc2 It seems that the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slump is over. Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, which was stunted at 3.51 percent in Q3-2021, is likely to accelerate in the last quarter of the year. However, investors need to be more vigilant when optimism sprouts. How strong is the driving force for growth, and how long will that force last? These are some important questions to be considered. Both the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation and the financial market are still full of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . There are several risk factors that can quickly reverse the situation.\par \par \uc2 The rising inflation in the United States is the most serious threat. In October, yearly inflation in the US reached 6.2 percent. This was far above market estimates and the highest in the last 31 years. Such a strong inflation can push The Federal Reserve to increase \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  sooner.\par \par \uc2 Yes, The Fed Chair Jay Powell promised that his institution would be more patient when it comes to determining interest rate \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . There are targets that must be met before the interest rate rises: full employment and an average inflation of two percent. But with yearly inflation already at 6.2 percent, the pressure on The Fed to adjust \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  is growing stronger.\par \par \uc2 An increase in Fed rates, especially if it happens in the first half of next year, will reverse the positive sentiments that blanket the Indonesian market. Even now, the market is still in the process of adjusting itself to other Fed policies, mainly the reduction of liquidity injection into the market, also known as tapering, starting from this November. The rise of \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  that come rather close to the tapering will become a double blow that can send markets reeling.\par \par \uc2 The other risk factor is the Christmas-New Year holidays. Not only will they create a jump in demand that pushes growth, the increased mobility in the long holiday also risks the spread of Covid-19. If it happens, the government will have no choice but to re-implement various activity restrictions. \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth can slow down once again.\par \par \uc2 Investors must also seriously weigh whether Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s export commodities will enjoy high prices for a considerable period of time. If the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is overburdened with inflation, the market mechanism will work in due time. Growth will slow down and the prices of those various commodities will be adjusted.\par \par \uc2 No one can predict when the price correction will happen. But when dollar liquidity is drying up and \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  are rising, commodity exporters and investors in the financial market must prepare to face a price collapse.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/11/15/787421/787421_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020211115ehbe0000e\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
