\par\par \b \uc2 BI to remain dovish until late 2022, but no more rate cuts\b0\par\par\uc2 Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 706 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 November 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) \uc2 is to hold its loose monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  stance a little longer than initially expected but without a rate cut as a balance between the country's muted inflation and \uc2 United States Federal Reserve\uc2 's accelerated taper plans.\par \par \uc2 BI initially planned to keep a pro-growth stance this year and then shift to a pro-stability stance next year. The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has maintained the seven-day reverse repo rate (7DRRR) at a record-low 3.5 percent since February in a bid to support \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery.\par \par \uc2 However, BI Governor \uc2 Perry Warjiyo\uc2  said on Wednesday that the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  would only reduce liquidity in banks starting 2022 and hold the current low rate "until there are signs of early rise in inflation".\par \par \uc2 Economists specifically expect BI to hold the rate until the second half of 2022 with a gradual easing of other monetary support.\par \par \uc2 "The pressure on stability will not be huge yet in the first half of 2022, supported by commodity prices that will stay high amid the gradual \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery as the government carefully eases [mobility curbs]," Bank Mandiri economist Faisal Rachman told The Jakarta Post in a text message on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 "In the second half, domestic demand will strengthen and it will raise inflation and imports, so stabilization from the monetary side will be necessary."\par \par \uc2 Economists at \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2  forecasted on Nov. 18 that BI would raise the benchmark rate by 50 basis points to 4 percent in the second half of next year. The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to reduce its bond-buying program first before the rate hikes.\par \par \uc2 The Fed's accelerated taper complicates BI's efforts to stimulate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Domestic inflation remains low, yet further lowering the 7DRRR risks triggering capital outflows, which might depreciate the rupiah.\par \par \uc2 The Fed recently signaled speeding up rate hikes to 2022 from 2023 in response to soaring inflation in the US, where the consumer price index hit a 31-year high of 6.2 percent in October due to domestic demand exceeding supply.\par \par \uc2 In contrast, Statistics Indonesia (BPS) data shows that inflation stood at a mere 1.66 percent in October, lower than BI's target range of between 2 and 4 percent.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has seen low inflation this year compared to other economies due to the Southeast Asian country's relatively weak domestic demand recovery and stable rupiah exchange rate.\par \par \uc2 "A rate cut is unlikely, I think. The room is limited," said Josua Pardede, the chief economist at publicly listed \uc2 Bank Permata\uc2 . "Even if inflation stayed muted until next year, for example, BI would likely maintain [the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate] instead of slashing it again."\par \par \uc2 Since the Fed's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  direction could be anticipated, the remaining \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  over BI's rate decision were whether or not producers passed on higher input costs to consumers and whether pent-up demand would rise significantly, he said.\par \par \uc2 BI expects inflation to fall within the target at the end of 2021 and 2022. This is in line with BI's expectation that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would continue to improve in the fourth quarter, as reflected in the leading indicators, such as factory activity and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  mobility.\par \par \uc2 Katrina Ell, a senior Asia-Pacific economist at financial intelligence firm Moody's Analytics, said while BI could lower the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate further, such rate cuts would be unlikely given the country's vulnerability to capital outflows.\par \par \uc2 "The preferred course of action if the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  needs additional \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be from additional \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  support that can provide more targeted support to the weaker pockets," Ell told the Post in an email.\par \par \uc2 Ell added that a key input into the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  would be what happened in the US, where inflation had picked up more dramatically than expected. If the Fed normalizes its \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  earlier, it will likely nudge BI to also move sooner to maintain financial market stability.\par \par \uc2 The Finance Ministry recently lowered its 2021 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  forecast to between 5.18 and 5.45 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP), far lower than the expected 5.7 percent of GDP, signaling stronger \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  standing for 2022.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211125ehbq00009\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
