\par\par \b \uc2 New Analysis:  \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty \highlight\uc2  looms after Job Creation Law declared unconstitutional\b0\par\par\uc2 1,002 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 November 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Rendy Dwi Novalianto, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The Constitutional Court delivered shocking news on Thursday by declaring that the main item of the reform agenda of President Joko "Jokowi" Widodo's administration, the omnibus Job Creation Law, is partly unconstitutional. This is a historic decision as for the first time the court has declared the unconstitutionality of a law based on significant procedural violations that occurred during its \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  deliberation.\par \par \uc2 There were three main points that court ruled as infringements of the law-formulation procedure: the omnibus law approach is still alien to Indonesia's law-making procedure; the draft that President Jokowi signed in November 2020 was not the same as the law passed by the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; and the deliberation process lacked meaningful \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  participation.\par \par \uc2 The court decision also demonstrates clearly that a key tenet of Indonesia's democracy is alive and well -- with the checks and balances between an independent judiciary and the executive clearly on display through this decision. This is particularly important given that many observers have questioned the Constitutional Court's independence after the hasty revision of the Constitutional Court Law that extended the term of all sitting judges last year, believing that this illustrated the influence of the Jokowi administration over the court.\par \par \uc2 While we should applaud the court's decision, which reaffirms Indonesia's functioning democracy, we should also assess the impact of the ruling on the investment climate in the country.\par \par \uc2 The Job Creation Law itself is an unprecedented reform, the most ambitious and significant reform to improve investment and the business climate since the 1998 reforms. This is Jokowi's signature achievement as president and is seen by Jokowi as indispensable to improving the country's investment competitiveness vis-?-vis its neighbors in East Asia.\par \par \uc2 Since its enactment last year, the law has generated significant interest from international investors. The Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) recorded a year-on-year investment increase between 10 and 15 percent until the third quarter of this year, with inbound investment in 2021 already surpassing the total inbound investment in 2019.\par \par \uc2 The rise can be observed coming significantly from domestic investors, but the interest expressed by international investors has increased significantly despite major challenges from the COVID-19 pandemic and restrictions on travel to Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 In a nutshell, the Job Creation Law has begun to improve perceptions of Indonesia's competitiveness for foreign direct investment (FDI) flows in Asia-Pacific. In some sectors, such as manufacturing, information and communication technology, and energy, the omnibus investment reforms, especially the elimination of the notorious Negative Investment List (DNI) has moved Indonesia from a mediocre investment destination to one of the most attractive investment destinations in Asia Pacific.\par \par \uc2 While Indonesia still comes up short behind Vietnam, the reforms are significant for Indonesia and clearly demonstrate the government's strong commitment to improving its investment and business climate.\par \par \uc2 So, what is the impact of the court ruling on Indonesia's investment and business climate? The short answer is the decision could revive perceptions of significant legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  for investment in Indonesia. Although the court declared that the existing law and its implementing regulations are still legally binding, it set a deadline of two years for the House and the government to revise the formulation procedure of the Job Creation Law, otherwise the 78 laws that the Job Creation Law revised will come into effect again.\par \par \uc2 This means the fate of the current reforms under the Job Creation Law will heavily depend on how fast and serious the House and the government can be in fixing the unconstitutionality of the law. Two years is a short period for revising laws, as usually law formulation can take between nine months to more than a year to finish, and many efforts have dragged on for years because of a lack of political consensus.\par \par \uc2 However, the Jokowi administration has been shown to be able to pass its priority \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  in a short period, notably the \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  Harmonization Law, which only took six months to finish.\par \par \uc2 The second \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  comes from the court's order for the government to stop issuing new policies and regulations that would have been designed to implement reforms called for in the Job Creation Law. This means the government is no longer able to issue technical regulations, guidelines or take a new action to implement the Job Creation Law.\par \par \uc2 While existing implementing regulations and procedures still stand, it creates major \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the government is still in the process of adjusting numerous technical regulations with the Job Creation law.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, the court's decision could also delay the establishment of new special \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  zones (KEK), full implementation of the Risk-Based Approach business-licensing system under the online single submission (OSS) scheme, while also putting into question the legality of labor \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  such as the annual minimum wage \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and the sustainability of investment in the sectors that the Job Creation Law has liberalized, including 245 business fields that the implementing regulations of the law opened to 100-percent foreign investment, such as power plants, e-commerce, pharmaceuticals, oil and gas refinery and many other sectors.\par \par \uc2 The future of these liberalized business fields will depend on the capability of the government and House in meeting the court's deadline. Otherwise, the old ownership cap in the 2016 DNI will return.\par \par \uc2 While we wait the next steps from both the House and the government, one thing is for sure, President Jokowi himself should reassure the business community that the government is committed to resolving this problem and will protect existing and upcoming investment in Indonesia. Otherwise, Indonesia's reputation as a country working hard to improve its attractiveness to investors could suffer a big setback, and failure to meet the two-year deadline could result not only in more \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  but also lengthy and costly international arbitration procedures.\par \par \uc2 __________________\par \par \uc2 A senior analyst at Bower Group Asia. These views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211126ehbr00003\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Instant Relief Fund\b0\par\par\uc2 1,983 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 November 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 FANNY Chotimah could not stay in Jakarta for long. On Wednesday night, November 24, she immediately boarded the Argo Lawu train home to Solo, Central Java, after signing a commitment and cooperation agreement with the ministry of tourism and creative \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  the same morning. \u8220\'20\'1CThursday morning I will arrive in Solo, and start shooting at noon,\u8221\'20\'1D Fanny told Tempo, Wednesday, November 24.\par \par \uc2 Time was not on her hands. Kembang Gula Foundation, a film community in Solo that she leads, was set to receive production funding assistance from the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery (PEN) program for the film industry. The problem was, Fanny and her small team only had two weeks to complete a documentary called Riwayatmu Kini (Your History, Now), which had been approved to receive the funding.\par \par \uc2 The first term of PEN assistance funds will be disbursed on December 1. After that, they must report the use of funds and production progress as the term for the second disbursement on December 10. All beneficiaries of this program must submit a narrative and financial accountability report by December 15.\par \par \uc2 Film workers during the signing ceremony of the government assistance cooperation agreement for the promotion of Indonesian films, at the Morrissey Hotel, Jakarta, October 25. Ministry of Tourism and Creative \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2 Fortunately, the shooting of a documentary on keroncong\u8212\'20\'14an Indonesian musical style that typically makes use of a ukulele-like instrument\u8212\'20\'14that Fanny offered had actually started in early November. \u8220\'20\'1CWe had been doing research since October,\u8221\'20\'1D said Fanny, who previously directed You and I, winner of the best feature-length documentary award at the 2020 Indonesian Film Festival.\par \par \uc2 However, the movie-making process, including short documentaries, takes quite a long time. Ideally, Fanny said, it would take two to three months to reach the finalization stage of production. \u8220\'20\'1CBut effectively we have two weeks, so everything has to be done at the same time otherwise we won\u8217\'20\'19t make the deadline,\u8221\'20\'1D said Fanny, who also stated that the PEN assistance is something that the film community has been waiting for a long time.\par \par \uc2 The Kembang Gula Foundation is one of 56 production houses and film communities that received film-making assistance from the PEN program. They consist of 23 production houses and 33 film communities that will work on 29 short films and 27 short documentaries. Each production house and community received Rp250 million in assistance.\par \par \uc2 In addition to the production scheme, there are two other schemes the government prepared to assist the film industry: promotion and pre-production for feature films and documentaries. A total of 22 films will receive promotional assistance worth Rp1.5 billion each. The pre-production assistance funds will be distributed to 50 production houses for 88 film projects worth Rp860 million each.\par \par \uc2 Production process of the film Riwayatmu Kini (Your History, Now) in Solo, Central Java, November 25. Kembang Gula Doc.\par \par \uc2 The films Paranoia, Cinta Bete, Cadet 1947, Yowis Ben 3, and Akhirat: A Love Story were among the recipients of promotional assistance from the PEN for the movie industry. The scheme was designed to help promote Indonesian films slated for release this year or early next year.\par \par \uc2 Initially, a promotional scheme was prepared for 40 feature films. Registration was open from October 1 to 10. However, the curation process only passed 22 films from 48 registered production houses. \u8220\'20\'1CMany were unprepared to submit (the proposal), plus we are also trying to strictly curate incoming proposals,\u8221\'20\'1D said Edwin Nazir, one of the curators for the promotion scheme.\par \par \uc2 Shanty Harmayn, the producer of the film Akhirat: A Love Story, said her production house really needed the PEN fund to promote the film amid the Covid-19 pandemic. \u8220\'20\'1CIt doesn't matter how much. Every single help we need,\u8221\'20\'1D Shanty told Tempo on November 26.\par \par \uc2 President Joko Widodo (right) with the Minister of Education, Culture, Research, and Technology Nadiem Anwar Makarim at the 2021 Indonesian Film Festival (FFI) Citra Award night at the JCC, November 10. Tempo/STR/Nurdiansah\par \par \uc2 Shanty has huge box office expectations for Akhirat: A Love Story. The film is set to hit theaters on December 2. The problem is, cinemas have been empty for a long time because of the pandemic. And now, calculations about the audience target\u8212\'20\'14usually projected by the promotional costs incurred\u8212\'20\'14have become even more \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \u8220\'20\'1CYou have to prepare (for the numbers to be) below expectations. That is a consequence that must be faced in times of a pandemic,\u8221\'20\'1D said Shanty, who is also the chief executive of Base Entertainment.\par \par \uc2 Producer Mira Lesmana, who worked on Paranoia, said the same thing. The cost of promoting a film is usually equal to, or even double, the cost of production. Moreover, there are many additional costs in film production during a pandemic, such as the cost for routine tests and quarantine during filming. \u8220\'20\'1CThis could be a factor causing moviemaking costs to be more expensive during the pandemic,\u8221\'20\'1D Mira said.\par \par \uc2 The results of the pre-production scheme assistance program from the PEN for film were announced on Friday, November 26. The funds are allocated for four pre-production components: scenario development, storyboard development, site survey, and pre-production workshop. With the completion of all curation for the three aid schemes, the government is estimated to use only Rp122.68 billion from the Rp266 billion PEN \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocated for the movie industry.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 THE financial aid for the film industry through the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery program was not planned at the beginning of the 2021 \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  preparation. Starting from a chat on the Clubhouse platform, film industry players who are members of 14 associations sent a letter to President Joko Widodo in March, saying that they needed assistance. The government also held a number of meetings with representatives of several associations, including the Indonesian Film Agency (BPI) and the Indonesian Film Producers Association (Aprofi).\par \par \uc2 At first, the discussion narrowed down to a plan to roll out an aid scheme that focuses on bringing back moviegoers to theaters. Cinemas have been the main contributor to the film industry\u8217\'20\'19s revenue, accounting for 90 percent. But since the Covid-19 pandemic hit Indonesia, theaters have been suspended, and their revenues fall 97 percent with only nine film titles shown throughout 2020. Before the pandemic, in 2019 Indonesian cinemas played 129 film titles watched by around 51 million people, putting the Indonesian movie industry in the top 10 of the global film market.\par \par \uc2 CINEMA RESCUE FUNDS\par \par \uc2 THE Covid-19 pandemic hit the cinema business, the biggest contributor to film industry income, right from the start. The national film industry is also affected, even though the digital era provides other ways for distribution. After a long time, the film communities\u8217\'20\'19 demand for the government to save the movie industry finally begun to receive answers. The latest one is that the government has allocated a national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery (PEN) funds for films, which will be rolled out through three aid schemes.\par \par \uc2 *) The results from the curation team established by the tourism and creative \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministry\par \par \uc2 TEXT: AISHA SHAIDRA\par \par \uc2 SOURCES: MINISTRY OF TOURISM AND CREATIVE \b \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMY\b0 \highlight\uc2 , PROCESSED BY TEMPO\par \par \uc2 That is the reason why some time ago the \u8220\'20\'1CBack to the Cinema\u8221\'20\'1D campaign was launched. In the beginning, several assistance schemes were designed. One of them includes a buy-one-get-one-ticket program or the curation of a tentpole film\u8212\'20\'14a production that costs a lot but has the potential to bring in a lot of viewers. That way, film producers would return to work and are willing to show their work in theaters, and would immediately get funds to work on new films. \u8220\'20\'1CSo, there are no funds that can be directly received by individuals or corporations. Everything is spent again for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 ,\u8221\'20\'1D said Chand Parwez Servia, Chairman of the Indonesian Film Agency, on Friday, November 19.\par \par \uc2 But before it was approved, the scheme\u8217\'20\'19s drafts fell apart after the government imposed tighter restrictions on \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities (PPKM). As cinemas closed, the aid scheme to purchase tickets was canceled.\par \par \uc2 Recently, a number of new schemes have emerged within the government\u8217\'20\'19s internal scope along with ongoing discussions of aid plans for the film industry. The PEN film assistance, with the schemes for fiction films and short documentaries production, was one of the most recent. Initially, the production-assistance scheme was designed to help the production of fiction movies and feature-length documentaries. However, the initial scheme was changed because film-making is a process that could take up to six months. It would be impossible for the crew to finish this year, which was the requirement.\par \par \uc2 In addition, the provision of funds for producing fictions and short documentaries, mostly made by film communities, is considered more suitable with the principle PEN funds\u8217\'20\'19 allotment. \u8220\'20\'1CThe focus of the PEN fund is that it is for those who are most vulnerable to being affected significantly by the pandemic,\u8221\'20\'1D said Raden Pardede, First Executive Secretary of the Covid-19 Mitigation and the National \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Recovery Committee, on November 18.\par \par \uc2 And so the long discussions between the tourism and the creative \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministry and the finance ministry in June, August, and lastly last October ended with three assistance schemes. An official from the tourism ministry who participated in the discussions said that the PEN fund assistance scheme took a long time to discuss because it had gone through several modifications. Several schemes were not approved because they conflicted with the finance ministry\u8217\'20\'19s regulations. \u8220\'20\'1CThe three existing schemes were decided based on components that can be financed by government assistance,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Changes in the assistance scheme divided the opinions of film industry players. A number of well-known directors chose not to participate when the tourism ministry opened registration for this PEN film assistance program. They not only questioned the change in the aid scheme, but also the unclear calculations used to determine the amount of aid in each new scheme. \u8220\'20\'1CSome chose to participate, rather than have the funds falling into unknown hands,\u8221\'20\'1D said a film director who wished to remain anonymous.\par \par \uc2 Deddy Mizwar, actor and founder of production house Demi Gisela Citra Sinema, was one of those reluctant to participate. He sees the PEN film assistance scheme as not having a clear direction or purpose. He thinks that aid programs should be focusing on attracting people to the cinema. \u8220\'20\'1CIf the problem is bringing audiences to the cinema, promote cinema safety, promote films that are of really high quality,\u8221\'20\'1D Deddy said on November 27.\par \par \uc2 Deddy is also worried about the accountability for the use of PEN funds in these schemes. With the promotion scheme, he said, it is unclear whether the aid program will be successful in bringing moviegoers back. The same goes for the pre-production scheme, which he said is not very clear on how the government will ensure that the film projects funded will actually be produced. \u8220\'20\'1CThere is no such strategy, it seems sporadic, (the important thing is) as long as the money is out,\u8221\'20\'1D said Deddy, who is also the chairman of the Indonesian Film Companies Association (PPFI).\par \par \uc2 Cecep Rukendi, the Tourism and Creative \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Ministry\u8217\'20\'19s Communication Bureau acting head, said the government considered the three final schemes would meet the level of urgency and the maximum benefit value. The level of urgency and benefits in question is that, in a short and limited time, it can absorb labor and drive the Indonesian film industry\u8217\'20\'19s ecosystem.\par \par \uc2 The government, according to Cecep, has also arranged mechanisms to ensure that the PEN program funds are maintained and right on target, from the upstream to downstream sector. \u8220\'20\'1CA number of institutions are also involved to supervise and assist the recipients of the aid program,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/11/28/788472/788472_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/11/28/788473/788473_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/11/28/788474/788474_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/11/28/788475/788475_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view 