\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b \uc2 2022 STATE  \highlight22\uc2 BUDGET \highlight\uc2  FOCUSES ON SIX MAIN POLICIES: PRESIDENT JOKOWI\b0\par\par\uc2 468 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 November 2021\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - The 2022 State Revenue and \b \highlight22\uc2 Expenditure Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  prioritizes six policies, with the main focus remaining COVID-19 control, President \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2 (Jokowi) has stated.\par \par \uc2 "We will focus on six main policies. First, to continue to control COVID-19 while still prioritizing the health sector," he said at the Merdeka Palace, Jakarta, on Monday.\par \par \uc2 He delivered the statement during an event attended by cabinet members and other state officials.\par \par \uc2 "Second (focus), maintaining the sustainability of social protection programs for the poor and vulnerable," President Jokowiinformed.\par \par \uc2 Third, improving or developing human resources to make them superior, he said. Fourth, pushing for the development of infrastructure and encouraging adaptation to technology, he disclosed. Fifth, strengthening \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  decentralization to increase and distribute welfare among the regions, he added.\par \par \uc2 "The sixth is to continue budgeting reform by implementing "zero-based budgeting" so that \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is more efficient," he remarked.\par \par \uc2 In 2022, ministers and regional heads must continue to prepare themselves to face the risk of the COVID-19 pandemic, which is still posing a threat to the global community, including Indonesia, President Jokowi said.\par \par \uc2 "\b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the health and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fields must be our basis for planning and implementing programs," he said.\par \par \uc2 The 2022 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  was designed and will be implemented in a responsive, anticipatory, and flexible manner, in response to the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  of 2022, he explained.\par \par \uc2 "Always innovate and anticipate various changes that occur while maintaining good governance," he remarked.\par \par \uc2 The President said that the 2022 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  has a crucial role.\par \par \uc2 "As the G20 Presidency, we must demonstrate our ability to deal with climate change, especially reductions in emissions and the movement to develop the environment in a sustainable manner. We must show real action toward (realizing) a green and sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he added.\par \par \uc2 The 2022 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been stipulated in Law Number 6 of 2021, which came into force on October 27, 2021. The law regulates the 2022 state revenue and \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Law Number 6 of 2021 states that the 2022 state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  includes a planned state revenue of Rp1,846.1 trillionand state \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  of Rp2,714.2 trillion.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  reached IDR 868 trillion or 4.85 percent of gross domestic product, while the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  was targeted at 4.85 percent of GDP.\par \par \uc2 The projected \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2022 is estimated at 5.2 percent, while the poverty rate is expected to decline to 8.5\u8211\'20\'139 percent.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, the open unemployment rate is expected to range between 5.5\u8211\'20\'136.3 percent, and the inequality ratio to fall to 0.376\u8211\'20\'13 0.378. Meanwhile, the human development index is targeted to increase to 73.41\u8211\'20\'1373.