\par\par \b \uc2 Jokowi assures investors after court rules passing of jobs law unconstitutional\b0\par\par\uc2 Marchio Irfan Gorbiano and Dzulfiqar Fathur Rahman, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 740 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 November 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 1\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 President Joko "Jokowi" Widodo has promised businesses that their investments will not be affected by the recent Constitutional Court ruling on the Job Creation Law, saying his administration would immediately work on a do-over of the lawmaking process.\par \par \uc2 The procedure of passing the law -- the key \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  item in the President's ambitious yet controversial reform agenda -- was recently declared unconstitutional by the court, which also ruled that the government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  must start the lawmaking process again from scratch within two years. If they fail to do so, the law will be permanently repealed and all the previous laws it has replaced must be reinstated. In the meantime, the law remains effective.\par \par \uc2 "In a democratic nation that is based on the rule of law, the government respects and will immediately implement what has been ruled by the Constitutional Court," Jokowi said in a press conference on Monday, in his first official response to Thursday's ruling.\par \par \uc2 "I have instructed the coordinating ministers and other related ministers to immediately follow up on the ruling as soon as possible."\par \par \uc2 The ruling was a major blow to Jokowi's bid to cut red tape and bring in investment to Indonesia. Economists feared it would bring back business \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially as interest from foreign investors has been steadily growing in Indonesia as an attractive investment destination.\par \par \uc2 Jokowi, however, gave an assurance that the ruling clearly said the law was still in effect pending the lawmaking do-over.\par \par \uc2 "All material and substance in the law and [existing implementing] regulations remain in effect without any provisions being revoked or declared invalid by the court," he said. "Therefore, I assure businesses and investors, both domestic and international, that the investments that have been made and investments that are being processed and will be in process are safe and secure."\par \par \uc2 This, he said, did not affect his commitment to easing the process of doing business, which will eventually create jobs.\par \par \uc2 Dubbed an omnibus as it was drafted to revise and combine 78 laws into 1,000 pages of \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the Job Creation Law was passed in October last year. The government said more than 43,000 regulations needed to be streamlined in order to improve the nation's competitiveness in the region.\par \par \uc2 But the court found that the process of drafting the jobs law was flawed because the Constitution mandates that lawmaking be carried out in accordance with prevailing procedures laid in the 2011 law on the drafting of laws and regulations, which does not recognize such a concept as an omnibus law. The court said the jobs law deliberation also lacked transparency and denied \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  participation.\par \par \uc2 Parts of the law, meanwhile, have been viewed by labor and environmental groups as detrimental to labor rights and environmental protections.\par \par \uc2 Coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister \uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2  said the ruling did not cancel out the impact of the jobs law, such as the operations of the Indonesian Investment Authority (INA) because the government issued the implementing \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  prior to the ruling.\par \par \uc2 He said it also would not affect the four newly established special \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  zones (SEZs), which have lured Rp 90 trillion (US$6.2 billion) worth of investment commitments, or the changes to labor and wage laws.\par \par \uc2 The new online single submission (OSS), which streamlines the business-licensing process, also remains operational and it will still be used by the government to process new licenses or the extension of existing ones.\par \par \uc2 For micro, small and medium enterprises, Airlangga said, it meant that the current relaxation in obtaining licenses, as well as certain facilities to get halal certificates and the ones that allow the government to buy their products and services for official state procurement were maintained so far.\par \par \uc2 Since the start of its implementation on Aug. 4, the OSS has issued nearly 380,000 licenses, of which an overwhelming majority are for micro enterprises.\par \par \uc2 "Next, the government will write a letter to the House speakership to list the jobs law revision as a priority in the 2022 National \b \highlight22\uc2 Legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  Program [Prolegnas]," Airlangga said in a press briefing on Monday.\par \par \uc2 Coordinating Legal, Political and Security Affairs Minister Mahfud MD, meanwhile, said the government was committed to completing the revision sooner than the deadline set by the court. (dis)\par \par \uc2 -- Vincent Fabian Thomas contributed to this article\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211129ehbu0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
