\par\par \b \uc2 The social dilemma of booster vaccines\b0\par\par\uc2 883 \uc2 words\par \uc2 2 December 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 M. Rifqy Nurfauzan Abdillah , London\par \par \uc2 The government is weighing the possibility of a paid booster jab scheme amid \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over how long the current vaccine immunity will last and fears of a looming third wave of COVID-19, especially as the more infectious Omicron variant is spreading.\par \par \uc2 The program is very appealing, especially for COVID-19 survivors. In a survey by Indikator Politik Indonesia, 53.9 percent of respondents said they would refuse to pay for a vaccine booster, while 34.2 percent would be willing to pay. The remaining 12 percent either did not know or did not answer.\par \par \uc2 However, the government has stated the booster will be available to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  at large only when the fully subsidized mass vaccination program is finished, which is expected to happen early next year.\par \par \uc2 Many have responded to the government's plan with skepticism. They worry about getting infected before the booster jab program even starts, partly due to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reopening and the approaching holiday season.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia recorded the highest single-day death rate for three days in a row from Aug. 18 to 20 when the Delta variant fueled a second wave of the pandemic here. Before the Delta variant struck, Indonesia was regarded as one of the slowest countries in responding to the pandemic as shown by hospital overcapacity and people's frustration.\par \par \uc2 The general \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , particularly COVID-19 survivors, deem the booster as their best hope. They are even more anxious after finding studies suggesting the efficacy of the Sinovac vaccine, which most Indonesians received, might wane after six months. The crisis has been exacerbated by a lack of clear and consistent \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  communication, which has prevented the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  from fully understanding the risk of contagion.\par \par \uc2 The government has gradually put the pandemic under control, but \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  distrust remains as can be seen in people taking their own preemptive measures in the face of a third wave, including the phenomenon of wealthy Indonesians taking boosters abroad. This raises a social dilemma, as on one hand support grows for the vaccine booster campaign, but on the other hand it may widen the vaccination gap and affect vaccination coverage.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has already passed the major milestone of administering 100 million vaccine doses. Challenges, however, remain such as geographical barriers and a global shortage of vaccines.\par \par \uc2 More than 80 percent of global vaccine supplies have gone to high- and upper-middle income countries. Even so, several wealthy nations with a high vaccination rate have administered booster vaccines, sometimes even faster than scientists' recommendation. Therefore, the \uc2 World Health Organization\uc2  has called for a moratorium on vaccine boosters for the sake of justice.\par \par \uc2 Although the WHO has called rich countries unethical and selfish, the rationale for carrying out a vaccine booster program can be understood as the countries are eager to restore normal life, in which people can work, gather with relatives and friends, and travel without quarantine.\par \par \uc2 Following pressures from many quarters, the Health Ministry announced on Nov. 8 the booster program could start when at least 50 percent of the population had received two jabs, a target that can be reached early next year.\par \par \uc2 There are several conditions for the booster program to commence in accordance with the principles of fairness and justice for all.\par \par \uc2 First, the government needs to exert the utmost effort to reach the target of full vaccination, taking into account people living in remote areas before the booster program starts. This is important to convince the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  that the government is committed to leaving no one behind and addressing the vaccination gap among regions.\par \par \uc2 Second, the booster program should begin with health workers and the elderly, who are the most vulnerable groups. Frontline health workers have received a booster, but not all of them due to limited availability of vaccines.\par \par \uc2 Third, transparency matters. The government should disclose a calculation that shows the equilibrium when herd immunity can be achieved. This is important to send a clear message to the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and international community that Indonesia prioritizes the full vaccination program over the booster.\par \par \uc2 Fourth, the government should inform the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  that the cost of the paid booster shot is at the expense of the recipients. The Health Ministry can circulate to local governments through the Home Ministry the list of people who are entitled to a free booster shot under the national health scheme.\par \par \uc2 Fifth, both the paid booster and state-subsidized booster programs should run simultaneously, or without too much of a time difference, so there are no disparities between people who can afford to pay and people who cannot. This \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  communication is crucial to convince the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  there is no discrimination in accessing health care.\par \par \uc2 In sum, the government needs to ensure a smooth transition when initiating the paid booster scheme for the general \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  by providing a careful action plan. The country can reap benefits of the paid booster program because it will generate positive externalities, such as herd immunity. The booster jab may also prevent \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  health from paralysis in case of a third wave.\par \par \uc2 __________________\par \par \uc2 An employee of the Finance Ministry's \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Agency and a master's of \b \highlight22\uc2 public policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  student at the \uc2 London School of Economics and Political Science\uc2 . The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211201ehc200004\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
