\par\par \b \uc2 Identifying Constitutional Court's decision on jobs law\b0\par\par\uc2 967 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 December 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 D. Nicky Fahrizal , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 After a long \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  discourse regarding the 2020 Job Creation Law, the Constitutional Court finally declared the law conditionally unconstitutional.The court ruling gives the government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  two years to revise the law in accordance withlaw-making procedures and wider \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  participation.\par \par \uc2 In its editorial on Nov. 29, 2021 "Law without credibility", The Jakarta Post conveys a strong message to policymakers that goals cannot always justify the means.In other words, the law revision that will be carried out will have to ensure that it follows the right mechanism, including a proper \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consultation.\par \par \uc2 Another Post article"\b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  looms after Job Creation Law declared unconstitutional(27 Nov, 2021), also explains how the Constitutional CourtDecisionNo.91/PUU-XVIII/2020 reiterated theperception of significant legal \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  for investment in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 There are at least two lessons to be drawn from the court's decision.First, the role of the Constitutional Court in Indonesia's democratic ecosystem is significant and relevant.In this case, if we adopt the approach of Mark Tushnet in 2014, the court's response to the polemic of the Job Creation Law uses aninsurancemodel approach, where the court is formed and equipped with aconstitutional reviewfunction to guarantee constitutional protection for the parties to dispute.\par \par \uc2 In theformal review of the Job Creation Law, the court guarantees the protection of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interests, as it rules that the government has bypassed the proper legal procedures and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consultation during the law-making formation.\par \par \uc2 Second, the trend of dependence onthe judicialization of politicswhere courts and judges are required to handle mega-political issues, as described by Ran Hirschl in 2010.In this context, the role of the court in handling the case shows the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 's dependence on it and its judges in dealing with constitutional matters related to mega-political issues.\par \par \uc2 The phenomenon behind the position and attitude of the Constitutional Court in relation to the insurance model and judicialization of politics is also worth observing.Firstly, the Job Creation Law is the result ofa mega-political constellation, where thelaw is seen as a political compromise between the political elite and market players who want reforms in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector,aswellas astrategy for various partiesto gain access toinfluencing national interests and resources.\par \par \uc2 Given that the law is the result of compromise and strategies, it results in constant tensions between normative demands, as regulated in the constitution, and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  mandates.Therefore, the constitutional mandate as the foundation in a constitutional democracy will also depend on political-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  rationality where \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  efficiency becomes its core issue, as noted by B. Herry Priyono in 2014.\par \par \uc2 Because of the constant tension between the constitutional mandate and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  demands, the role of the court as a guarantor is crucial as well as strategic in providing decisions, guidelines or methods to bridge these constant tensions.As a judicial institution within the scope of the judicialization of politics then, the court is encouraged todeny the political question doctrine.\par \par \uc2 The court is, however, still a political institution, where the judges are also political actors.Therefore, the resulting decision is not formed in a vacuum, but it reflects beliefs and political, social and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  struggles.\par \par \uc2 Key considerations and strategic decisions by the judges are also found in the court's decision.In terms of strategic considerations, the judges decided to maintain the Job Creation Law considering the beneficial aspects of its implementation for the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 .Therefore, although the law has significant procedural violations, the jobs law was not declared unconstitutional permanently.\par \par \uc2 From these strategic considerations, the judges reached a compromise based on considerations of pragmatism and legalism.In this context, the considerations attempt to resolve different interests based on pragmatism, namely,the benefits obtained if the Job Creation Law is maintained, and the legalism aspect where the law is an autonomous dimension, and its normative demands must be obeyed.\par \par \uc2 The Constitutional Court's decision contains four key messages.First, the government and the House are given two years to revise the Job Creation Law and the status of the Job Creation Law remains in effect within that period.This reflects the psychological considerations ofthe business sector, allowing the government to control theuncertainty of the business climate.\par \par \uc2 Second, there is the suspension of strategic policies implementation and the court's order to stop the issuance of implementing regulations.Third, the omnibus method contradicts the principles of certainty and standards as regulated in Law No. 12/2011, however, the omnibus method can still be adopted if Law No. 12/2011 is amended.Lastly, \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consultation and participation are crucial in the revision process of the Job Creation Law.\par \par \uc2 From these four key messages, the government and the House are encouraged to work quickly and properly so that legal certainty for the business world can be guaranteed.Moreover, political consolidation between supporting political parties should be carried out immediately to maintain political credibility.\par \par \uc2 In closing, it is necessary for the government and the House to work on the law revision based on creative fidelity, where creativity rests on fidelity to the predetermined normative demands.Thus, it is possible to simultaneously revise Law No.12/2011 first and continue to revise the Job Creation Law.The necessary prerequisites are \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  communication and political maneuvering within the limits of the applicable law.\par \par \uc2 However, the key message for policymakers is to pay attention to the details in eachstageof the law-making process.Aligning with the quote from \uc2 Richard Branson\uc2 , founder of Virgin, "If you place the emphasis on getting the little things right, and address the everyday problems that come up, you can encourage a culture of attention to detail".\par \par \uc2 __________________\par \par \uc2 A researcher at the Politics and Social Change Department, the Centre for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211205ehc600004\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Making Up for Lost Time\b0\par\par\uc2 2,049 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 December 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 IF there is a kind of war that makes some people happy, it would be the ongoing trade war. \uc2 Indika Energy\uc2  Chief Executive Officer (CEO) and Chairman of the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin), Mohammad Arsjad Rasjid P. Mangkuningrat, is among those who benefit.\par \par \uc2 Indika and other mining companies are overjoyed. The trade war involving China and Australia\u8212\'20\'14a United States ally\u8212\'20\'14presents an advantage for Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s coal businesses.\par \par \uc2 In October 2020, China asked its state-owned enterprises to stop importing coal from Australia. China and Australia\u8217\'20\'19s relationship took a turn for the worse, in part triggered by the Australian state of Victoria\u8217\'20\'19s unilateral decision to cancel the \uc2 Belt and Road Initiative\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s partnership with Beijing due to pressure from the federal government and the US.\par \par \uc2 Coal barges are pictured as they queue to be pulled along the Mahakam River in Samarinda, East Kalimantan, August 2019. REUTERS/Willy Kurniawan\par \par \uc2 Although Indonesia has not been directly involved in the trade war, the country\u8217\'20\'19s coal mines are benefiting the situation. More of their coal is entering China to fill the vacuum left by Australia\u8217\'20\'19s coal. \u8220\'20\'1CThis is why the price of Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s coal is rising,\u8221\'20\'1D said Arsjad when we met him at his house that he transformed into his personal office in Jalan Cisanggiri, South Jakarta, on Sunday, November 28. \u8220\'20\'1CWe are sometimes slow in responding. If there\u8217\'20\'19s an opportunity, take it!\u8221\'20\'1D he said, snapping his fingers.\par \par \uc2 Like the fate of all commodities during the Covid-19 pandemic, the price of coal had plummeted, with its lowest price reaching US$49.75 per ton in August 2020 at the Newcastle coal futures. Meanwhile, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s coal reference price in the same month was US$29.42 per ton.\par \par \uc2 The Newcastle coal price began to recover in November 2020, when it reached US$79.85 per ton. But Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s coal reference price only approached that level in January. Since then, the price of coal has soared. In October, the Newcastle coal price reached US$223.45 per ton. One month later, in November, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s coal reference price also experienced a hike to US$215.01 per ton.\par \par \uc2 At first Arsjad was skeptical that the good price would last. But developments in the trade war have turned out positive for Indonesian coal. Tensions rose after the US and the United Kingdom formed a new coalition with Australia (AUKUS) in order to counterbalance China in the Asia-Pacific region. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s even better for us,\u8221\'20\'1D said Arsjad, chuckling. \u8220\'20\'1CMaybe (the current price of coal) will last a while.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 But Arsjad\u8217\'20\'19s prediction differs from \uc2 Fitch Ratings\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19. The New York-based credit rating agency predicts that the world\u8217\'20\'19s coal selling price will decline in 2022 after reaching its peak at the end of 2021. Mirae Asset Management also projects that coal price will decline next year to around US$100 per ton, the reason being, coal\u8217\'20\'19s largest consumers, such as China and India, will boost their own domestic productions.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 AMID \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding the price of coal, the coal mining and processing industry represents the optimism of the energy sector. An \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, encouraged by a better control of the Covid-19 pandemic, will boost energy demand.\par \par \uc2 The upstream oil and gas industry, another energy sub-sector, shares the optimism in welcoming 2022. Like coal, the price of crude oil has been solid since the end of 2020, when the mobility of people and goods began to recover after the long pandemic. In November, the world\u8217\'20\'19s Brent crude oil reached US$47.59 per barrel after a drop to US$22.34 per barrel in March 2020. As of December 3 this year, the world\u8217\'20\'19s crude oil price still remained at US$69.91 per barrel. \u8220\'20\'1CThe better oil and gas price in the upstream sector will still last in 2022,\u8221\'20\'1D said Head of the Upstream Oil and Gas Special Regulatory Task Force (\uc2 SKK Migas\uc2 ), Dwi Soetjipto, in Nusa Dua, Bali, on November 29.\par \par \uc2 A \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  worker inspecting oil pipelines at the Refinery Unit V, Balikpapan, East Kalimantan, October 2019. ANTARA PHOTOS/Yulius Satria Wijaya\par \par \uc2 On November 29-December 1, Dwi Soetjipto held the 2nd International Convention on Indonesian Upstream Oil and Gas at the Bali Nusa Dua Convention Center. The former state oil and gas company Pertamina CEO admitted to acting boldly in organizing a convention during the pandemic. \u8220\'20\'1CDubai was bold enough to hold a convention. Why shouldn\u8217\'20\'19t we?\u8221\'20\'1D said Dwi.\par \par \uc2 To Dwi, the convention was not about demonstrating bravery. The \uc2 SKK Migas\uc2  wanted to send the message to the upstream oil and gas industry that 2022 will be an opportunity to make up for the numerous postponed investment plans during the last two years of the pandemic. \u8220\'20\'1COil price, which will still be solid, will impact investment in 2022,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Dwi is optimistic that 2022 will serve as a good momentum for the upstream oil and gas industry. Demand for oil fuel is predicted to have completely recovered by then. Dwi also believes that the Covid-19 pandemic will soon transform into an endemic, which means that more and more people will travel.\par \par \uc2 Several figures strengthen Dwi\u8217\'20\'19s faith. This year, the \uc2 SKK Migas\uc2  projects that investment in the upstream oil and gas sector will reach US$11 billion, or equivalent to Rp159.693 trillion at an exchange rate of Rp14,500 to the US dollar. As of October, already US$8.1 billion, or equivalent to Rp117.592 trillion, had been realized. \u8220\'20\'1CMeanwhile, the projection for next year, according to our long-term plan, is already set at US$13 billion (Rp188.728 trillion),\u8221\'20\'1D said the 66-year-old man.\par \par \uc2 Of course, said Dwi, such a massive projection can shift either up or down, according to work plan documents and the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  for oil and gas contractors, not all of which have been submitted to the \uc2 SKK Migas\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Among the postponed upstream oil and gas investments, which will be pursued in 2022, is the development of Train III Tangguh Liquid Natural Gas Refinery in Teluk Bintuni, Papua. The work area\u8217\'20\'19s contractor, British Petroleum, stopped the project due to the Covid-19 outbreak in Papua in early September. The project has reached 89.58 percent completion on shore and 99.19 percent off shore.\par \par \uc2 As a result, the expansion project, which will produce 700 million standard cubic foot of gas and 3,000 barrels of oil per day, will only commercially operate in 2022, although its construction has been ongoing since August 25, 2016, or six years ago.\par \par \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  is also optimistic about 2022. The company has set the bold target of extracting oil from over 800 development wells already existing in its work areas. The development plan is twice the size of \uc2 Pertamina\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s upstream activity of extracting oil from only around 370 wells this year.\par \par \uc2 Next year, most development wells will be drilled in the Rokan Block, an oil and gas block in Riau, whose management has just been transferred to \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  from \uc2 Chevron\uc2  on August 9.\par \par \uc2 Budiman Parhusip, CEO of Pertamina Hulu Energi\u8212\'20\'14a \uc2 Pertamina\uc2  subholding in the upstream oil and gas sector\u8212\'20\'14said that since the start, the company has not only been given the mandate to maintain Rokan\u8217\'20\'19s production. \u8220\'20\'1CWe have been instructed that Rokan must be able to improve its performance after \uc2 Pertamina\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s entry,\u8221\'20\'1D Budiman said on November 30.\par \par \uc2 With other major projects taken into account, \uc2 Pertamina\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on investment in 2022 will reach US$3.4 billion, or around Rp43.35 trillion. Among the major projects being prepared is the completion of the development of the Jambaran Tiung Biru gas field in the Cepu Block, East Java, targeted to come on stream at the end of this year, or in early 2022. There is also the optimized development of the Sanga-sanga Block and the Mahakam Block in East Kalimantan.\par \par \uc2 Likewise, the electricity sector welcomes the 2022 \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery. State electricity company PLN can now feel some relief at seeing the country\u8217\'20\'19s improved electricity consumption after a sharp drop during the first year of the pandemic.\par \par \uc2 In 2020, out of the national electricity production of 265,119 gigawatt hours (gWh), only 239,842.28 gWh, or 90.47 percent, was absorbed by all PLN customers. The production was already reduced from the maximum installed capacity of all power plants. Meaning, compared to electricity consumption in 2019, PLN\u8217\'20\'19s electricity sales plummeted to minus 1.28 percent in 2020.\par \par \uc2 At seeing signs of improved electricity consumption, PLN set a high target for consumption growth in 2021, at 4.5-4.75 compared to last year. It seems that PLN was on the right track. As of August, electricity consumption growth had reached 10.52 percent year-on-year. By October, all PLN customers had consumed 210,000 gWh. \u8220\'20\'1CPLN is focused on creating demand for electricity through intensification and extensification,\u8221\'20\'1D said Agung Murdi, PLN Corporate Communication Executive Vice President, on December 3.\par \par \uc2 Agung explained that the intensification program is being implemented by offering various services, for example by encouraging an electricity-based lifestyle such as induction cooking and using electric vehicles. Meanwhile, in its strategy to expand its market, PLN targets companies that are still using their own power generators. \u8220\'20\'1CAnother method is by looking at potential markets, such as agriculture and marine electrification,\u8221\'20\'1D said Agung.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 IN fact, another opportunity for the energy sector has also emerged amid the international pressure on all countries to mitigate the climate crisis. This is why 2022 is believed to be the stepping stone for pursuing the development of new and renewable energy (NRE).\par \par \uc2 In order to reach the target of net zero carbon in 2060, the government is prioritizing the development of NRE in its 2021-2030 Electricity Provision Plan. Around 51 percent of the total capacity of new power plants to be built in the next decade will be NRE. \u8220\'20\'1CMostly from solar panels,\u8221\'20\'1D said Head of the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin) NRE Division Permanent Committee, Muhammad Yusrizki, on December 2.\par \par \uc2 TEXT: KHAIRUL ANAM, AGOENG WIJAYA\par \par \uc2 SOURCES: CENTRAL STATISTICS AGENCY, SKK MIGAS, ICE COAL PRICE, MINISTRY OF ENERGY AND MINERAL RESOURCES, PROCESSED BY TEMPO\par \par \uc2 According to Muhammad, solar panels are prioritized because Indonesia is already far behind in terms of the country\u8217\'20\'19s NRE mix. In the third trimester of 2021, NRE\u8217\'20\'19s portion in the domestic energy mix dropped to 10.9 percent from 11.2 percent in the same period last year. Meanwhile, the government has set a target of at least a 23-percent NRE mix in 2025. Solar energy is seen as able to solve the issue of time restriction in reaching said target. \u8220\'20\'1CIt only takes two years to operate from the initial installation,\u8221\'20\'1D said Yusrizki, who is also in the solar power business. \u8220\'20\'1CGeothermal power and hydropower take five to eight years to operate.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Next year, PLN will begin to auction 200 megawatts of solar power. As for the rest, private companies continue to storm the market by offering solar panels to multinational companies operating in Indonesia. Many global corporations have become increasingly aware of the need to use of clean energy, either due to the improved awareness of their consumers or the demands of financers.\par \par \uc2 According to Fabby Tumiwa, General Chairperson of the Indonesian Solar Energy Association (AESI), companies have begun installing their own solar panels on rooftops since 2019. Next year, said Fabby, even more companies will be using solar power. \u8220\'20\'1CMining companies have also begun replacing their diesel generators with solar power generators,\u8221\'20\'1D said Fabby on November 29. \u8220\'20\'1CThey have already performed numerous auctions this year, and next year will be the execution.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 But Fabby feels that the primary obstacle to the development of NRE has not been outlined to this day. The selling price of PLN\u8217\'20\'19s electricity is still below its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  value. Meanwhile, the purchase price of NRE is higher than coal powered electricity. As a result, green energy is still placed lower on the priority because it\u8217\'20\'19s currently impossible for the debt-ridden PLN to shoulder the difference.\par \par \uc2 KHAIRUL ANAM\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/12/05/789039/789039_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/12/05/789041/789041_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/12/05/789042/