\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b \uc2 ACCURATE EXIT STRATEGY CAN HELP ADDRESS PANDEMIC SCARS: INDRAWATI\b0\par\par\uc2 364 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 December 2021\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By\par \par \uc2 Nusa Dua, Bali (ANTARA) - An accurate exit strategy can help address the scarring effect of the COVID-19 pandemic, Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2  has observed.\par \par \uc2 "An accurate exit strategy and efforts to handle the scarring effect are a prerequisite to sustainable recovery,\u8221\'20\'1D she said at a press conference held on the sidelines of the Finance and \b \highlight22\uc2 Central Bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  Deputies (FCBD) Meeting in Nusa Dua, Bali, on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 An accurate exit strategy must be created as the high level of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  caused by the COVID-19 pandemic and uneven recovery between developed countries and developing nations has cast a shadow over the world, she elaborated.\par \par \uc2 In addition, strong global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance, particularly in developed countries, coupled with high inflationary pressure has also pushed for a change in tighter policies or tapering, she said.\par \par \uc2 Hence, the exit strategy will be discussed at a meeting during Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s G20 Presidency next year. The meeting will focus on three issues\u8212\'20\'14inclusive health, digital transformation, and energy transition, she said.\par \par \uc2 During its G20 Presidency, Indonesia will strive to create equitable vaccination access, accelerate digitalization, and direct the coordination of global policies related to climate change financing, she said.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s G20 Presidency will offer a chance to the country to showcase its role in leading a global forum to address global challenges.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia is determined to address the global challenge by looking for the best solution, ensuring that all countries recover together, and pushing for \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms in favor of stronger, sustainable, balanced, and inclusive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, the minister said.\par \par \uc2 This aligns with the theme of Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s G20 Presidency of "Recover Together, Recover Stronger" by focusing on six priority agendas, which are on the finance track, including coordinating an exit strategy for supporting global recovery.\par \par \uc2 Next, is the effort to handle the scarring effects on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to support stronger growth in the future and strengthen the financing system in the digital era, she said.\par \par \uc2 The last is to develop sustainable finance, increase inclusive financial system, and conceive an international \b \highlight22\uc2 taxation\b0 \highlight\uc2  agenda, she added.\par \par \uc2 (T.H-SHT/A/S022/S022) 09-12-2021 23:22:50\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020211209ehc9002mh\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Rooftop Solar  \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainties \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 2,209 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 December 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 COCA-COLA Europacific Partners Indonesia is in the middle of reinforcing the roof structure of its factory in Pandaan, a subdistrict in Pasuruan Regency, East Java. The company that resulted from the merger of \uc2 Coca-Cola Amatil\uc2  with \uc2 Coca-Cola European Partners\uc2  is planning to build another rooftop solar power generator, also known as an on-grid solar photovoltaic (PV) system or Rooftop PLTS.\par \par \uc2 The PV grid will be the company\u8217\'20\'19s next green project, following the one that covers an area of \u8203\'20\'0B\u8203\'20\'0B72,000 square meters with a peak capacity of 7.13 megawatts (MW), installed at the factory in Cibitung, Bekasi Regency, West Java, in 2020. \u8220\'20\'1CGreen energy projects like this are important for companies pursuing carbon offsets,\u8221\'20\'1D Lucia Karina, Director of \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs, Communications, and Sustainability at Coca-Cola Europacific Partners, told Tempo on Friday, December 10.\par \par \uc2 Since last year, the company has been auditing the roof construction at the Pandaan factory. The result showed that some areas needed structure reinforcement. The factory\u8217\'20\'19s rooftop would be the base for the PV modules. \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s PV mini grid in its Pasuruan factory is designed to have a peak capacity of 3.7 megawatts, half of that in Cibitung.\par \par \uc2 However, Lucia said, the plan to install solar panels in Pandaan has been stalled by permit issues.\par \par \uc2 Lucia said that the licensing system in East Java still uses an operating permit issued by the governor. Meanwhile, the central government uses a business licensing system that is integrated online, alias the online single submission. \u8220\'20\'1COur legal team has sent a letter, but there has been no response. So there is no certainty yet,\u8221\'20\'1D she said.\par \par \uc2 Director of Various New and Renewable Energy Chrisnawan Anditya in Jakarta, in June. esdm.go.id\par \par \uc2 Lucia suspected the problem is not with the East Java provincial government, but with regulations changes at the central level. Even the type of permit in the form of an operational license has changed into a business license for the personal use of electricity provision. \u8220\'20\'1CIf the regulations above change, the rules below must also adjust,\u8221\'20\'1D she said. The \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  over the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Lucia said, halted the licensing process.\par \par \uc2 Regulations on rooftop solar power generators have been going back and forth. A long discussion by the energy and mineral resources ministry had resulted in Minister \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 26/2021 on roof solar power generator connected to the electric power network belonging to business license holders for the provision of electricity for \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  needs.\par \par \uc2 Passed on August 20, the rule, which is supposed to replace Energy Ministers \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 16/2019 on the use of roof solar power generator systems by PLN consumers, could not be implemented yet. Rumors circulated among business actors that the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  collided with Presidential \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 68/2021 on the president\u8217\'20\'19s approval for ministerial/heads of institutions \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  drafts, which was issued two weeks earlier.\par \par \uc2 Fabby Tumiwa, Chair of the Indonesian Solar Energy Association heard that the government would review the energy minister \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 . He thought the lack of palace approval was an odd excuse. The reason is that the discussion of the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been carried out intensively and rigorously since February. There have also been cabinet meetings discussing numerous plans for new provisions. \u8220\'20\'1CIn July it entered the justice and human rights ministry. In August it was promulgated. That\u8217\'20\'19s why it\u8217\'20\'19s already in the official gazette,\u8221\'20\'1D Fabby said on December 9. \u8220\'20\'1CNow the state secretariat has invited ministries and institutions again. The process is like making a new law, starting over from scratch."\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 AS Fabby Tumiwa said, the government is reviewing the rules on rooftop solar power generator that had been passed as a minister \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 . According to the Energy Ministry\u8217\'20\'19s Director of Various New and Renewable Energies Chrisnawan Anditya the discussion involved the finance ministry and state electricity company PLN, from the beginning of September to the end of November.\par \par \uc2 Now, the coordinating ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the cabinet secretariat are asking President Joko Widodo\u8217\'20\'19s approval over the results of the discussion. The latest update was, according to Chrisnawan, the director-general of new, renewable energy and energy conservation has sent a letter to the \uc2 National Development Planning Agency (Bappenas) \uc2 deputy on November 25. \u8220\'20\'1CWe are also still waiting for further processes from the coordinating ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ,\u8221\'20\'1D said Chrisnawan on December 10.\par \par \uc2 Workers install rooftop solar panels at the Coca-Cola Amatil Indonesia factory, Cibitung, Bekasi, West Java, December 2020. Tempo/Tony Hartawan\par \par \uc2 Wahyu Utomo, Deputy of Regional Development and Spatial Planning at the Coordinating Ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the agency that deals with the issue, was reluctant to provide an explanation. \u8220\'20\'1CSorry, I cannot provide answers yet. Perhaps you can check with the energy ministry,\u8221\'20\'1D Wahyu said on December 8. Meanwhile, the Finance Ministry\u8217\'20\'19s Head of the \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  Agency, Febrio Kacaribu, has not responded to Tempo\u8217\'20\'19s request for confirmation.\par \par \uc2 In general, Chrisnawan ensured that Energy Minister \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 26/2021 remains the same. \u8220\'20\'1CWe only reviewed its impact on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 ,\u8221\'20\'1D he remarked.\par \par \uc2 The impacts he meant were the changes in the multiplier factor scheme for the export of electricity from PV grid PLTS to PLN. Electricity is exported if there is an excess of power generated compared to household consumption or the PLTS owner\u8217\'20\'19s industry. In the new \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the multiplier factor is 100 percent, up from the original 65 percent. This means that PLN has to pay more\u8212\'20\'14technically in the form of a reduction in the customer\u8217\'20\'19s monthly electricity bill\u8212\'20\'14for the solar panel-generated electricity that entered the power network.\par \par \uc2 There are concerns that once the PV grid industry becomes massive, PLN would pay the price. When a lot of power is imported from the rooftop plants, PLN would have to pay extra. Meanwhile, PLN is now facing a problem of oversupply, especially in the Java-Bali electricity system. The Covid-19 pandemic adds to the complexity of the problem, as the demand for industrial electricity has plunged. The average reserve margin in PLN\u8217\'20\'19s entire electricity system is now more than 50 percent. Before the pandemic, the unabsorbed electricity was around 30 percent.\par \par \uc2 PLN is receiving increased pressure from the 35,000-megawatt program. The construction of several steam power plants (PLTU) has been completed and will enter the national electricity grid in stages every year. The Sumsel 8 PLTU with 2 x 620 MW capacity in Muara Enim, South Sumatra, for example, is scheduled to enter the power system in the first quarter of 2022. PLN has also negotiated for the delay of the commercial operation date for unit I of the power plant developed by Bukit Asam and China Huadian HongKong Co Ltd. The plant was originally scheduled to start commercial operation in quarter four this year.\par \par \uc2 There are fears that the changes in the \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  provisions for PV grid-generated electricity will further weigh on PLN\u8217\'20\'19s finances. The government is worried that PLN\u8217\'20\'19s financial problems will burden the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which has been bearing electricity \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 According to Fabby Tumiwa, the government\u8217\'20\'19s concerns were out of proportion. \u8220\'20\'1CThe finance ministry is too paranoid about the financial risks it fears will happen to PLN,\u8221\'20\'1D said Fabby, who is also the Executive Director of the Institute for Essential Services Reform.\par \par \uc2 He did not know the details of the finance ministry\u8217\'20\'19s calculation on this issue, because he was never invited to discuss the fair value of the PV grid system\u8217\'20\'19s development. As for the discussion at the energy ministry, Fabby said, so far it has involved associations and independent institutions, to make calculations based on real market analyses.\par \par \uc2 According to Fabby, the fair value of PV grid development should also take into account the developer\u8217\'20\'19s capital expenditures and profits. \u8220\'20\'1CBecause it is an incentive to motivate the growth of new-renewable energy, it has to be quite generous,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Deputy CEO of PLN, Darmawan Prasodjo, at the launch of the New PLN Mobile customer service application in Jakarta, December 2020. pln.co.id\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry Standing Committee Chairman for New and Renewable Energy, Muhammad Yusrizki, can understand the concerns of the government and PLN. He said that business, especially multinational companies, is increasingly driving towards a green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Indonesia has also set a net-zero emission target in 2060, even sooner. This situation could be a new threat for PLN.\par \par \uc2 He predicts global corporations will compete to build their own PV mini-grid. \u8220\'20\'1CThis industrial movement will be a big wave. PLN can slowly lose demand, it may even kill PLN,\u8221\'20\'1D said Yusrizki.\par \par \uc2 At the moment, Yusrizki continued, there are two groups comprising hundreds of big companies committed to practicing a sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Under the banner of the \uc2 United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change\uc2 , they are aggressively promoting the \u8216\'20\'18race to zero\u8217\'20\'19 campaign. This group includes \uc2 Unilever\uc2 , \uc2 Nestle\uc2 , \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2 , \uc2 Microsoft\uc2 , \uc2 Accenture\uc2 , \uc2 Schneider Electric\uc2 , and Aveva. Following that, an Amazon-led group has made a \u8220\'20\'1C10 years ahead\u8221\'20\'1D pledge for climate. This group is supported by more than 100 companies worldwide. \u8220\'20\'1CThese companies are in Indonesia. This is the world\u8217\'20\'19s pressure on Indonesia,\u8221\'20\'1D said Yusrizki.\par \par \uc2 The wave of PV grid constructions, Yusrizki added, has \u8216\'20\'18successfully\u8217\'20\'19 bankrupted many of the world\u8217\'20\'19s power companies, such as in Germany, England and the United States. \u8220\'20\'1CThey shut off coal and gas-fired power plants because the demand has dropped drastically since solar grids entered the utility-based system massively, in housing, shops, offices, to industrial complexes. It\u8217\'20\'19s a disruption.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 PLN\u8217\'20\'19s management, Yusrizki said, understands the challenge. \u8220\'20\'1CThis is the scary thing about distributed renewable energy,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. \u8220\'20\'1CGenerators are distributed to the most micro level: households. It\u8217\'20\'19s not next year, but five to 10 years from now.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 AMID the magnitude of challenges from the electricity business, PLN remains optimistic that the demand for industrial electricity will not be eroded by global corps\u8217\'20\'19 trend to pursue their target of net zero-emission. PLN\u8217\'20\'19s Executive Vice President for Corporate Communications and CSR Agung Murdifi believes that the company would be able to meet competitive and reliable demand, especially for industries.\par \par \uc2 He reminded that solar panels are intermittent generators. They are not stable as they are not always available when needed, and they need storage devices such as pumped storage and batteries. Their users also need generating units that have quick responses as backup support.\par \par \uc2 A worker maintains the solar panels installed on the roof of the Directorate-General of Electricity building at the Ministry of Energy and Mineral Resources (EDSM), Jakarta, in March. ANTARA PHOTOS/Aditya Pradana Putra\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, Agung said, PLN now has a Renewable Energy Certificate (REC) that guarantees industrial electricity supply from new and renewable energy. This means that the industry does not need to spend large investments to build its own new and renewable energy plants.\par \par \uc2 PLN noted that cumulative REC sales continue to increase. As of December 2, sales rose to 283,387 units from 273,703 units in the previous month. The REC enterprise sales for small, medium and large companies also rose from 21,722 units in October to 31,182 units in November. \u8220\'20\'1CCurrently, there are 33 companies on the waiting list for PLN\u8217\'20\'19s REC services with a total of 47 transactions,\u8221\'20\'1D said Agung on December 3.\par \par \uc2 Going forward, PLN is also confident that electricity demand will increase again as the Covid-19 pandemic is more under control and the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovers. In accordance with PLN\u8217\'20\'19s 2021-2030 Electricity Supply Business Plan, electricity demand in 2022 is projected to increase by an average of 4.9 percent per year. The company is optimistic that electricity will recover 100 percent, as before the pandemic. According to Agung, the current electricity consumption by industries has increased by 10 percent on an annual basis.\par \par \uc2 Chrisnawan Anditya also ensured that the energy ministry, as the regulator, would always pay attention to the balance between PLN\u8217\'20\'19s interests and the wishes of the people who want to install PV grids on their rooftops. Nevertheless, he was reluctant to explain the studies on the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  risks of PV grids development. \u8220\'20\'1CThe energy ministry, the finance ministry, and PLN have discussed and calculated the impacts. The results will later be discussed at the coordinating ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the cabinet secretariat," he said.\par \par \uc2 Another interesting issue is that the rooftop PV grid project can actually be used as an instrument in carbon trading. Article 28 paragraph 1 of Energy Minister \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 26/2021 also creates opportunities for PV grid users or business license holders to provide electricity for the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interest. However, paragraph 2 also states that the provisions on carbon ownership and carbon trading business mechanisms will be further regulated by ministerial regulations.\par \par \uc2 Chrisnawan was unable to explain the plan for the carbon trading scheme referred to in the development rooftop PV grids system. \u8220\'20\'1CThe implementation awaits the derivatives of the presidential \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on net carbon emissions,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 KHAIRUL ANAM\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/12/12/789617/789617_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/12/12/789618/789618_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/12/12/789620/789620_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/12/12/789622/789622_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/12/12/789624/789624_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020211213ehcc0000d\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 A Certainty in the Chaos\b0\par\par\uc2 684 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 December 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 THE latest inflation in the United States is becoming more worrisome. The year-on-year inflation for November, which was released on Friday, December 10, revealed the highest inflation ever seen in the US since 1982, at 6.8 percent. This is quite the sharp increase from year-on-year inflation for October, which was 6.2 percent.\par \par \uc2 Such a high figure will be an additional push for the Federal Reserve to act. In his testimony before the \uc2 US Senate\uc2 , the Fed Chair Jay Powell stated that mitigating inflation would be the priority for his policies. But that statement cannot remain as an empty political promise without concrete action.\par \par \uc2 There are two policies of the Fed that can act as a response to dampen inflation. The first is to immediately reduce liquidity injections into the market, or by doing a tapering. The second is by increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  faster. Without those two policies, inflation can become even more uncontrollable.\par \par \uc2 The problem is, economists and market analysts always have other perspectives when they weigh the issues. The key question lies in the main cause of that high inflation. Many economists have doubted the flood of money\u8212\'20\'14the Fed has been injecting US$120 billion per month since the outbreak of the pandemic; the extremely low-\b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; the Fed has maintained \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  at near zero percent\u8212\'20\'14is the main cause of inflation. In short, inflation rose not merely due to monetary expansion.\par \par \uc2 Instead, non-monetary factors have contributed more towards inflation. There has been a disruption in the global supply chain due to the pandemic. Shipping and logistical costs rose sharply. In developed economies, there is a labor shortage when the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  starts moving again. It is not easy to re-recruit workers who went away when businesses closed. All these issues end up in higher prices.\par \par \uc2 Then, if non-monetary factors are behind inflation, is it possible that just the Fed\u8217\'20\'19s monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  can fix it? If the Fed would fasten tapering and interest rate hikes, it is the financial market that will suffer from massive shocks everywhere.\par \par \uc2 What follows next is shrinking \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. The result is more frightening compared to inflation: stagflation. Inflation will not fall because it is being treated incorrectly. Instead, high inflation will come at the same time as stagnant growth.\par \par \uc2 This endless debate has continued to sway markets. The fear of tapering and higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  after Powell\u8217\'20\'19s testimony to the Senate caused global stock prices to fall rapidly, including in Indonesia. This week, the market recovered and stock prices are rising again.\par \par \uc2 The continuously changing information about how dangerous the Omicron variant is adds volatility to the market. Around the world, governments are \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  what policies they should implement. In Indonesia, the government suddenly changed its mind, canceling a tight \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  restriction that should have taken effect throughout the Christmas and New Year\u8217\'20\'19s holidays.\par \par \uc2 Even so, in the midst of the market turmoil and the continuously changing government response, one phenomenon continues to move in one direction with consistency. Foreign investors are slowly pulling out of Indonesian government bonds. As of December 8, foreign capital invested in Indonesian government bonds are left at Rp903 trillion. This is already lower compared to its nadir at Rp924 trillion when market panic blew up on April 2020.\par \par \uc2 Besides \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the national banks also took over the role of foreign investors as the main owners of Indonesian government bonds. As of December 8, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s gross ownership totals Rp1,064 trillion, meanwhile, the national banks hold Rp1,595 trillion. As a comparison, in January 2020, national banks only had Rp740 trillion in government bonds.\par \par \uc2 On one hand, dependency on foreign investors has decreased. On the other hand, our banks are more exposed to high risk if the price of Indonesian bonds collapses. The government\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions are now more strongly connected with the health of banking. If the government\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  credibility falls apart, it will easily drag down the banking sector with it.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/12/13/789665/789665_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020211213ehcc0000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
