\par\par \b \uc2 RI will benefit from RCEP but has yet to ratify it\b0\par\par\uc2 1,090 \uc2 words\par \uc2 17 December 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Lili Yan Ing, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 East Asia's \uc2 Regional Comprehensive \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Partnership\uc2  (RCEP) will come into effect by Jan. 1, 2022, as it has already reached a quorum. As of today, 11 countries have ratified the agreement. They are Brunei, Cambodia, Laos, Thailand, Vietnam and Singapore, as well as all the non-ASEAN signatories: Australia, China, Japan, South Korea and New Zealand. In South Korea, the RCEP will come into effect on Feb 1, 2022.\par \par \uc2 Yet Indonesia has not ratified the agreement.\par \par \uc2 The RCEP is the largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  bloc in the world. Even without India, the countries in the agreement account for 30 percent of the world's population, 29 percent of the global gross domestic product (GDP), 27 percent of global trade and 29 percent of foreign direct investment (FDI).\par \par \uc2 By comparison, the Trans Pacific Partnership (or TPP), which no longer includes the United States and is now called the Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for TPP (CPTPP), represents only 7 percent of the world's population, 13 percent of global GDP, 15 percent of trade and 20 percent of FDI.\par \par \uc2 The good thing about the RCEP is that even though it does not call for liberalization at the same level, scope or depth of commitment as the CPTPP, its impact on the economies of member countries, and indeed on the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , will be massive. The RCEP will incentivize supply chains in the region while also being sensitive to the different political conditions and levels of development in member countries.\par \par \uc2 At the macro level, the RCEP has impacts on the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  through exports, imports and investment. It is estimated that the RCEP will contribute around US$1 billion to Indonesia's trade surplus by 2040. It will increase investment inflows to Indonesia by about $1.7 billion.\par \par \uc2 Overall, the agreement will boost Indonesia's GDP by 0.07 percent by 2040, according to a 2020 estimate by the Trade Ministry and Finance Ministry. These are potential benefits which can only be realized after it is in effect. So, first thing to emphasize here is that Indonesia has to ratify the RCEP to enjoy its full benefits.\par \par \uc2 Companies in Indonesia will benefit from the RCEP in at least three ways: lower \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates for their exports, better access to cheaper or better-quality inputs for making their products and a more open and more transparent business environment for trade in goods, services, investment and the movement of people.Under the RCEP, companies will enjoy a business environment that does much more to facilitate regional trade and investment.\par \par \uc2 To optimize the benefits of joining the RCEP, Indonesia should do at least two things.\par \par \uc2 First, the government needs to translate the commitments it makes under the RCEP into domestic policies and regulations. These must be consistent with the commitments in the agreement so that companies can operate in a stable and predictable environment. The country should avoid making any contradictory policies, regulations or official statements, as this will only create \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the market.\par \par \uc2 Second, preferential trade and investment agreements will work only if Indonesia improves its regulations and procedures for exports, imports and investment. To enjoy the preferential \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates offered in the RCEP in the trade of goods, for example, Indonesia should simplify the procedures required to obtain a certificate of origin (COO) for member countries.\par \par \uc2 In addition, governments and business associations will be responsible for providing information publicly and educating businesses and the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  about these rules and how to adhere to them.\par \par \uc2 Likewise, in the RCEP, members have agreed to adopt a "negative list" of services and investment, which details certain foreign equity caps in listed sectors. Beyond those listed sectors, the sectors are open to foreign investment Indonesia needs to develop such a list, make it transparent and update it regularly. The implementation should be consistent on what has been committed to in the RCEP. A better trade and investment environment will create better investment opportunities for companies operating in Indonesia, particularly for small and medium enterprises (SMEs) - both in terms of attracting investment from other RCEP countries and making investments in other RCEP countries.\par \par \uc2 While we have acknowledged the benefits of the RCEP, there have also been serious concerns, particularly about more intense competition from China. I do not foresee any major blows to Indonesia's labor-intensive industries from the RCEP's implementation because these industries have already had to adjust to international competition. After all, the ASEAN-China Free Trade Agreement has been in effect since January 2010.\par \par \uc2 Now let's see what data tell us. In 2020, Indonesia imported $40 billion worth of goods from China. Electrical machinery and electronics accounted for half of those imports. Iron, steel and vehicles accounted for much of the rest. Labor-intensive products such as footwear and apparel currently account for just 12 percent of imports from China and this share has been decreasing, as a fraction of total imports from China, in recent years.\par \par \uc2 So, for Indonesia's labor-intensive industries, the competition now is not primarily from China but rather from Vietnam and Pakistan, and lately also from Bangladesh and Morocco.\par \par \uc2 This is partly because the unit labor cost in China has been increasing since the early 2000s. From 2000 to 2019, the unit cost of labor in the country grew by 87 percent. China has bypassed the US in terms of FDI inflows. In 2020, China received the world's largest FDI inflows, totaling $163 billion. But the reasons why companies like \uc2 Apple\uc2  and FoxConn invest in China have more to do with the quantity and quality of engineers and skilled workers in China, not low labor costs. In fact, the 20 largest Chinese companies in terms of market capitalization are mostly in the services sector, Tencent, Alibaba and ICBC.\par \par \uc2 All in all, the important thing to keep in mind is that global competition is already here, with or without the RCEP. The best thing Indonesia can do to win the competition is not "protecting" its producers or workers but rather providing a conducive environment for companies to grow and expand, while also teaching Indonesian professionals and workers specific technical skills and the digital savvy demanded by markets so that they will be ready to enter job markets or become entrepreneurs and be more mobile across industries and countries.\par \par \uc2 _____________________\par \par \uc2 Lead adviser for the Southeast Asia region at the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Research Institute for ASEAN and East Asia\uc2  (ERIA). The views expressed are her own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211216ehch00009\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
