e bill had been delayed by "a matter of timing" and that the House simply wanted to ensure that the lawmaking process followed established procedure to prevent it from being questioned in the future.\par \par \uc2 The delay, the latest of many, has frustrated women's rights activists and critics of the legislature alike, as well as members of House factions invested in the bill.\par \par \uc2 A disappointed Willy Aditya, the chairman of the bill's working committee and a NasDem Party member, said lawmakers could have simply convened last-minute talks to revise the steering committee's decisions before the end of the current sitting period.\par \par \uc2 "A consultation meeting could have actually been held to replace the Bamus session, but the House speakers failed to reach a consensus to do so," Willy said last week.\par \par \uc2 Luluk Hamidah of the National Awakening Party (PKB), another member of the bill's working committee, interrupted Thursday's plenary session to say, "So many people who have been waiting for the bill believe the House has failed them."\par \par \uc2 She added that her colleagues were acting as if there was no "urgent need" for the bill.\par \par \uc2 Silent epidemic\par \par \uc2 The disappointment was palpable among women's rights activists, including longtime advocates of the bill united under the Network of Women's Rights Defenders for Victims of Violence.\par \par \uc2 Bivitri Susanti, a constitutional law expert and member of the network, said lawmakers' refusal to push through the bill demonstrated their indifference to the issue.\par \par \uc2 "It seems like there is no sense of urgency among lawmakers because the bill isn't as 'juicy' as others. [The sexual violence bill] has no \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  value to them," Bivitri said in a press conference on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 The further delay comes amid a general increase in reports of sexual violence in the nation.\par \par \uc2 In its 2020 report, the National Commission on Violence Against Women (Komnas Perempuan) noted that 431,471 cases of sexual violence against women had been reported in 2019.\par \par \uc2 Activists believe the actual number of cases is likely higher, as many are believed to go unreported as a result of stigma and fear.\par \par \uc2 Many perpetrators of sexual violence are people close to the victims or those responsible for protecting them, including family members, teachers, lecturers and even police officers.\par \par \uc2 Most recently, a teacher in Bandung, West Java, has been brought to trial for allegedly raping 13 students from three different Islamic boarding schools over the past five years.\par \par \uc2 The 36-year-old allegedly fathered nine children with the victims, all of whom were between 16 and 17 years old.\par \par \uc2 Actual progress?\par \par \uc2 Rights activists say the increase in reported cases indicates the urgent need for the bill to be passed, even if the current version has been watered down over the course of negotiations.\par \par \uc2 Diah Pitaloka, a PDI-P lawmaker, Baleg member and vocal proponent of the bill, said the latest draft would still be a milestone in transforming the legal approach to cases of sexual violence.\par \par \uc2 "It has offered a new paradigm and progressive legal framework to investigate and handle sexual violence cases, which are often hindered by difficulties in finding evidence or witnesses," Diah told The Jakarta Post.\par \par \uc2 Sulisyowati Irianto, a professor of law at the University of Indonesia, said the recent renaming of the bill from the initial sexual violence eradication bill to the sexual violence crimes bill was due, in part, to a lack of victim-centered perspectives.\par \par \uc2 "The basic principle of the criminal [legal perspective] focuses only on ensuring the perpetrators receive proper punishment," Sulistyowati told the Post on Saturday.\par \par \uc2 The latest draft of the bill, a copy of which was obtained by the Post, acknowledges five forms of sexual violence: sexual harassment (both physical and nonphysical), cyber sexual harassment, forced use of contraceptives, forced sterilization and sexual exploitation.\par \par \uc2 This is a significant departure from the initial draft of the bill, which denoted 15 forms of sexual violence, including forced marriage, forced abortion and forced prostitution.\par \par \uc2 "Most lawmakers have disregarded the experience of the victims," said Sulistyowati, "even though the initial draft is based on real world cases and includes surveys and qualitative data from the victims."\par \par \uc2 While the \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  has essentially secured the House's endorsement, the path forward is still long.\par \par \uc2 After House lawmakers approve the draft bill themselves, the executive will need to be brought in for further deliberations, Willy said.\par \par \uc2 Diah said the House would still be gathering input from experts and the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "It will still take months [for the bill to be passed into law]," she said, adding that it would depend on politics and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  opinion.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211219ehck0000b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
