\par\par \b \uc2 Omicron discovery could delay  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  recovery\b0\par\par\uc2 Divya Karyza and Norman Harsono, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 899 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 December 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 After reporting the country's first known case of the Omicronvariant of the coronavirus, the government has declared its readiness to retighten curbs if necessary, a move that would likely slow down -- but not halt -- the nation's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery.\par \par \uc2 Coordinating ministers said last week that the government would tighten \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  mobility restrictions (PPKM) should a spike in COVID-19 cases overwhelm the healthcare system, and that this would have knock-on effects on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity.\par \par \uc2 Economists have long warned of such an eventuality, but the odds have risen, as the Health Ministry announced on Thursday Indonesia's first confirmed case of Omicron, a variant that seems to be more transmissible but less deadly than its predecessors.\par \par \uc2 "The development of the Omicron variant will be the key to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery in 2022. If Omicron were to resultin significant hospitalization and the current vaccines were to lose their potency, the recovery would be slower than expected," Coordinating Maritime Affairs and Investment Minister \uc2 Luhut Pandjaitan\uc2  said on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 New studies have found that COVID-19 vaccines appear to offer significantly less protection against the Omicron variant but that a booster dose restores much of the protection.\par \par \uc2 Economists generally expect Omicron's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  impact on Indonesia to be nowhere near as bad as the previous two waves, citing the country's room for emergency response measures and its preparedness after dealing with previous waves.\par \par \uc2 But they also say that tightened PPKM would weaken consumer spendingand that things could worsen depending on what medical experts learn about the new variant and how other governments respond over the coming months.\par \par \uc2 Rully Arya Wisnubroto, a senior financial market analyst at state-owned \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2 , noted thatbesides the pandemic, Indonesia faced other macroeconomic risks, such as soaring global inflation, rate hikes abroad and a slowdown in China's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 "We see that \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still high, [but] the probability of continued \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is still quite [high]," he toldThe Jakarta Poston Friday.\par \par \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2  expects Indonesia's gross domestic product (GDP) to grow5 to 5.5 percent next year.\par \par \uc2 Gas and brakes\par \par \uc2 Since July, the government has had a four-tiered PPKM system in place that requires each city or regency to enforce restrictions based on the local level of risk, with level 4 being the most stringent.\par \par \uc2 Theselevels are set based on positivity rates, hospital bed occupancy, new cases,death figures and vaccination rates.\par \par \uc2 Even before the first Omicron case was detected, the government had announcedplans to temporarily tighten PPKM nationwide in late December and early January, hoping to prevent a case surge during the Christmas and New Year holidays.\par \par \uc2 "We will watch the situation. If we see a spike or curve, we will hit the brakes. But if cases are flat, we will hit the gas," said Coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister \uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2  on Dec. 15, the day before case one was announced.\par \par \uc2 He said the government would focus on speeding up the jab drive to reach an 80 percent vaccination rate by March 2022, which would make Indonesia "relatively protected from the variant."\par \par \uc2 As of Friday, some 72 percent of Indonesians hadhad afirst vaccine dose, while 51 percent hadreceived a second one,Health Ministry data shows.\par \par \uc2 Health Minister Budi Gunadi Sadikin said on Thursday that the government also planned to expand its booster vaccination program and double down on genome sequencing.\par \par \uc2 The Transportation Ministry, also on Thursday, said it would closely monitor the observance of prevailing health rules in all modes of transportation, both domestic and international, and at points of entry.\par \par \uc2 Downside risks\par \par \uc2 Indonesia expects its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to largely return to pre-pandemic conditions in 2022, as indicated by a GDP growth target of 5.5 percent outlined in the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . That compares to the 4.5 percent expected for this year and a 2.07 percent contraction recorded last year, when the first wave of the coronavirus hit the country.\par \par \uc2 GDP was up by an annual 3.51 percent in the third quarter of this year, proving overly optimistic the government's forecast of 4.5 percent, as curbs were tightened in response to the Delta variant-fueled second wave.\par \par \uc2 "Omicron can be a threat if not mitigated by the government," Josua Pardede, chief economist at publicly listed \uc2 Bank Permata\uc2 , said on Friday.\par \par \uc2 However, he expected the Omicron variant to have a very limited impact on fourth-quarter GDP growth, arguing that it was unlikely that the government wouldtighten the PPKM beyond what had already been planned for the year-end holidays.\par \par \uc2 Josua estimatedthat GDP growth wouldfall between4.75 and5.25 percent in the fourth quarter of this year, driven by investment and consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , with the trade surplus narrowing in line with rising imports as factory activity resumed, and lower exports as global commodity prices normalized.\par \par \uc2 Center of Economics and Law Studies (CELIOS) director Bhima Yudhistira estimated that tightened PPKM would slow down annual GDP growth to 1 to 2 percent in the first quarter of 2022 due to delayed consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and supply chain disruptions.\par \par \uc2 However, he predicted Indonesia would reach 4.5 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the fourth quarter of this year, partly because of the base effect and thanks to strong exports.\par \par \uc2 "This is reasonable, considering that last year, there was no commodity boom and social restrictions were tighter," he said.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211219ehck0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
