\par\par \b \uc2 Workers, employers escalate threats after Jakarta wage hike\b0\par\par\uc2 Vincent Fabian Thomas, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 813 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 December 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Tensions between businesses and workers are high two days after Jakarta Governor \uc2 Anies Baswedan\uc2  announced a higher regional minimum wage than previously set, with neither side looking keen to yield.\par \par \uc2 The announced revision would see Jakarta's 2022 minimum wage rise 5.1 percent to Rp 4,641,854 (US$323), a far greater increase than the previously decided 0.85 percent raise to Rp 4,453,935. Workers have lauded the move and have vowed to do whatever they can to ensure the decision will stand.\par \par \uc2 Businesses, represented by the Indonesian Employers Association (Apindo) and the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry (Kadin), have said they will push for the decision to be revoked, arguing that the revised minimum wage hike violates a 2021 government \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on wages based on the 2020 Job Creation Law.\par \par \uc2 "We will file a lawsuit against the revision through the state administrative court (PTUN)," Apindo chairman Hariyadi Sukamdani said during a press conference on Monday, adding that the groups would file the case as soon as the official document on the minimum wage was published.\par \par \uc2 "We urge all businesses in Jakarta not to apply the revised minimum wage while we are waiting for the PTUN ruling," Hariyadi added.\par \par \uc2 The Jakarta governor's decision comes after a recent ruling by the Constitutional Court on the Job Creation Law reignited longstanding tensions between businesses and unions.\par \par \uc2 Workers, backed by legal experts, say that in declaring invalid the procedures leading to its creation, the ruling renders the entire law unconstitutional, thereby depriving the newly stipulated minimum wage formula of its legal basis.\par \par \uc2 For two weeks, regional governments undertook no visible efforts in response to the ruling, despite workers pressing them to follow the previous law for setting minimum wages, while the central government maintained that the Constitutional Court ruling would not affect the ongoing implementation of the law through derivative regulations.\par \par \uc2 However, the Jakarta governor's decision changes everything. Businesses now fear that other regional administrations will follow Jakarta's lead -- as unions are demanding.\par \par \uc2 "That's what we're worried about. One other province has followed suit. You can check it for yourself," Kadin deputy chairman on manpower affairs Adi Mahfudz said during the same press conference.\par \par \uc2 "Don't let this have a broader impact," he added.\par \par \uc2 Adi warned that Jakarta's decision had plunged businesses into regulatory \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and could deter investment. In addition, he added, it would have many implications for both companies and workers.\par \par \uc2 "It could hamper production. It is also possible that there will be an increase in layoffs, especially in Jakarta," Adi said, adding that the revision had baffled businesses as it had disrupted cash flow projections for next year.\par \par \uc2 Strike on agenda\par \par \uc2 In response, Confederation of Indonesian Trade Unions (KSPI) chairman Said Iqbal said workers would stage another strike should businesses insist on following through with lawsuits, even if they won the cases.\par \par \uc2 "First, there will be massive protests at every PTUN throughout Indonesia. Second, at the gubernatorial office. Third, at every Apindo secretariat too there will be massive protests," Said warned on Monday in a press conference held an hour before businesses held theirs.\par \par \uc2 "Don't pour gasoline on the fire. I'm sorry for being too harsh. We are fatigued. This discussion has been going on too long," Said added.\par \par \uc2 Workers said the Jakarta governor had done the right thing in deciding to revise the minimum wage decree. Said cited the National Development Agency (\uc2 Bappenas\uc2 ) saying that a 5 percent annual increase was the optimal figure for raising minimum wages, adding that it would add Rp 180 trillion worth of purchasing power annually, which could benefit businesses.\par \par \uc2 He added that workers were urging other regions to follow Jakarta's move by amending their own decisions on the 2022 minimum wage, arguing that many sectors, including mining, plantation and export-focused manufacturers, could afford the hike.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, pandemic-ravaged sectors like tourism and transportation, as well as companies reporting net losses for two consecutive years, could postpone the hike, he added.\par \par \uc2 Governor Anies said on Saturday that the decision to revise the minimum wage was in line with the current trajectory of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 GDP growth is slated to reach 4 to 5 percent next year, according to estimates from numerous agencies and institutions.\par \par \uc2 The prevailing formula only resulted in a 0.85 percent increase, below Jakarta's annual inflation rate of 1.1 percent.\par \par \uc2 "We feel that the formula given to us in the provinces of Indonesia, especially in DKI Jakarta, does not provide a sense of justice," Anies said, as quoted by news agency Antara.\par \par \uc2 The Manpower Ministry, however, urged the Jakarta governor to follow the formula stipulated in the 2021 government \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on wages, adding that the prevailing formula was mandated by the law.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211221ehcm0000g\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
