\par\par \uc2 FEATURES\par \b \uc2 OPTIMIZING GOVERNMENT ASSISTANCE FOR  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMIC \highlight\uc2  RECOVERY\b0\par\par\uc2 1,298 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 December 2021\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Azis Kurmala\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - The COVID-19 pandemic has greatly affected the economies of various countries in the world, including that of Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 The pandemic that struck at the start of 2020 has had an impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of households; micro, small, and medium enterprises (MSMEs); corporations; as well as other \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  actors.\par \par \uc2 However, Indonesia has continued to make improvements in terms of bringing its COVID-19 pandemic situation under control.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia recorded just 216 positive cases in December 2021, a significant improvement as compared to July 2021, when the second wave of COVID-19 infections almost overwhelmed the country.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has also registered a steady increase in the vaccination rate, with around 152.6 million, or 73.4 percent of the target population receiving the first vaccine dose.\par \par \uc2 Apart from an increase in the vaccination rate, various \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery policies are already on the right track, so that the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  can grow positively.\par \par \uc2 Coordinating Minister for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs Airlangga Hartarto expects the country\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the fourth quarter of 2021 to lie in the range of around 3.7 and four percent.\par \par \uc2 Hartarto noted that some key sectors, such as manufacturing, mining, and plantations, have recovered early. Meanwhile, the agriculture and real estate sectors have also shown resilience during the COVID-19 pandemic.\par \par \uc2 The minister remarked that the COVID-19 pandemic has posed major challenges in terms of the rising unemployment. In August 2020, the pandemic resulted in around 29.12 million people, or 14.28 percent of the working age population being categorized as unemployed, not working temporarily, not entering the workforce, and working with reduced hours.\par \par \uc2 In order to overcome these problems, he noted, one of the strategies adopted was to utilize the Pre-Employment Card Program.\par \par \uc2 This program is immensely beneficial in improving the competence of the workforce through online vocational training. Another objective of this program is to maintain the purchasing power of the affected people through social assistance.\par \par \uc2 Recipients of the Pre-Employment Card Program are generally young workers aged 18 to 35 years and with high school level education or below.\par \par \uc2 Hartarto noted that the Pre-Employment Card also covers all community groups, including women, who have more than one dependent child in disadvantaged areas.\par \par \uc2 Until the end of November 2021, there were at least 78 million online registrants for the Pre-Employment Card Program. Meanwhile, since 2020, the number of beneficiaries had reached 11.4 million people, with total incentive disbursed amounting to Rp25.1 trillion.\par \par \uc2 In terms of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery, an evaluation survey of the Pre-Employment Card Program showed that after being registered and participating in this program, the number of unemployed beneficiaries decreased, from 56 percent to 39.8 percent.\par \par \uc2 In addition, the incentives received after the training is completed also increased the purchasing power as well as created jobs and entrepreneurship through MSMEs.\par \par \uc2 For MSMEs affected by the COVID-19 pandemic, he noted, the government had launched various \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  programs to support and empower MSMEs in order to survive in the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic.\par \par \uc2 A series of social protection programs have also been implemented by the government, including the Smart Indonesia Card for higher education, Smart Indonesia Program, national health insurance for contribution assistance recipients, Family Hope Program, cash social transfer, and staple food cards.\par \par \uc2 In addition to the COVID-19 pandemic, Hartarto noted, the Indonesian government views food security as one of the important issues that must be addressed in order to ensure a sustainable and resilient \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The government has established a national food system to increase food production and productivity to meet the national needs.\par \par \uc2 The system aims to fulfil five important objectives comprising sustainable domestic production and availability to meet the demand for quality and safe food, a conducive environment for local food development, stabilization of food access, strengthening farmer corporations and food distribution efficiency, as well as food assistance for households to address food insecurity.\par \par \uc2 Technology should be applied in production, distribution, and consumption to improve the efficiency and effectiveness of each process in producing food.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia"s priority programs in the agricultural sector include price stabilization, integrated livestock, agricultural intensification, and controlled land conversion.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Indonesia has continued to increase, Hartarto stated. In 2020, as much as 41.9 percent of the total ASEAN digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  transactions came from Indonesia, which were contributed by the e-commerce sector, he pointed out.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia"s total digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  transactions had reached US$44 billion in 2020 and are expected to increase to US$124 billion by 2025, he added.\par \par \uc2 E-commerce transactions, digital banking, and electronic money are also forecast to continue to increase this year, he remarked. The largest increase of 48.4 percent (yoy) is expected in e-commerce transactions, he noted. Electronic money and digital banking are projected to increase by 35.7 percent (yoy) and 30.1 percent (yoy), he added.\par \par \uc2 "This increase in digital transactions has a crucial role and contributes to Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery during the COVID-19 pandemic," Hartarto stated.\par \par \uc2 Better prospects\par \par \uc2 Governor of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI) \uc2 Perry Warjiyo\uc2  forecasts better prospects of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery in 2022 as compared to 2021, with growth in the 4.7-5.5 percent range.\par \par \uc2 "Our \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will be better while heading towards recovery, with growth in the range of 4.7-5.5 percent in 2022, from this year"s 3.2-4 percent," Warjiyo stated.\par \par \uc2 According to Warjiyo, the optimism of recovery must be strengthened by applying the precautionary principle. Growth was supported by development in the consumption, investment, export sectors as well as controlled inflation at three percent, give or take one percent.\par \par \uc2 "The digital \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and finance will continue to increase very quickly to support our \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery," he affirmed.\par \par \uc2 In addition, BI has responded to the precautionary principle through the synergy of existing national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies and was further strengthened by the Financial System Stability Committee (KSSK) and all stakeholders, including Commission XI of the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "There is one prerequisite that we must follow together, which is expediting vaccination, so that mass immunity can be achieved immediately and open up \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sectors gradually to support the nation"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery," he explained.\par \par \uc2 Warjiyo noted that the five \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  responses of BI comprised the transformation of the real sector, including the downstreaming of natural resources, which also responded to global challenges to the green \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Second, the synergy between the Ministry of Finance and BI regarding \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary policies in order to maintain macroeconomic stability and jointly restore the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Third, BI, along with KSSK, encouraged credit and financing from the financial sector banking to the real sector of the business world, from the demand and supply side.\par \par \uc2 The fourth response is the digitalization of the national financial \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in accordance with President Jokowi"s direction and the last \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  response is developing and building an inclusive and green financial \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "That is our answer to prudence in an effort to ensure the prospects of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery will rise and recover. Synergy and innovation in national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery," he noted.\par \par \uc2 BI"s \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in 2022 is focused on continuing to encourage \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery with synergies among the government, KSSK, and related stakeholders.\par \par \uc2 "The monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is aimed at responding to the increasing global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," he expounded.\par \par \uc2 In addition, BI remains committed to maintaining exchange rate stability and ensuring better liquidity in the banking system.\par \par \uc2 BI has also planned to gradually and cautiously reduce banking liquidity assistance.\par \par \uc2 Thereafter, the low interest rate of 3.5 percent will continue to be maintained until there are signs of an increase in inflation.\par \par \uc2 (T.A063/A/H-FDH/H-FDH) 25-12-2021 18:07:35\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020211225ehcp000jh\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
