\par\par \b \uc2 Dear millennials, let's talk about our scars\b0\par\par\uc2 1,009 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 December 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Dedy Swares Sinaga, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 With the emergence of the Omicron variant, how this pandemic will end is becoming more \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . And so is how our future will unfold. It is true that all living generations are negatively affected by the COVID-19 pandemic. But we, millennials--now in our 20s-30s, are on a sure path to be permanently impacted by the health, social and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crises. Moreover, it is fair to call our cohort "the generation of crises."\par \par \uc2 At least three major international-scale crises have left scars on the trajectory of our lifetime welfare.\par \par \uc2 First, the Asian financial crisis (AFC) ruined our parents' jobs and, naturally, took a physical and psychological toll on child development. Many social programs were also severely cut. These tough circumstances incurred significant costs for many of us in acquiring key skillsets. For instance, when our peer cohorts in other countries were familiarizing themselves with PCs equipped with a smaller floppy disk, many Indonesian millennials, myself included, had never even touched a computer, at least until we were at senior high school or university.\par \par \uc2 The second is the 2007/2008 global financial crisis (GFC). For Indonesia, the shock might not be as colossal as the AFC. But the GFC still left a permanent mark on millennials' lifetime income. Many joined the workforce during this hard time with no work experience, i.e. small chance to be recruited. And even if we were lucky, we had to accept a lower salary and slower increases for some years due to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown. Several studies, like Scwandt (2020), show that graduating during a recession has a significant impact on a person's future midlife health and mortality; recession graduates have a higher chance of acquiring an unhealthy lifestyle due to early job displacements and despair.\par \par \uc2 The third crisis, and probably not the last one, is the ongoing COVID-19 crisis. Those who just entered the labor market in 2020 onward share a similar fate as those entering during the GFC. Some thought we were having steady jobs only to realize our employers could not stay afloat without rationalizing labor costs. Also, some recently promoted to management positions must restart careers and forego many perks we hoped we could hold or even expand in years to come. But again, another crisis hit us; we have no choice but to fight and make every effort to survive.\par \par \uc2 Not only will we shoulder the costs of handling past crises, we might as well be the first now-living generation in Indonesia who cannot rely on a "demographic bonus" in our golden years. Meaning, unlike Baby Boomers and Gen-Xs, millennials cannot expect younger cohorts to ease our collective burden. In light of this fact, pursuant to Government \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  (PP) No. 45/2015, our government has been gradually increasing the retirement age from 56 to 65. Also, more employers are phasing out defined benefit pension plans and offering younger workers a defined contribution version.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, we must prepare for a more challenging future of work due to technological changes. Those traditional, routine and mechanical jobs are fading. Thus, we must embrace technological progress to stay relevant.\par \par \uc2 Please bear in mind: If in your 30s, you still cannot afford to buy a dream house like your parents, it is not because you are lazier than them.\par \par \uc2 Speaking of embracing disruption, there is also an urgency to address climate change. This is not simply because it is a trending topic on our social media timelines. In reality, we might be the last generation who can still enjoy the beauty of Earth before catastrophe strikes. We are on track to embrace the initial impact of global warming foretold by scientists decades ago. Yet, to avoid those ecological disaster scenarios, we need to, and are even compelled to, pay a higher cost of living than our seniors for similar planet quality.\par \par \uc2 We are treading an uneasy path. Hence, please bear in mind: If in your 30s, you still cannot afford to buy a dream house like your parents, it is not because you are lazier than them. No! There are things beyond our control that, collectively, our society must address and solve. Also, please do not compare yourself to our fellow successful tech start-up executives; their story is an exception to us, not a norm. So, it is okay not to be as successful as them. Truth be told, even staying alive is a privilege many of us cannot celebrate.\par \par \uc2 All this, however, should not bring us to the conclusion that since a gloomy future will fall upon us, we should, hence, hold a pessimistic worldview. In fact, despite those understandable reasons to be cynical, Indonesian millennials are still proudly optimistic about the future. For the last five years, the monthly \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Consumer Expectation Survey has shown respondents aged 20-40 are generally more optimistic on future expectations about consumer confidence, income and job availability.\par \par \uc2 Nonetheless, policymakers and employers must recognize that the majority of their workforce are people who have been constantly trying to survive major crises since their childhood. These people might value the present and tangible benefits higher than whatever the future may offer; a challenge to government long-term investment plans and corporate remuneration policies. In addition, millennials also need a non-piecemeal long-term strategy to ameliorate the scars--they might not even realize--from the past crises.\par \par \uc2 So, let us start broader discussions about the past scars and future well-being. We need to openly talk about and tackle the unhealed wounds to prevent massive potential losses to future welfare and to achieve a more equitable Indonesia Maju (Advanced Indonesia) for all generations. Moreover, what kind of battle can a society win if the majority of its workforce have untreated serious wounds? What kind of progress will a society have if the majority of its contributors are unable to reach their full potential?\par \par \uc2 __________________\par \par \uc2 The writer is an economist at \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211226ehcr00005\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
