\par\par \b \uc2 Can \uc2 NFA\uc2  strengthen RI's food system governance?\b0\par\par\uc2 1,073 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 December 2021\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 5\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2021 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Felippa Ann Amanta, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The C0VID-19 pandemic has highlighted the precariousness of Indonesia's food system, which refers to all of the actors, activities and interconnected processes in production, processing, distribution, consumption and disposal of food products as well as the broader \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2 , societal and environmental contexts. Disruption in any part of the system can have a ripple effect on the rest of the system and threaten people's livelihoods and food security.\par \par \uc2 For example, a roadblock restricting mobility in one village can obstruct food distribution, cause delays and food loss, reduce access to food, affect food prices and hurt farmers' incomes.\par \par \uc2 To mitigate the risks of disruption, good governance across the food system is of paramount importance. Yet, major governance gaps still exist in Indonesia's food system. With this backdrop, President Joko "Jokowi" Widodo announced the creation of the National Food Agency (\uc2 NFA\uc2 ). Can the \uc2 NFA\uc2  answer the governance challenges, or will it compound the complexity of the existing governance structures?\par \par \uc2 Given the broad range of activities in the food system, where at least 12 ministries and agencies are explicitly tasked with regulating and governing portions of the system, from the Agriculture Ministry and the Maritime Affairs and Fisheries Ministry to the latest involvement of the Defense Ministry in the food estate program. Not to mention the regional governments, which play a significant role both in \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and implementation, and the \uc2 National Logistics Agency\uc2  (Bulog) and state-owned enterprises that execute government interventions. This division of labor is necessary to achieve the immense task of ensuring food security for all Indonesians. However, it can introduce tensions and trade- offs especially when competing interests arise.\par \par \uc2 The competing interests have resulted in a fragmented and disjointed \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  approach to the food system. For example, the Health Ministry's dietary guidelines popularized through the Isi Piringku (Fill My Plate) campaign promotes diverse consumption of carbohydrates, fruit, vegetables and proteins. However, the Agriculture Ministry prioritizes production of only a few strategic commodities namely rice, maize, soybeans and beef for the sake of self-sufficiency.\par \par \uc2 The latest food estate program headed by the Defense Ministry also focuses specifically on producing cassava. This strategy has created the unintended consequence of limiting the variety of food. Production of other food items, such as fruits and vegetables, have stagnated or even declined. Now, Indonesia is among the countries with the lowest consumption of fruits and vegetables, far below the \uc2 World Health Organization\uc2 's recommended guideline.\par \par \uc2 Another area of contention is the frequent disagreement over import decisions. Food imports are needed to supply raw materials for the food and beverage industry and to stabilize market prices, but they are often met with strong pushback. Import decisions on strategic commodities are therefore carefully considered in a closed coordination meeting between the ministries involved. Yet, even with this coordination mechanism, disagreements such as on timing or quota still emerge.\par \par \uc2 Take these two opposing stories for example: late last year, the industry raised concerns about a potential shortage of sugar because of delayed and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  sugar imports. This month, President Jokowi questioned why garlic imports were arriving during harvest season and suppressing prices for farmers. Evidently, the import process is still plagued with inefficiencies that harm both consumers and producers alike.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 NFA\uc2  was supposedly designed to address the aforementioned coordination issues. Based on Presidential \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 66/2021, the agency is responsible for ensuring availability and price stability, nutrition and food diversification, logistics of procurement and distribution, and food safety for nine strategic commodities. To do so, the \uc2 NFA\uc2  is given the authority to coordinate, set policies, monitor and implement interventions through state-owned enterprises such as Bulog. The functions of the \uc2 NFA\uc2  cut across the functions of the 12 existing ministries and agencies and even take over some decision-making authorities.\par \par \uc2 For example, the \uc2 NFA\uc2  can set import/export policies and decisions that are currently under the Trade Ministry's authority, or price references, which are under the Agriculture Ministry's scope. While centralizing almost all aspects of the food system under one lead coordinating agency may sound promising, there is skepticism whether this new agency can deliver on the insurmountable task. If not planned carefully, the agency may end up being another bureaucratic barrier in an already complex governance structure.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 NFA\uc2 's effectiveness will depend on the leadership, structure and culture of the agency. The development of the \uc2 NFA\uc2  is the right moment for the government to transform our food system governance. The Committee on World Food Security's guideline suggests three principles for effective food governance, that it must be transparent, democratic and accountable. The committee also proposes four general recommendations to improve governance. These recommendations can be adapted for the \uc2 NFA\uc2  as well.\par \par \uc2 First, the \uc2 NFA\uc2  should promote \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  coordination and coherence by integrating the understanding of food systems and nutrition into local and national development. This starts by conducting a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  stocktaking of the regulations across the different ministries, and resolving any regulatory overlaps, contradictions or gaps between the ministries or between national- subnational governments.\par \par \uc2 Second, the \uc2 NFA\uc2  should strengthen multisectoral, multistakeholder and multilevel coordination and action. To do this, the \uc2 NFA\uc2  should not just rely on the ministries and agencies or state-owned enterprises, but should include the wider and deeper participation of the private sector, academics, farmers, fishermen and civil society organizations in \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  dialogues, as well as programmatic action. The \uc2 NFA\uc2  should consider leveraging the private sector for solutions to the food system challenges.\par \par \uc2 Third, the \uc2 NFA\uc2  should include accountability mechanisms and tools for monitoring and evaluation of policies and programs. Proper monitoring and evaluation are necessary to ensure policies and programs are cost-effective in achieving their intended outcomes. In addition, these mechanisms can mitigate the rent-seeking practices that have historically plagued Indonesia's food systems, as evidenced by the numerous corruption cases revolving around food commodities.\par \par \uc2 Last but not least, the \uc2 NFA\uc2  should strengthen the participation and inclusion of indigenous peoples and local communities in the food system. Each region has a unique production, distribution and consumption pattern. Therefore, a top-down approach may not be suitable. Considering local knowledge in informing policies and programs is critical. The development of the \uc2 NFA\uc2  will determine the future of Indonesia's food system; hence, it is imperative that we all make it right.\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par \uc2 Head of research at the Center for Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Studies (CIPS)\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020211226ehcr0000f\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Booster Vaccines Should Be Free for Everybody\b0\par\par\uc2 546 \uc2 words\par \uc2 27 December 2021\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2021. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 PRESIDENT Joko Widodo should reexamine the plan for the Covid-19 booster vaccine program that people will have to pay for. It is not right that the government is allowing private companies to make a profit from this program, even though this only applies to some people. The ministry of health is to begin the third vaccine program in January 2022. This booster vaccine is needed at a time when the B.1.1.529, or Omicron, variant has already arrived in Indonesia. There are two schemes for this program, free booster vaccines and paid jabs.\par \par \uc2 However, free booster vaccines will only be available for the 61.6 million poor people who are National Health Insurance contribution assistance recipients (PBI JKN). Under this scheme, the state will pay for the supply of 92.4 million vaccine doses. Meanwhile the 208.3 million people not in this group will have to pay if they want to receive a booster jab. There is not yet any detailed information about the funds needed to supply booster vaccines to PBI JKN and senior citizens. Neither have there been any calculations about the necessary \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  or budgetary capacity if the government supplies free boosters for everybody.\par \par \uc2 In the midst of this \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government has gone ahead with issuing permits for private importers to import 231.4 million vaccine doses for the paid booster program. These private companies are to be allowed to be the vendors and the organizers of the paid booster program. With a potential consumer base of more than 200 million people, the potential is there for huge profits.\par \par \uc2 The fact that the government is to roll out a paid vaccine scheme involving the private sector has made people suspicious: is it because state funds are limited or is it to allow private companies to make a profit? After all, Finance Minister Sri Mulyani Indrawati has said that there is still funding available to the tune of Rp35 trillion for the supply of vaccines next year.\par \par \uc2 Apart from this, considering the still unvaccinated target population for the \u8216\'20\'18obligatory\u8217\'20\'19 first and second vaccines, which stands at 30 percent, there are still funds available for supplying free boosters. If they are insufficient, the government should reallocate funding from other \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  areas that are not a priority. The endeavor to supply Covid-19 vaccines for everybody is the key to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery.\par \par \uc2 The reasoning that the booster vaccines are not an urgent need is also not relevant. If new mutations of the Covid-19 virus appear with more dangerous characteristics, there is a risk that the first and second vaccine doses will no longer be effective.\par \par \uc2 Some research has backed up this concern. Findings from the University of Hong Kong released last week state that an individual injected with two doses of the Sinovac or \uc2 Pfizer\uc2  vaccine does not have enough antibodies to fight off the Omicron variant. Sinovac, \uc2 AstraZeneca\uc2  and \uc2 Pfizer\uc2  are the vaccines used on the majority of Indonesians.\par \par \uc2 Given these circumstances, the government should realize that booster vaccines are a priority need and a right of all citizens. At a time of this protracted pandemic, vaccines are a \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  commodity that cannot be bought and sold.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2021/12/27/790880/790880_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020211227ehcr00001\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
